INSERT INTO `trail` VALUES (1,'Clark','Colorado','Pearl Lake State Park','2-3608','Go west two miles on U.S. 40 to County Road 129, then turn right. Go north 23 miles to Pearl Lake Road, turn east and drive the final two miles to the park.',40.78992,-106.893955,'Pearls are a gift of nature and Pearl Lake State Park is just that.  Just a few miles off the road, it feels like an escape into the backcountry of Colorado. Nestled in the mountains north of Steamboat Springs, this peaceful park sits in a quiet lakeside setting.  Overlooking Farwell Mountain, visitors camp along the shoreline and on a ridge with amazing views. Hike from the boat ramp to the dam and connect with the Coulton Creek Trail on the Routt National Forest.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(2,'Clifton','Colorado','James M. Robb - Colorado River State Park','2-3618','To Island AcresI-70 to Exit 47, five miles east of Palisade.To FruitaI-70 to Exit 19 at Fruita. South on HWY 340 for 1/2 a mile. Park entrance is on the west side of the highway.To Connected LakesSouthwest portion of Grand Junction; Take Broadway/Hwy 340 to Power Road (near Albertson\'s) and travel Northwest. Continue on Dike Road to the park.To Corn Lake361 32 Road (State Highway 141), south of D Road, North of the Colorado River.To Wildlife AreaOn D Road at 30 1/4 Road.',39.148352,-108.738865,'The Colorado River State Park was renamed James M. Robb - Colorado River State Park in 2005 to honor a visionary.  Mr. Robb was instrumental in creating this &quot;string of pearls,&quot; or five distinct sections, that are this park. There is a wonderful 3 mile long paved hiking trail that heads west from Corn Lake to the Wildlife Area as well as a 1.5 mile paved trail that heads east of the Corn Lake boat ramp. Be sure to check out the .75 mile long trail at Island Acres that follows the Colorado River. Connected Lakes has 4 miles of trails that circle around the lakes on the park, both paved and hard packed. The Fruita section has a .25 mile trail between the Colorado River and Bookcliff Lake and a trail that goes completely around Red Rocks Lake.',11,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(3,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Maxwell Natural Area','2-723','go to the road directly south of hughes stadium and ride west on it to the base of the foothills.  from there ride north directly along the foothills, if you notice yourself going east at all you are going the wrong way, but it is easy to find your way back. continue on the trail as it climbs up the foothill onto a saddle a bit below the highest part of the hill.  once there follow the trail as it curves south (left) up through a grassy meadow.  the trail will eventually turn left and dissapear over the edge on the hill.  the next .25 miles are in every way nice... downhill, rocky, on this trail you will leave some flesh behind.  anyway, after the downhill turn right to run back to town, or turn left back onto the trail you started on.  i suggest going left and looping the trail 6 or 7... hundred times.  i do, have fun. ',40.55633,-105.14103,' The 1.5 mile trail at Maxwell Natural Area is part of the 6.8 mile Foothills Trail which crosses city, county, state and federal lands. The Foothills Trail connects Pineridge, Maxwell and Reservoir Ridge natural areas. Trail markers show you the way. Biking on the Foothills Trail is for the experienced cyclist- the trail is challenging.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(4,'Glenwood Springs','Colorado','Red Mountain Trail','2-1332','exit Glenwood Springs and come in to town.Turn right on 8th street ,come to the next stop and turn right.Come to the next stop and turn left.Go about .25 of a mile and turn right.This is where the road tee\'s.Go about 100YRDS. and then you need to take a left.The road will curve to the left,so take the road another 100YRDDS and your there. parking is to the left.',39.54513,-107.33447,' Red Mountain has a beautiful north face that towers of the town of Glenwood Springs, CO. Red Mountain Trail takes you up the eastern ridge along a private road. The path switchbacks its way up the mountain, making it the easiest and longest route to get up the mountain. On your way up you\'ll be able to catch glimpses of Glenwood Springs below, and once you make it to the top you\'ll be rewarded with outstanding views!',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(5,'Bellvue','Colorado','Lory State Park','2-1752','Take US 287 north to County Road 54G (LaPorte). Go through the town of LaPorte and turn left onto County Road 52E. Turn left again at County Road 23N, go 1.4 miles and take a right on Lodgepole Drive. Drive another 1.6 miles to the park entrance.',40.596333,-105.181524,'Hit the trail at Lory State Park and enjoy mountain biking, hiking and horseback riding amid some fabulous foothills scenery just minutes from Fort Collins and adjacent to Horsetooth Reservoir. From rolling valleys to mountainous hillsides, Lory State Park\'s 20 miles of trails rarely exceed a 12 percent grade. The variety of trails makes the park suitable for short or long hikes, mountain bikes, horseback riders and joggers. Safe drinking water and restroom facilities are not available on the trails. An adequate water supply should be carried and may be obtained near the park entrance.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(6,'Victor','Colorado','Mason','2-8883','Starting from Divide go south on highway 67 toward Cripple Creek.  Turn left on highway 81 toward Victor.  After a few miles you will cross a cattle-guard and on the left will be Gold Camp Road.  Follow Gold Camp Road until you go thru a tunnel.  Shortly after the tunnel FS 376 will be on the left (north).  Follow FS 376 to the Seven Lakes area.  A parking area will be at the end of the road at McReynolds Reservoir.',38.77554,-105.00943,' 5 mile hiking trail located near Victor, Colorado',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(7,'Littleton','Colorado','Two-brands Trail','2-7932','Hildebrand Ranch Park is located south of Deer Creek Canyon Road and west of South Wadsworth Blvd., adjacent to Chatfield State Park. The newly completed trailhead is accessible from Deer Creek Canyon Road approximately 1.3 miles west of Wadsworth Boulevard.  Note that the parking area has a one way traffic flow and that parking is for park visitors only.',39.55234,-105.11034,' Two-brands Trail is a 5 mile hiking trail in Littleton, Colorado.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(8,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Young Gulch','2-946','Take HWY 14 west from Fort Collins up Poudre Canyon.  Go 13 miles from HWY 287 junction, 3 miles past Poudre Park.  Trailhead parking on the left at milemarker 109.',40.6887,-105.34884,' In the spring of 1919, the city of Fort Collins developed a property known as Young\'s Gulch, building a road and planting trees with the aid of the Forest Service. Little evidence of the original road remains, but the trail that resulted is currently known as Young Gulch.The trail meanders up Young Gulch and Prairie Gulch, crossing the stream many times. The climb is very gradual and scenic with shrubs, juniper, ponderosa pine and Douglas fir along the hillside. After passing through a large meadow, the trail ascends for about another mile to end at the edge of private property overlooking the Stove Prairie Road. Please do not trespass.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(9,'Walsenburg','Colorado','Lathrop State Park','2-3625','Three miles west of Walsenburg on U.S. Highway 160',37.602703,-104.832994,'Lathrop State Park is 1,594 acres of recreational enjoyment nestled in the shadow of the Spanish Peaks in Southern Colorado. Lathrop\'s two trails, the Hogback Trail and the Cuerno Verde Trail, offer visitors exceptional views of the Spanish Peaks, Greenhorn Mountain and Pikes Peak. Yucca, prickly pear, cholla and claret cup cacti can be viewed from the trails as well as a variety of wildflowers that bloom from early spring through late autumn. The Hogback Trail is for hikers only. The Cuerno Verde Trail goes around Martin Lake and is open to bicyclists and hikers.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(10,'Lakewood','Colorado','Bear Creek Lake Park','2-124','The easiest way to get there with a bike is to park at the Morrison Exit of C-470 (there is a small lot on the NW corner of Morrison Rd. and C-470). From here you can connect to the bike path that goes under C-470 and immediately you enter Bear Creek Lake park.  Otherwise, you can park inside the park, but there is a fee to do so.',39.65155,-105.17461,' The park features nearly 15 miles of soft-surface (primariliy dirt) trails for users of all abilities. Most trails are open to horses, pedestrians and mountain bikes. The trails in the park are:   Owl Trail: 0.7-mile loop, 0.5-mile extension. Hiker Only. Very nice trail through a riparian area.     Fitness Trail: 1.6 miles. Meanders through prairie ecosystem with workout stations along the route.     Cowen Trail: 1.4 miles. Short grass prairie hike through the former Cowen town site.     Fisherman\'s Trail: 1.3 miles. Scenic trail along the shore of Bear Creek Reservoir, with access to many fishing sites.     Mount Carbon Loop: 6.9 miles. A long loop around the park, featuring the park\'s highest point.     North Park Trail: 2.2 miles. Hilly trail through the short grass prairie on the north side of the park.     Cottonwood Trail: 1.1 miles. A winding trail through the riparian area along Bear Creek.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(11,'Woodland Park','Colorado','Rampart Reservoir','2-269','From Colorado Springs and I-25, take US 24 West to Woodland Park.  Turn right just past McDonald\'s onto Baldwin Rd.  Follow this through the stop signs (at least 3).  Go about 3 miles and turn right onto Loy Creek Rd. at the 3 way intersection.  Continue on this paved road to the four way intersection of dirt roads.  Turn right, following the sign for Eagle Creek (this is Rampart Range Rd.).  Trailhead is approximately 2.5 miles on the left.',38.9778,-105.00907,' This is a beautiful loop trail with plenty of side trails to explore as well. The path takes you through thick forests around the reservoir, where you\'ll get spectacular views of the lake and the surrounding mountains. Please share the path with mountain bikers.  *Currently this area is closed due to damage from wild fires.',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/20110730144106-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(12,'Estes Park','Colorado','Rocky Mountain National Park','2-2924','From Denver and the east, take U.S. 34 from Loveland, CO or U.S. 36 from Boulder through Estes Park, Colorado.Source: National Park Service',40.366269,-105.56119,' Rocky Mountain National Park has 355 miles of hiking trails. They range from flat lakeside strolls to steep mountain peak climbs.  Source: National Park Service',355,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/06/rocky_mountain_national_park4-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(13,'Gunnison','Colorado','CDT CO15: Saguache Park Road to CO Hwy 114 Trailhead','2-3241','While Saguache Park Road is the southernmost point of this section, the most easily-accessible trailhead is off of Hwy 114 on the northern end: lat=38.222917, lon=-106.591417',38.131345,-106.697074,' Section 15 of the CDT travels for 13.5 miles through the high mountains of Colorado from Saguache Park Road to the trailhead at CO Hwy 114.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(14,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Cheyenne','2-839','Enter Palmer Park on Paseo and take the first right after the Mark Reyner stables.  The trail is accessible from the parking lot down the dirt road (South Canyon.)',0,0,' A three-mile loop rated black or difficult.  It\'s got lots of rocky step-ups and drop offs and quite a few short climbs.  Overall it\'s a good hike and quite capable of getting your heart rate up.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/057-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(15,'Mancos','Colorado','Knife Edge Trail','2-3152','Just inside the main park entrance starting and ending at Morefield Campground.',37.304197,-108.425269,' A 2 mile out and back trail with views of the Knife Edge (8290 feet). Starts and ends at the Morefield Campground area. This is a fairly easy hike that skirts around the cliff face and provides stunning views of the Sleeping Ute mountain and Cortez.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(16,'Idaho Springs','Colorado','CDT CO33: Rainbow Road to Rollins Pass','2-3290','CO',39.81124,-105.667737,' Section 33 of the CDT in Colorado runs for 11.3 miles from Rainbow Road to Rollins Pass. Along the way, the trail passes the summit of James Peak, the summit of Heartbeat Peak, and Mount Epworth.',11,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(17,'Loveland','Colorado','Boyd Lake State Park','2-3617','From I-25, take exit 257 and travel West. Continue on Highway 34/East Eisenhower Boulevard to Madison Avenue (appx 3 miles). Turn North on Madison Avenue (right turn) until you reach East 37th Street (appx 1 mile) where you will go east (right turn again). Follow E. 37th Street for about 1/2 mile, it curves north and is renamed County Road 11-C, Boyd Lake State Park is on the East side of this road.',40.433914,-105.045453,'Boyd Lake State Park is a water-sports haven for northern Colorado.  The lake lies at the western-most edge of the plains at the foot of snow-capped Long\'s Peak and the mountains of the Continental Divide. Hikers enjoy the paved and gravel trails beside the beaches, and under the shade of cottonwood trees next to the water\'s edge. Boyd Lake\'s trail is a segment of the City of Loveland\'s recreation trail system.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(18,'Keystone','Colorado','Westridge Loop','2-562','From I-70 head east on HWY 6 towards Keystone. At the stoplight just before Keystone turn right onto Keystone Rd. Turn Immediately left. Cross the Snake river and turn right onto Soda Ridge Rd. After .4 miles turn left onto Keystone Gulch Rd. and park at the gate.',39.59936,-105.97488,' Westridge Loop is a network of trails that forms a loop near Keyston, CO. This trail takes you along the mountainside where you\'ll hike through dense forests and open areas where you you\'ll get stunning views of the area. At one point the trail crosses the Colorado Trail. This is a multi-use trail, so please share the path.',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(19,'Pine','Colorado','Buck Gulch','2-157','Take US 285 West from Denver to Pine Junction.  Turn left onto County Road 126 and go about 6 miles to Pine Valley Ranch entrance on the right.  Follow the road to the end at the trailhead.',39.40722,-105.34639,' Bulch Gulch is a gravely singletrack trail that climbs rather steeply up from the Open Space parking lot and intersects the main Buffalo Creek trail system. This trail passes through an old forest fire burn so there are numerous trees down along the sides of the trail, and a number of old charred trees still standing. Because of the burn there are some great views to be had on this trail!',11,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(20,'Fruita','Colorado','18 Road Trail System','2-3253','See Google Maps location given.',39.310347,-108.705964,' 18 Road is an expansive 40 mile network of singletrack trails in the North Fruita Desert that is exceedingly popular with mountain bikers, but is also open to hikers. Many of the trails wind through the flatter desert surrounding the gravel road. Some climb the steep dirt mounds, and The Edge goes all the way up to the bluffs. It gets very, very hot here during the summer, so be prepared! This is a great place for a winter hike, though!',40,'http://www.tripleblaze.com/./ra-content/images/uploads/2009/04/DSCF0015-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(21,'Clark','Colorado','Steamboat Lake State Park','2-3607','Go west two miles on U.S. 40 to County Road 129 (also called Elk River Road). Turn north and drive 25 miles. The Visitor Center is on the left-hand side of the road. You can\'t miss us!',40.801724,-106.980037,'One of the true jewels of Colorado, Steamboat Lake State Park has something special for everyone.  Whatever your preference, well-deserved relaxation and recreation awaits you. One of the true jewels of Colorado, Steamboat Lake State Park has something special for everyone. Hahn\'s Peak frames the breathtaking scenery of this premier park offering family fishing, camping, picnicking, trail and boating recreational opportunities. There are 5 different hiking trails within this state park, ranging from 1-5 miles.',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(22,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Pineridge Natural Area','2-978','Directions to the Trailheads: Dixon Reservoir TH: From Elizabeth Street in Fort Collins head west till it ends at Overland Trail Road. Turn left (south) on Overland Trail Road. After 1.25 miles, turn right (west) onto County Road 42C (this is the road that goes west towards the foothills, passing just south of Hughes Stadium). Follow the road as it bends left (south) and starts going up the hill. At 0.9 miles, there is a gravel turn off (left) for the Pineridge Natural Area parking area.Horestooth Road TH: In Fort Collins, head west on Horsetooth road till it dead ends at a parking area.Cottonwood Glen Park TH: In Fort Collins, head south on Overland Trail road till it dead ends at a parking area.',40.54977,-105.14389,' A popular foothills natural area where visitors can enjoy city views, foothills terrain, a reservoir and beautiful forest- all close to home. There are seven miles of soft surface including a loop around Dixon Reservoir (1.8 miles). Pineridge is the southern end of the 6.8 mile Foothills Trail. The Foothills Trail connects Pineridge, Maxwell and Reservoir Ridge natural areas. Trail markers show you the way. Biking on the Foothills Trail is for the experienced cyclist- the trail is challenging.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(23,'Montrose','Colorado','Rim Trail of the Black Canyon','2-1702','From Montrose, follow signs for Black Canyon of the Gunnison National Park.  The trail head is located next to the campground, a couple miles inside the park entrance.',38.544677,-107.688981,' Trail is located along the rim of the Black Canyon of the Gunnison.  It follows the rim of the canyon offering spectacular views of the canyon and surrounding area.  The area on the rim is small to large shrubbery with occasional small oaks.  The trail is self guided with a pamphlet and markers with interesting features, including many geolocial features.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/01/black_canyon_trail_16-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(24,'Brighton','Colorado','Barr Lake State Park','2-3613','Take I-76 northeast, exit on Bromley Lane. Go east to Picadilly Road, then south to the park entrance.',39.945465,-104.773426,'There\'s something for every type of outdoors person - from the fishing enthusiast and boater to the naturalist - at Barr Lake State Park, a short drive northeast of the Denver area. An 8.8-mile trail for hikers, horseback riders and bicyclists follows the perimeter of the lake. The trail is currently closed form mile post (MP) 2.5 (the inlet) to MP 6 (the Stone House) for trail work.There are shorter walks to the various boardwalks that extend over the lake. An easy 1.3-mile walk from the Nature Center brings you to the Gazebo Boardwalk, where you can get an excellent view of the eagle\'s nest and the rookery using a spotting scope. The road across the top of the dam (Crest Trail) is open to hikers and bicyclists.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(25,'Cortez','Colorado','Hovenweep National Monument','2-2922','Paved roads lead to the visitor center and Square Tower Group from Cortez, Colorado (County Road G / McElmo Canyon Road), from Highway 191 south of Blanding, Utah, and from Pleasant View, Colorado. All roads into the outlying units are dirt and are not maintained regularly, making them impassable during inclement weather. High-clearance vehicles are recommended for visiting these sites. Source: National Park Service',37.383281,-109.070913,' The trail system at Hovenweep provides visitors excellent views of all the archeological sites. The Square Tower Group features a two mile loop that begins at the visitor center and is a perfect starting point for any visit. Between the visitor center and the first overlook (a distance of roughly 300 yards), the trail is paved and may be traversed by visitors in wheelchairs with assistance. Most visitors spend an hour exploring the area, with the full two-mile loop taking at least 1.5 hours. Visitors may also explore the outlying sites, which include Cajon, Cutthroat Castle, Goodman Point, Holly and Horseshoe/Hackberry. Most areas have very short (a half mile or less one-way) trails which are primitive and lightly maintained. Backpacking is not permitted at Hovenweep. Source: National Park Service',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Hobenweep-NM-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(26,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Jones Downhill','2-331','From Colorado Springs, take W. Cheyenne Blvd. west (access from I-25 via exit 140A [US 25 S] - right onto Ramona, turns into W Cheyenne Blvd.) Go almost to Seven Falls - just before Seven Falls, turn right into North Cheyenne Canyon. Continue into the park, past Helen Hunt Falls until the pavement ends (approx. 2 miles). Park at the parking lot here. Trail starts at the rear of the parking lot towards Gold Camp Rd.',38.79052,-104.9039,' Enjoy this 22 mile loop trail that winds through thick forests, explores old tunnels, and traverses rocky outcroppings. This is the perfect place to get back into nature, and the views from certain sections of this trail are amazing! This trail is a multi-use trail and is popular with mountain bikers, so please share the path and practice trail etiquette.',22,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(27,'Dinosaur','Colorado','Fossil Discovery Trail','2-3341','From HWY 40, heading west from Dinosaur, CO or East from Vernal, UT, turn North on HWY 149 (Quarry Entrance Rd).  Follow road through monument entrance to the temporary visitor center.',40.43788,-109.30632,' Short hike through some of the best views of dinosaur artifacts in the park.  The trail is accessed by bus, which leaves from the temporary visitor center and drops you off at the site of the previous visitor center.  The trails winds down hill through the canyon and back to the temporary visitor center.  Most times there are rangers along the trail to point out some of the more interesting points like exposed dinosaur bones.',1,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/01/fossil_discovery_12-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(28,'Green Mountain Falls','Colorado','Catamount Trail','2-5934','US 24 West from Colorado Springs. From Cascade traffic light, drive 4 miles and take second exit marked Green Mountain Falls, Chipita Park. Take the ramp down on the main street, Ute Pass Ave.',0,0,' Follow one of two trails, marked with blue dots or yellow dots. These trails climb up through a number of switchbacks with 2 overlooks along the way featuring beautiful views of the valley below. The trail crosses through a grassy area called the Garden of Eden and winds along the creek to a point where you can enjoy views of the stunning Pikes Peak.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/04/cdv_photo_007-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(29,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Liberty Cap','2-5821','To reach the eastern trailhead follow Hwy 340 west to Redlands Parkway.  Turn left and follow S. Broadway past Meadows Way.  Turn left at the next road, Wildwood Drive and follow this around to the trailhead.  There should be signs.  The upper entrance to Liberty Cap is located in the Colorado National Monument.',0,0,' From the eastern entrance you\'ll climb 2 miles to the Liberty Cap formation.  The trail is rocky and steep; it is not one for the faint-of-heart! Round trip from the east entrance to the formation is 4 miles.  If you enter from the Monument you\'ll have a longer hike but with less elevation gain/loss.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/04/liberty-cap-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(30,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Trail 401','2-152','From Crested Butte, drive north past Mt. Crested Butte on Gothic Road.  Continue ~7.5 miles then park at the parking lot for Judd Falls.',38.96597,-106.99392,' Trail 401 is a trail of epic grandeur. This trail defines &quot;high-alpine:&quot; the summit tops out at 11,400 feet. Along it\'s entire length, 401 provides epic views of the surrounding mountain peaks, the valley below, and then gorgeous views of the Maroon Bells wilderness from the top. Portions of this trail pass through deep Colorado forests, but most of it runs through high-alpine meadows full of head-tall wildflowers. Hiking Trail 401 is truly unlike any other trail experience!  Note: 401 is also named &quot;Trailriders Trail,&quot; as it is a massively famous mountain bike trail. Just be aware when you head out!',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/maroon-bells-wilderness-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(31,'Lafayette','Colorado','White Rocks Trail','2-1540','From 95th Street (Hover in Longmont), go south to Valmont Road.  Turn west on Valmont, and less than 1 mile there will be a parking lot on the north side of Valmont.',40.04024,-105.14605,' White Rocks Trail is a 7 mile out-and-back trail near Lafayette, CO. This trail is fairly easy and crosses a few hills. The path is pretty dry and dusty, and it traverses a desert-like terrain. This is a multi-use trail, so please share the trail.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(32,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Stratton Open Space','2-266','From I-25, exit at Hwy 24 West.  Go about a mile and turn left onto 21st Street.  Go about 3 miles on 21st to W Cheyenne Blvd.  Turn right.  Go about half a mile and turn right onto Ridgeway Ave.  Stratton Open Space and parking lot is on the right.',38.79517,-104.85853,' There are three trailheads that service the Stratton Open Space: 1) La Veta Way off Cresta Rd; 2) Ridgeway off W. Cheyenne Blvd. and 3) trailhead on north side of road about .3 miles up the road from the main park gate by the Starsmore Discovery Center.  Most of the trails within the Stratton Open Space are easy to moderate in difficulty and offer &quot;loops&quot; that allow users to enjoy the Open Space. Keep in mind that all trails designated as &quot;paths&quot; are for hiking only; equestrians and cyclists may use all of the other loops.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/022-1.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(33,'Firestone','Colorado','St. Vrain State Park','2-3615','Exit I-25 (Exit 240) on Colorado 119 west, then north on County Road 7 until it turns into County Road 24 1/2. Turn right to the park entrance. Please be aware of the speed limits, they are there for your protection as well as our wildlife and are enforced.',40.167946,-104.983794,'Ponds that are home to graceful Egrets, white Pelicans and tall Cormorants, invite vistors to observe and enjoy nature to the fullest.  The Park has great new facillities, with more under construction, such as additional hiking trails and Blue Heron Reservoir opening in the near future. Flat, easy trails make a leisurely stroll around the park a comfortable experience. There are three trails in the park that are named for the pond that each trail encircles. They are Pelican pond, Bald Eagle pond and Coot pond trails. Muskrat Run Trail also is 1 mile in length and encircles Sandpiper Pond.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(34,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Paul Intemann Memorial Trail','2-169','Take US-24 West from I-25.  Turn left onto 21st Street.  At the top of the hill, go right onto Lower Gold Camp Rd.  At the four way stop, go straight.  The parking area is on the right side with a sign saying &quot;Section 16.&quot;  Additional parking below this parking area.',38.82285,-104.89037,' Paul Intemann Memorial Trail is a fun 5 mile out-and-back hike that offers beautiful views of the area. Enjoy the winding singletrack that traverses the hill side and look over the nearby valley. Watch out for bikers and horseback riders!',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/018-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(35,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Foothills','2-47','From the Overland Trail-Rd 42C intersection in Fort Collins, take 42C west towards the south end of CSU Hughes Stadium.  Park on the north side of the road.  The trail is on the right (north) side of the road on then SW side of the stadium, and is a gravel road that quickly turns into singltrack.  On the south side of 42C is a trail into the Pine Ridge Natural Area and Dixon Reservoir.  This trail can also be accessed from  Road 23 that follows the east side of Horsetooth Reservoir.',40.55697,-105.14384,' The Foothills Trail is a 6.8 mile out-and-back earthen trail that travels along the foothills parallel to Horsetooth Reservoir from Dixon Reservoir at Pineridge Natural Area to Reservoir Ridge Natural Area and Michand Lane. This trail is on rugged terrain.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(36,'Glenwood Springs','Colorado','Boy Scout Trail','2-837','The &quot;legal&quot; way to do this trek is to ride up Red Canyon Road on your bike or a shuttle. To do this take Highway 82 South towards Aspen until you get to Buffalo Valley/Beau Jo\'s. Hang a left on Red Canyon Rd and go up almost 2 miles. This route is 2 miles. The preferred route is to take Doc Holliday\'s trail up through a small stretch of private, meeting up with the Boy Scout. To get to Doc\'s take a left on 13th off of Grand/82 and then left on Bennett. The trailhead is well marked. ',39.54737,-107.31869,' The Boy Scout Trail near Glenwood Springs will take you through thick forests, over cattle fields, and along ridges. There are some areas where you can get really good views of the city below.  This trail doesn\'t loop all the way but it does connect to the same road, and it\'s possible to hike back up the road to where your car is. This is a multi-use trail so please use caution.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(37,'Drake','Colorado','Crosier Mountain','2-1944','Moving west on hwy 34 take 43 out of drake. Keep going until you get to the pit on your right side. The trail head is 6 miles after the 34/43 junction.',40.45702,-105.42572,' Nice trail winding through the deep forests of Drake, Colorado. Hike through beautiful meadows, where you\'re likely to see some elk grazing, or head to the summit for some stunning views of the surrounding area. These trails are multi-use so please keep an eye out for mountain bikers and practice trail etiquette.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(38,'Dolores','Colorado','Mancos State Park','2-3622','From MancosTurn north on Highway 184 for 1/4-mile, take County Road 42 east approximately 4 miles to County Road &quot;N&quot;. County Road 42 is paved for approximately 1 mile then it becomes a well maintained gravel road for the remaining 3 miles to County Road &quot;N&quot;. Then take County Road &quot;N&quot; west 1/2-mile to the park entrance.From CortezTake U.S. 160 east from Cortez approximately 19 miles to Mancos. Turn north on Highway 184 and follow directions from Mancos.From DurangoTake U.S. 160 west from Durango 27 miles to Mancos. Turn north on Highway 184 and follow directions from Mancos.From TellurideTake U.S. Hwy 145 from Telluride through Dolores. Turn south on Hwy 184 towards Mancos approximately 18 miles. Before you reach the junction of Hwy 145 and Hwy 160, take County Road 42 east approximately 4 miles to County Road &quot;N&quot;, and then take County Road &quot;N&quot; west 1/2-mile to the park entrance.',37.399886,-108.2695,'Mancos State Park in Southwestern Colorado is a haven for the year-round outdoor enthusiast and traveler. Most trails located in Mancos State Park are single-track and suitable for mountain bike use. Winter conditions can make trails unsuitable for biking. Mancos trails connect to numerous U.S. Forest trails and the Denver-to-Durango Colorado Trail. http://www.coloradotrail.org/.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(39,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Emerald Valley','2-1935','Head out of Colorado Springs on Old Stage Road.  About 6.3 Miles after turning on to Old Stage, look for FS 371 on the left.  Follow it up the hill where there is parking at the high point or go on down the other side--0.4 miles from the start of 371 is a pullout big enough for 2-3 cars or 0.5 miles is a pullout just big enough for one car right next to the trialhead.  Beware if it\'s been raining as FS 371 requires a steep climb back out and there\'s some ruts, so a 2wd may have a rough time of it.  Be sure to take the right trail--from the third pullout, there\'s two trails--ignore the one above the pullout and take the one below--you\'ll know its the right one as there\'s a concrete slab partially concealing a pipeline.',38.72896,-104.90892,' This out-and-back hike is fairly level with some rocky footing in some places. On the trail you\'ll pass some streams and creek crossings as well as a jeep road. Hike into the beautiful aspen groves in this area and just enjoy being outdoors.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(40,'Fruita','Colorado','Zippety Do Dah','2-1938','Book Cliffs area due north of Fruita.',39.31007,-108.70605,' Zippety Do Dah runs through the Book Cliffs area and features 9 miles of beautiful ridge hiking. The trail offers scenic, wide-open views of the surrounding desert country. Try to stay on the trails as there are very steep banks in places that could leave you injured. You can use this as an out-and-back trail or connect to other trails in the network to make it a loop. Please note that this trail is mainly used for mountain biking, and there is a high amount of bike traffic in the area.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(41,'Louisville','Colorado','Coal Creek Trail','2-495','From 287, travel to Louisville.  Turn West on Highway 42/Empire Road (East is Exempla Circle).  Go for about 1.5 miles, and on the North side is the Aquarius Trailhead parking lot (just West of the Louisville Cemetary).  It\'s at the top of the hill.',39.9733,-105.11498,' A highlight of Louisville\'s trail system is the Coal Creek Regional Trail which runs east to west along Coal Creek in the southern part of Louisville. The Coal Creek Regional Trail is a continuous eight-mile, mostly soft-surface trail that currently runs from McCaslin Boulevard in Superior through Louisville to 120th Street in Lafayette. A joint effort between the cities of Louisville, Lafayette, Superior and Boulder County, the trail will eventually tie into the City of Boulder and Town of Erie trail systems as well as link to the Rock Creek Trail system and the City and County of Broomfield. Louisville is fortunate to have direct access to one of Boulder County\'s most well-developed and beautiful regional trail systems.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(42,'Salida','Colorado','Castle Gardens','2-8196','Park at the Living Waters Church or connect to it from the Race Track trail in the Methodist Mountain Trail System.',38.50952,-105.9741,' Castle Gardens is a unique canyon area that features fantastic dirt ridges, drainages, and formations. This trail heads up the canyon, hugging the dirt walls, offering up incredible views of these unique formations. This isn\'t an expansive area; instead, the dirt formations are limited just to this one canyon. This little gem tucked away in the hills surrounding Salida is very special!',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/12/8974_10152965941173447_1866317640716586664_n.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(43,'Salida','Colorado','CDT CO19: Monarch Pass to Hancock Trailhead','2-3244','CO',38.49719,-106.326227,' The CDT runs for 17.7 miles from the Monarch Pass Trailhead on US Hwy 50 to the Hancock Trailhead. Along the way, the trail passes Monarch Mountain Ski Area, several prehistoric walls, the Top of the Divide, Hunt Lake, Boss Lake, Bald Mountain, Taylor Mountain, Mount Aetna, Monumental Peak, Hancock Peak, Mount Chapman, and Pomeroy Mountain.',18,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/09/2014-09-20120048-1.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(44,'Sterling','Colorado','North Sterling State Park','2-3610','From I-76, take exit #125 (Sterling) and turn west on Hwy 6 (eastbound traffic from Denver, turn left off the exit ramp - westbound traffic from Julesburg/Nebraska, turn right the off exit ramp). Follow Hwy 6 west for 2 miles over the bridge into downtown Sterling. The road becomes Chestnut St - continue straight. After 3 blocks, the road jogs left and becomes Platte St. Continue on Platte St for 2 blocks to the four-way stop at N. 3rd Ave. Turn right at the stop sign and go 4 blocks to Broadway. Turn left at the traffic light and go 4 blocks to N. 7th Ave. Turn right onto N. 7th Ave and follow the directions below.',40.765472,-103.26838,'This large, spacious reservoir on the high plains draws locals and tourists alike from May through September and waterfowl hunters during the hunting season.  North Sterling State Park is a gateway to fun and relaxation. Elks Campground is open year-round. Point-to-point, natural surface trails extend over 3 miles from the Inlet Canal southwest along the shoreline to a trailhead on County Road 29. Dogs are required to be on a maximum six foot leash.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(45,'Golden','Colorado','South Table Mountain','2-1621','There are many access points to this trail system, but I haven\'t found any parking lots for the trail. The best access is from I-70 in the Belmar shopping area, Turn off on Denver West Blvd (this is located between Colfax 38th ave.) going north. ThereÃ¢ÂÂs a Marriott hotel on your left at this point. Take your next left at the light (on Denver west pkwy towards NREL) and park in one of the larger parking lots on your left. There\'s also access from the other 2 sides of South Table, behind Applewood golf course and next to Coors Brewing, but I canÃ¢ÂÂt give directions to theses trail heads.',39.75227,-105.21023,' South Table Mountain is an 8 mile loop located right outside of Golden, CO. It\'s the perfect hike for families or if you want to get a quick workout in. The trail takes you up the mountain via switchbacks, and once you\'re at the top you can check out the views from Castle Rock. Here you\'ll find stunning scenery and you\'ll be able to look out over Golden and the surrounding valley. This is a multi-use trail so be sure to share the path!',8,'http://www.tripleblaze.com/./ra-content/images/uploads/2015/03/4194-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(46,'Nederland','Colorado','CDT CO34: Rollins Pass to Monarch Lake','2-3291','CO',39.93446,-105.683122,' Section 34 of the CDT in Colorado runs for 19.4 miles from Rollins Pass to Monarch Lake. Along the way, the trail passes the James Peak Protection Area, Skyscraper Peak, Mount Jasper, Mount Neva, Satanta Peak, Mount Adams, Lonesome Peak, and Monarch Lake.',19,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(47,'Almont','Colorado','CDT CO22: Cottonwood Pass Road to South Clear Creek','2-3247','CO',38.844502,-106.446374,' Section 22 of the CDT in Colorado runs 19.2 miles from Cottonwood Pass Road Trailhead in the south to South Clear Creek Trailhead in the north. Along the way, the trail passes Texas Creek, Clear Creek, West Apostle Mountain, Ice Mountain, North Apostle Mountain, and Huron Peak (elevation 14,003).',19,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(48,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Blue Sky','2-480','Devil\'s Backbone TrailheadFrom Loveland:Take Highway 34 west of Loveland to just past mile marker #88 (2 miles west of the K-Mart). Turn right (north) onto Hidden Valley Drive just east of the old water tank. The trailhead is on your left. Soderberg Trailhead (via Horsetooth Reservoir Inlet Bay)From Loveland:From Highway 34 (Eisenhower) go north on Wilson. Wilson becomes Taft Hill Road in Fort Collins. Turn left (west) onto County Road 38E and continue west to the reservoir.  Continue west on County Road 38E approximately 4 more miles to the entrance at the south end of the Reservoir. The entrance to South Bay (including campground, restaurant, group use area, and swim beach) is at the south end of the reservoir. Watch for signs. To get to Inlet Bay (including Inlet Bay Marina and Inlet Bay Campground) continue west on 38E 1 3/4 miles past the South Bay entrance. Watch for signs and turn right on Shoreline Drive. Follow the directions above to the Horsetooth Reservoir Inlet Bay entrance. Turn right on Shoreline Drive, continuing 1.2 miles to the Soderberg Open Space and trail head on the west side of the road. From Fort Collins:From Harmony and Taft Hill Road turn west onto County Road 38E. Continue west on County Road 38E approximately 4 more miles to the entrance at the south end of the Reservoir.  The entrance to South Bay (including campground, restaurant, group use area, and swim beach) is at the south end of the reservoir. Watch for signs. To get to Inlet Bay (including Inlet Bay Marina and Inlet Bay Campground) continue west on 38E 1 3/4 miles past the South Bay entrance. Watch for signs and turn right on Shoreline Drive. Follow the directions above to the Horsetooth Reservoir Inlet Bay entrance. Turn right on Shoreline Drive, continuing 1.2 miles to the Soderberg Open Space and trail head on the west side of the road.  Coyote Ridge TrailheadFrom Loveland:From Highway 34 (Eisenhower) go north on Wilson for approximately 5.5 miles where the entrance is on the west side of the road. From Fort Collins:From Harmony and Taft Hill Road go south on Taft Hill Road for approximately 4 miles where the entrance is on the west side of the road. (Directions from Larimer County, Parks website: http://www.larimer.org/parks/driving_bluesky.htm)',40.41182,-105.15256,' Blue Sky is a beautiful trail which connects the Horsetooth Mountain Park, Coyote Ridge, and Devil\'s Backbone trail systems. Hike through a desert environment with some meadows and prairies interspersed. This is a great place to go for a quiet, secluded hike. Watch out for rattlesnakes, though! This is a multi-use trail so please practice trail etiquette.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(49,'Boulder','Colorado','Bald Mountain Trail','2-1699','From Boulder Head west on Mapleton.  Once it turns into Sunshine Canyon Drive (County Road 52), go about 4.5 miles until you get to the Bald Mountain Scenic Area on the south side of the road.',40.04761,-105.34131,' A short, scenic hike to the top of Bald Mountain rewards you with a spectacular panorama of the Great Plains and Continental Divide. The perfect place for an afternoon picnic, Bald Mountain is ideal for both family time and contemplative solitude.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/03/cdv_photo_001-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(50,'Cortez','Colorado','Phil\'s World','2-430','Right off of 160W between a shooting range and the Fairgrounds (the drive in is a little hidden, but next door to the shooting range, and practically across the street from the Fairgrounds). This is about 45 minutes from Durango.',37.34843,-108.49922,' Phil\'s World is a 10 mile loop trail located near Cortez, Colorado. Hike this well-maintained and well-marked singletrack through the desert. The trail passes low-lying desert shrubs as well as desert forests.  This is a popular area for mountain bikers so please share the trail.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(51,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','St Mary\'s Falls','2-551','Follow the directions to Buckhorn.  They share the same trailhead and both start by riding up Gold Camp Road.  Follow Gold Camp Road past the entrance to the Buckhorn singletrack.  Go around the left turn and up and over the collapsed tunnel.  Once on top of the collapsed tunnel, the singletrack climbs to the right.',38.79028,-104.90373,' St Mary\'s Falls is a 3.2 mile out-and-back trail that leads along a creek up to the St. Mary\'s Falls. The trail does have an incline, but it\'s not too difficult, and there are plenty of places to stop and cool down in the creek along the way.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(52,'Estes Park','Colorado','Alberta Falls','2-3150','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Go past the Beaver Meadows Visitor Center and turn left onto Bear Lake Road. Follow this road until you come to Glacier Gorge Trailhead on the left hand side.',40.308974,-105.640584,' This is a pretty easy trail accessed from the Glacier Gorge Trailhead with only a 160 ft elevation gain. You\'ll hike for 0.9 miles one way alongside Glacier Creek, through a forest. After crossing several bridges over the creek you\'ll be at the rushing waters of Alberta Falls.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-104-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(53,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Palmer Point Trail','2-320','Palmer Point Trail is located in Palmer Park and can be accessed either at Austin Bluffs and Brenner Dr (park on the street) or at the Paseo entrance to the park, where there is a trailhead with a bathroom and a water fountain.',0,0,' The Palmer Point Trail is rated as a blue (using the park\'s green/blue/black rating system) trail that loops around the north part of the park.  It offers up a decent 4.1 mile hike full of great scenery and potential wildlife viewing (deer, etc.)  It\'s a fairly easy hike-while there are quite a few short climbs, there are also many flat spots.  The trail also has some technical, rocky sections and both rock and wooden step ups/drop offs.  If you\'re hiking counter-clockwise, when you get to the North Canon trailhead off Paseo, you\'ll have to cross the street and hike east on the Grandview Trail for a bit, the Palmer Point Trail will pick up again just south of the Lazy Land Picnic Area entrance after you cross the road.  All in all, it\'s a pretty cool little hike, and easy enough for a novice.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/004-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(54,'Lone Tree','Colorado','Glendale Open Space Trail','2-968','Take I-25 to exit 190, the parking lot and trailhead on the east side of the highway.If you are headed south on I-25, go left on the exit ramp and loop around under the highway.If you are headed north on I-25, just follow the exit into the parking lot.',39.49097,-104.87,' This trail winds through a grassland plain with plenty of low lying shrubs around. Enjoy the stunning view of Pikes Peak and the Colorado Front Range from this easily loop trail. Please share the path as this is a multi-use trail!',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(55,'Pagosa Springs','Colorado','CDT CO04: Wolf Creek Pass to South River Peak','2-3201','CO',37.482825,-106.79985,' The CDT trail runs for 19.5 miles between Wolf Creek Pass on US Hwy. 60 and South River Peak. Along the way the trail passes Mount Hope and traverses many high-alpine ridges and mountain sides.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(56,'Breckenridge','Colorado','Boreas Pass','2-1435','from Main st in Breckenridge, Boreas Pass rd is on the south end of town, I think theres a light at the intersection of Main and Boreas Pass rd.  go east on Boreas Pass rd, not far you\'ll see a parking lot on the right, good place to start.   ',39.47734,-106.04537,' Boreas Pass features is a dirt road that climbs up to an elevation of 11,482 feet, and provides stunning views of Breckenridge below. The trail is about 15 miles long total winds up into the beautiful Rocky Mountains. Beware of bike traffic as well as car traffic, as this is still a used road.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(57,'Pagosa Springs','Colorado','CDT CO02: Blue Lake AP to Elwood Pass Trailhead','2-3199','See google maps location given',37.237929,-106.628779,' The CDT trail runs for 24.4 miles from Blue Lake to the Elwood Pass Trailhead. Along the way it passes several high mountain passes, 13,300 foot Summit Peak, The Unicorn, Montezuma Peak, and Long Trek Mountain.',24,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(58,'Pagosa Springs','Colorado','Brockover Mesa - Canyon Rim Loop','2-1724','Drive west out of Pagosa Springs, Colorado, on US 160 for 4 miles.  Turn north (right) onto North Pagosa Blvd.  Drive 3.7 miles.  Look to your left opposite Mockingbird Place to see the forest entry gate #5.',37.29061,-107.10553,' This scenic trail is a part of the Turkey Springs/Brockover Mesa Mountain. The trail follows the Martinez Canyon Rim and provides beautiful views all along the trail. There are some creek crossings and meadows along this fairly easy trail as well. This is a perfect day hike to see a lot of beautiful views without too much strenuous work. This is a multi-use trail so please practice trail etiquette.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(59,'Highlands Ranch','Colorado','Highlands Ranch Backcountry','2-1093','Take wildcat reserve up to mountain vista highschool and park in the lot that the trail up to the dirt road and climb for 8 minutes and hit the trail',39.52118,-104.96415,' Highlands Ranch Backcountry Wilderness Area has 8,200 acres of conserved open space. Here there are 20 miles of natural surface trails for hikers and mountain bikers to explore. These trails are multi-use so please practice caution.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(60,'Lake George','Colorado','Spinney Mountain State Park','2-3628','Drive 55 miles west on U.S. 24 west over Wilkerson Pass. Turn south on Park County Road 23 and drive 2.8 miles to County Road 59. Turn right and continue another 1.1 miles to the park entrance (where the asphalt ends).',39.004192,-105.629572,'World class Gold Medal trout fishing awaits beneath the waters of Spinney Reservoir. Fishing trails exist along the river both above and below Spinney Reservoir and can be quite scenic. Hiking around the reservoir can also be fun, but be prepared, it is a long hike and only fishing access and game trails actually exist.',0,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(61,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Captain Jack\'s','2-277','From Colorado Springs, take W. Cheyenne Blvd. west (access from I-25 via exit 140A [US 25 S] - right onto Ramona, turns into W Cheyenne Blvd.)  Go almost to Seven Falls - just before Seven Falls, turn right into North Cheyenne Canyon.  Continue into the park, past Helen Hunt Falls until the pavement ends (approx. 2 miles).  Park at the parking lot here.  Trail starts up High Drive.',38.79908,-104.88353,' The trailhead is directly east of Tunnel #1 at the multi-use trail sign. The Captain Jacks Trail system is a multi-use system that allows hikers, bicyclists, equestrians, and motorcycles. For those who are up for a real challenge, the Captain Jacks Trail joins with the Jones Park Trail at the saddle behind Mt. Buckhorn, and the trail continues for another 2.4 miles to Jones Park.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/04/IMG_1019-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(62,'Sedalia','Colorado','Devil\'s Head Stretch','2-938','From I-25, take Hwy-85 west to Sedalia.In the middle of Sedalia, turn south on CR-67 (Jarre Canyon Rd.)Take CR-67 west until you hit Rampart Range Rd. (approx. 9 miles, just past the camp/country store)Turn south on Rampart Range Road.  Drive about one or two miles, and then pick any parking area near the road.Trail runs parallel with Rampart Range Road on the right side.',39.37624,-105.0935,' Devil\'s Head Stretch is a rolling trail within the high mountains of Sedalia. Enjoy cool forested trails that get you out in nature, and stop along the many outlooks to check out the stunning views of the area! The area gets pretty crowded on the weekends, so you\'re best bet is a nice weekday hike. This is a multi-use trail and is very popular with mountain bikers, please beware and practice trail etiquette.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(63,'Grand Junction','Colorado','West Bench Trail','2-969','From Grand Junction head East on I-70.  Turn right on CO 65.  When you arrive at Mesa Lakes, turn right and Park near Sunset lake.',39.05248,-108.095,' The West Bench Trail #501 begins at the information sign and travels southward where it crosses a wooden bridge over Mesa Creek. It intersects a natural road and heads northwest parrelling the road.  When the road ends the trail goes back to a single track and intersects a fenceline.  After passing through a rock slide and crossing a stream bed it enters an open meadow and then into aspen and spruce/fir. It continues on through meadows and spruce/fir forests, crossing a stream several times before ending at the forest boundary information sign.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/05/Picture-5-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(64,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','Hot Springs Trail','2-8685','From downtown Steamboat Springs, take US-40 west about 1.8 miles to Routt County 129, turn right (north) towards Steamboat Lake.  A little past Mad Creek, park in the trailhead lot.  The trail is back south along the left side of the road.  ',40.56367,-106.88526,' 16 mile hiking trail located near Steamboat Springs, Colorado',16,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(65,'Boulder','Colorado','Wapiti Trail','2-8762','From Highway 36, head west on Lefthand Canyon. Take a right on Geer Canyon Road, and this will take you to the trailhead.',40.14935,-105.30026,' 5 mile hiking trail located near Boulder, Colorado',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(66,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Red Rock Canyon','2-303','From Colorado Springs, take Hwy 24 towards Manitou Springs.  Just after the Garden of the Gods turn off, you\'ll see the brown sign for the Red Rock Canyon Open Space.',38.85311,-104.88235,' Red Rock Canyon features about 11 miles of trails through its Open Space. The park is open from dawn until dusk, and can get a little crowded at times. There are dog-friendly hiking trails where owners can take their dogs off the leash.  These trails wind through the scenic canyon and hikers can enjoy stunning rock formations and possibly some wildlife viewing as well!',11,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/05/cdv_photo_001-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(67,'Canon City','Colorado','Lion Canyon Loop','2-748','From Hwy 50 in Canon City, head south on Hwy 115 (9th St) for a little more than a mile. Turn right onto Elm St. and then left shortly thereafter onto Oak Creek Grade Rd (CR Rd 143) and head south out of town for a little over 12 miles to the Oak Creek NF campground. Park at the Lion Canyon trailhead at the rear of the campground.',38.29536,-105.26947,' Lion Canyon Loop is a 15 mile loop trail that takes you through deep forests and highlights gorgeous views of the surrounding mountains. This trail is shared by mountain bikes so please be sure to share the path and practice trail etiquette.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(68,'Gunnison','Colorado','Hartman Rocks','2-399','From Gunnison, go about a mile on US 50 W, turn left onto County Road 38.  Travel about a mile to the Hartman Rocks parking area on the right.',38.5058,-106.94133,' The Hartman Rocks Recreation Area offers a convenient place near Gunnison for a variety of short to medium hikes on its network of both dirt roads and single track trails. It is one of the first areas to melt off in the spring so it may be accessible when other areas are still muddy or snowed in. It is also a good place for a warm up hike to help you acclimate to the altitude before you head up into the higher mountains.  These routes wander through rolling hills of sagebrush interspersed with scenic granite rock formations and Cottonwood groves in some drainages. The area is dominated by an interesting geologic formation called a Ring Dike about 6 miles in diameter. On the western edge of this formation is the Aberdeen Quarry that was worked in the late 1800s to provide high quality granite for the State Capitol building in Denver.',20,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/399-1223989828.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(69,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Gold Camp Road','2-274','From Colorado Springs, take US 24 West towards Manitou Springs.  Turn left onto 21st Street.  Go about 4 miles and turn right onto W Cheyenne Blvd.  Go about 1.5 miles and turn right into Cheyenne Canyon Park.  Follow the road all the way up to the gravel parking lot (about 2-3 miles).  Park here and follow the dirt road that begins at the back of the parking lot (heading up the hill).',38.79039,-104.90355,' This out-and-back trail follows gravel roads from Colorado Springs to Cripple Creek. Part of the trail follows an old railroad grade, and it is open to motor-vehicles so you may see some traffic. You\'ll get to see old tunnels, aspen forests, and beautiful views of the country side.',40,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/274-1221500643.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(70,'Gunnison','Colorado','CDT CO14: Eddiesville Trailhead to Saguache Park Road','2-3237','CO',38.025478,-106.835826,' The CDT runs for 13.6 miles from the Eddiesville Trailhead to the Saguache Park Road. Along the way it passes La Gariita WB and Cochetopa Creek.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(71,'Silverton','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Molas Pass To Bolam Pass Rd.','2-1624','From Durango, take US 550 past Durango Mountain Resort to Molas Pass overlook and parking area. Restrooms available.',37.7373,-107.69748,' This section of the Colorado Trail starts out at US 550, passes through the Little Molas Lake Campground, and begins the ascent. You\'ll climb through an old burn area, which leaves wide open space to see the surrounding views.  The elevation remains well above 10,000 feet for a good long while, and once you finish this section, you\'ll find yourself at Celebration Lake. This area can be more crowded since it\'s accessible by 4WD.',21,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/02/colorado-trail-1.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(72,'Superior','Colorado','High Plains Trail','2-864','Trailhead is located on the North side of Hwy 128 which runs West out of Broomfield.  It actually connects the Coalton Trail to Marshall Mesa/Community Ditch by way of the Greenbelt Plateau Trail.',39.92877,-105.16611,' This is a fairly easy trail that winds through fields full of prairie grass that offer stunning views of the Flatirons, and occasionally highlighting Longs Peak and some of the Indian Peaks. Part of the trail can be a little rocky, but overall it\'s a nice easy hike. This is a multi-use trail so be on the lookout for mountain bikers and make sure to share the trail!',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(73,'Durango','Colorado','Horse Gulch','2-1622','Park at the Horse Gulch Trailhead. Take College to 8th, turn right by Durango Natural Foods. Turn left again on 3rd by Building Specialties. Park and ride up Horse Gulch Road, the rocky doubletrack 0.6 mile. At the major, signed junction turn right at the Meadow.  ',37.26431,-107.87191,' Horse Gulch is a 6 mile loop within the Telegraph Trail System. The trail will take you through wide open meadows that highlight the stunning mountains that surround you. The trail also leads up rocky paths and through scrub &quot;forests.&quot; This trail is multi-use and is popular with mountain bikers, so please share the trail.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/02/IMG_0064-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(74,'Arboles','Colorado','Navajo State Park','2-3623','Take US HWY 160 west from Pagosa Springs for about 17 miles, then turn south onto CO HWY 151 for about 18 miles to Arboles. Turn left again onto County Road 982 and drive 2 miles to the park.',37.008925,-107.408662,'Navajo State Park is Colorado\'s Answer to Lake Powell.  Navajo Reservoir Extends for 20 miles South into New Mexico. Hikers may enjoy several designated trails throughout the park. There are also miles of outstanding areas to hike along the San Juan River. Nature Trail- this 1,008 ft. dirt trail winds along the lake and is not appropriate for biking. Rosa Trail- this 3,460 ft. dirt trail circles Rosa Campground, overlooking the lake and marina. Windsurf Beach Trail- this 6,024 ft gravel trail extends from the Visitor Center, along the old railroad grade which overlooks the lake, to Windsurf Beach primitive campground. Piedra Trail- this 5,063 ft. gravel trail continues from Windsurf Beach primitive campground along the Piedra arm of the lake, and then climbs to views above the river itself. It is the first segment of a trail that will eventually reach all the way to Arboles Point primitive campground at the confluence of the San Juan and Piedra Rivers. Some spots may be somewhat steep for biking. Sambrito Wetlands Trail- this 3,534 ft gravel trail circles part of the Sambrito Wetlands Area of the park. The far end of the loop overlooks the San Juan River Valley and part of the lake in the distance.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(75,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Lunch Loop--Tabeguache','2-621','From HWY 50 in Grand Junction, take CO HWY 340 south across the Colorado River to Monument Road.  Take a left on Monument Rd. and go for 2 miles and the parking lot will be on your left. ',39.04905,-108.60552,' This hike traverses beautiful desert terrain and the path winds through low-lying brush and climbs up scenic bluffs and mesas. With a lack of trees and forests, this trail allows you to view the entire area around, and the desert colors are stunning. This trail is mainly used as a mountain bike trail, so please share the path.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(76,'Cedaredge','Colorado','Crags Crest Trail','2-2040','From Montrose: Drive West on US Highway 50 for 20 miles to Delta.  Bear right onto Colorado Highway 92.  Drive for 4 miles on CO 92 before turning left onto Co 65, following signs for the Grand Mesa.  Continue past Cedaredge and start heading up the Mesa.  At about 54 miles you will reach the Vistor Center on your right.  Park there.',39.04812,-107.93681,' The Crag Crest Trail #711 is a designated National Recreation Trail and is restricted to foot travel except for the first 1.5 miles of trail from the West Trailhead. This section which connects the West Trailhead with the Cottonwood Trailhead is also open to horses. This trail has become popular because it offers many scenic vistas and a unique display of geologic history.  The trail is a 6.64 mile route which connects Island Lake with Eggleston Lake, however, this may be extended to a 10 mile circular hike by returning to the original trailhead on the Crag Crest Lower Loop Trail #711.1. The trail rises steeply to the crest from the East Trailhead, and more gradually from the West Trailhead. Some sections along the top portion of the crest are narrow with drop-offs on both sides. Due to the high elevation of this trail, travel is often hampered by snow drifts until early July.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(77,'Morrison','Colorado','Mathew Winters','2-98','From I-70 and Hertitage road go south .5 miles Parking lot is on the west side of the road.',39.694493,-105.204884,' Matthew Winters is a great starting point for a number of different trails, including Dakota Ridge, Red Rocks, Morrison Slide, and more. The Red Rocks trail runs past some amazing rock outcroppings and the Dakota Ridge trail climbs up and then runs along the Hogback, offering great views of Denver and the Front Range. Red Rocks is a fairly easy hike and Dakota Ridge is more challenging.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(78,'Castle Rock','Colorado','Dawson\'s Butte','2-1965','From Denver/Castle Rock--head south on I-25 to the Plum Creek Exit--go west across the freeway and turn south on the frontage road.  Go 5 miles to Tomah road and go right.  It\'s another 1.5 miles to the Dawson Butte Ranch entrance.  From Colorado Springs/Monument--heat north on I-25 to the Tomah Road Exit.  Go west across the freeway and make an immediate right on the frontage road and go north to Tomah Road.  Take a left.  It\'s another 1.5 miles to the Dawson Butte Ranch entrance.  ',39.2943,-104.91928,' Dawson\'s Butte is a basic loop trail, with plenty of bridal trails running off to the sides. Hike through a mix of dense ponderosa forests and wide open meadows, and the grade is fairly gradual with only a 300 foot elevation change within 5 miles.  This is a multi-use trail so please be aware of mountain bikers and horseback riders, and practice trail etiquette.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(79,'Fruita','Colorado','Edge Loop','2-660','From Grand Junction drive west on I-70 to Fruita Exit #19. From the off ramp travel north 1/10 mile then go right to the roundabout. Continue straight through the roundabout, travel 2 blocks and turn left on Maple Street. Travel 4 miles north on Maple St. (17 1/2 Rd). Turn right at N. 3/10 Rd, .5 mile to 18 Rd. Go north on 18 Rd for 7.5 miles .Park at the upper parking lot',39.31047,-108.7059,' Edge Loop features 32 miles of hiking trails near Fruita, CO. The trail starts at the 18 Roads Bookcliffs Recreation Area and it takes you up into the Bookcliffs.  There are plenty of intersecting trails that can be used to shorten the hike if need be. Please note that this trail is mainly used as a mountain bike trail, and has a lot of bike traffic.',32,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(80,'Breckenridge','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Kenosha To Breckenridge','2-1648','We had a car parked on both ends of this route.  A nice way to do this is to have a couple of friends (or significant others) drop you off at Kenosha Pass you can ride this path 32 miles down into Breckenridge and meet them.  Otherwise, this is a very difficult route to pull off.  Kenosha Pass is about 20 miles west of Bailey on Hwy 285.',39.41287,-105.75872,' This section is an incredibly scenic part of the Colorado Trail. It begins by ascending up to Georgia Pass; the ascent is fairly gradual and since it\'s just above the tree line this hike produces beautiful views! It\'s about 12 miles from Kenosha to the top, and once you get there you\'ll want to break out your camera because the nearly 360 degree views are breathtaking.',33,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(81,'Littleton','Colorado','Deer Creek Canyon Park','2-279','Go west on W Deer Creek Canyon Rd, which intersects Wadsworth just south of C-470 by Chatfield.  Travel 4 miles to Grizzly Dr and turn left.  Parking lot is on the right about 1/2 mile up this steep road.',39.54314,-105.15216,' Deer Creek Canyon Park is defined by its sterling recreation opportunities and golden habitat for wildlife.  Hikers and equestrians have the Meadowlark Homesteader and Golden Eagle Trails all to themselves. On multi-use trails, mountain bikers test their mettle on &quot;The Wall,&quot; a steep section of rocky terrain on Plymouth Creek Trail, and pedal the 2.5-mile Red Mesa Loop. All trail users should be aware of the risk of rattlesnake encounters.  Meadowlark: Hiker only; exposed with great views of parking area, meadows and the south valley; consistent 10 percent grade. Golden Eagle: Hiker only; scenic view at summit; 3-mile hike to reach trailhead. Plymouth Creek: Multi-user trail; lush sections; rocky in spots; steep climb west of Meadowlark junction. Plymouth Mountain: Multi-user trail with scenic views to the east; Steep side slope on north end. Scenic View: Short, multi-user trail with steep section; beautiful 360-degree summit view. Homesteader: Hiker only; forested trail with an average 4 percent grade; trail follows canyon rim on the north side. Red Mesa Loop: Multi-user trail with open view of the canyon and forested section.',12,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/01/DSC_0047-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(82,'Fruita','Colorado','Chutes and Ladders','2-585','From Fruita, take Aspen St. East about 4 blocks to Maple St.  Turn left (North) on Maple.  Go about 3 miles and turn right onto 3/10 Rd.  Go to the T intersection and hang a left.  Take this road about 6-7 miles to the (unmarked) parking lot on the left.  Note: this road becomes a dirt road about 3 miles down.  This trail starts directly across the road from the parking lot (singletrack) and heads down to a dried up lake.  Follow the trail north as it parallels the road.',39.31009,-108.70573,' Chutes and Ladders is mainly a mountain bike trail, but it is open to hikers. It\'s 7 miles in total and covers a beautiful desert area with some great cliff climbing up switchbacks. Enjoy the desert scenery but beware of mountain bike traffic.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/04/DSCF0015-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(83,'Manitou Springs','Colorado','Barr Trail (Pikes Peak)','2-455','Take I-25 to Colorado Springs, go west on Hwy 24 to Manitou Springs. Exit and go through Manitou Springs to Ruxton Rd. (you\'ll see signs going to the cog railway, follow them). Turn left on Ruxton and climb up the hill past the cog train station and turn right up a steep hill to the parking lot.',38.85536,-104.93374,' Barr Trail is the most popular trail to summit the famous Pikes Peak. During the 13 mile ascent you will climb a total of 7,800 feet in elevation. This hike is a very difficult, brutal climb, and should only be attempted by those in a fit physical condition. The trail is well-marked, traveled often, and easy to follow, and it should take you anywhere between 6-10 hours to summit the mountain.  Enjoy the beautiful forests and rock formations on your climb up, and, of course, once you\'ve summited the mountain-top views are sure to take your breath away.',26,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/455-1223933545.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(84,'Grand Lake','Colorado','Adams Falls','2-3157','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Keep heading east and it will turn into Trail Ridge Road. You have to go all the way down past the Kawuneeche Visitor Center. Then you are in the Grand Lake area. Take the next road to the left and follow signs for Adams Falls or East Inlet Trailhead.If you\'re traveling from the west side of the park go to the Grand Lake area just before the Kawuneeche Visitor Center and follow signs for Adams Falls or East Inlet Trailhead.',40.237593,-105.777528,' Located at the East Inlet Trailhead. The trail is only 0.3 miles one way to the falls. There are quite a few steps throughout the trail but I would consider it pretty easy overall. After a short while you will get to a lookout point just above Adams Falls. The sound of the roaring waterfall contrasts the silence of the area. If you walk a little further past the falls you will come to a big grassy area where moose and elk like to hang out.',1,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-185-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(85,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','Mad Creek/Red Dirt Loop','2-1790','Several miles north or Steamboat up 129.  There\'s a large, well marked trailhead at Mad Creek.',40.56733,-106.88674,' Mad Creek/Red Dirt loop is an easy going 6 miles filled with stunning views of the surrounding wilderness area. There are plenty of chances to see a wide variety of wildlife on this trail, and in the wildflower season, this trail comes alive! There is some mountain bike traffic here so be sure to share the trail.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(86,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Columbine','2-170','Take US-24 West from I-25.  Go left onto 21st Street.  Go about 4 miles, turn right at the light onto Cheyenne Blvd.  Take a right into N. Cheyenne Canyon Park, park anywhere near the entrance to the park.  Trail starts at gate at rear of small parking area on left of road.',38.79113,-104.87417,' This trail makes its way up the Canon from behind the Starsmore Discovery Center to the Upper Columbine trailhead near Helen Hunt Falls. The Mid Columbine trailhead is about 1 mile up the road from the main park gate by the Starsmore Discovery Center. The Upper Columbine trailhead is about 350\' east of Helen Hunt Falls. Hikers, cyclists and equestrians can use this trail.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/05/DSCF4065-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(87,'Pinewood Springs','Colorado','Lion Gulch','2-834','From Boulder, take 36 N/W past Lyons, the trailhead is about 20 minutes outside Lyons (roughly), just a small parking lot on the side of the road with a sign/map.',40.30285,-105.38833,' The trail drops abruptly from the trailhead then begins a three mile climb along a stream in Lion Gulch. It provides access to the historic area known as Homestead Meadows where eight homesteads were established between 1889 and 1923. Information boards provide background stories at each location. Hiking to all the homesteads adds another 2.8 miles. See Homestead Meadows Trail. Lion Gulch trailhead accommodates approximately 35 vehicles.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(88,'Ward','Colorado','Sourdough Trail','2-115','From Boulder, head up to Nederland.  Go right(north) on Highway 72 for aboug 7 miles.  Turn left onto County Road 116 (there\'s a sign for the University of Colorado Mountain Research Station).  go about .5 mile to the parking lot on the left, trail starts across the road, this is the south end of the trail.http://maps.google.com/maps?q=nederland,+co&amp;hl=en&amp;ll=40.027549,-105.524712&amp;spn=0.036871,0.06669&amp;hnear=Nederland,+Boulder,+Colorado&amp;t=m&amp;z=14There\'s another trailhead further north, from Ward, head up Brainard Lake Rd, there\'s a large nice new parking area on the right just before you get to the Toll gate.  For this stretch of Sourdough, most of the climbing is done heading North from the South end, and mostly downhill going South.',40.0276,-105.52453,' Sourdough Trail is an awesome singletrack trail that takes you along alpine trails and winds through high elevation forests. Every once in awhile the forests open up and you get to see the stunning views of the surrounding mountains and valleys! This is a multi-use trail so be sure to share the path.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(89,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Horsetooth Mountain Park','2-1593','Horsetooth Mountain ParkTake Harmony west toward the mountain, go throught hte front range hills5 miles on the right, the parking lot is there',40.52303,-105.18162,' The scenic 2,711-acre Horsetooth Mountain Open Space (consisting of Culver, Soderberg, and Hughey Open Spaces) covers elevations from 5,430 to 7,255 feet. Its 29 miles of hiking, biking, and horseback riding trails connect to the Blue Sky Trail and Lory State Park trails. The outstanding Horsetooth Rock is a familiar local landmark visible from the plains. This open space is also known for Horsetooth Falls in the spring, and for tremendous Front Range views. Drinking water is available at the trailhead. Please carry enough for your hike or ride.',29,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/04/6fb-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(90,'Evergreen','Colorado','Elk Meadow','2-189','From Denver, take I-70 to Evergreen Parkway (CO 74) towards the town of Evergreen.  Turn right onto Stagecoach Blvd.  Follow the signs to the parking lot on the right (about a mile).',39.65458,-105.36643,' True to its name, Elk Meadow Park is the most likely place in the Open Space system to view herds of elk. The meadow is prime grazing ground for the largest of Colorado\'s native deer, as well as where mountain bluebirds flit and red-tailed hawks circle the sky hunting for rodents and other prey. Trail experiences are diverse-short jaunts on flat terrain, a rolling trek on Meadow View Trail, the 4.7-mile haul with a 2,100-foot elevation gain from the Stagecoach Boulevard trailhead to 9,708-foot Bergen Peak. This Denver Mountain Parks landmark affords sweeping views of the Continental Divide. The number of switchbacks on this steep, rocky path demand sharing the trail, as always, along with being prepared for wildlife encounters.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/04/886496_10202390249817233_860333937_o48573.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(91,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Grey Rock','2-8625','From Ted\'s Place at Hwy 287 x Hwy 14, drive 9 miles west to a well-marked parking lot on the south side of the road.',0,0,' Moderate accent to the top of a beautiful rock providing a unobstructed view of the Rockies and the Front Range.  Two routes are listed.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(92,'Morrison','Colorado','Mount Falcon Park','2-176','From Denver, take the the Morrison Rd./CO 8 exit from CO 470.  Head west into town (Main Street), take a left to stay on CO 8.  Go about 1.5 miles and turn right onto Forest Ave.  Follow the signs to the parking area for Mount Falcon Park.  ',39.64688,-105.19604,' There are a number of different trail loops at this park, some easier to access than others. Some of the loops further out offer some gorgeous views of the front range and Denver far below. There are shelters and picnic areas at the trailhead as well.',9,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/176-1223988459.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(93,'Como','Colorado','Gold Dust','2-1876','Head NE from Fairplay on 285 for 9 miles and turn left at the sign for Como.  Park anywhere in town and begin the ride.',39.32017,-105.89568,' Gold Dust Trail provides access to Boreas Pass via the old Boreas Pass Wagon Road, which it connects to after crossing FDR 406.  Much of the northern portion of the trail follows an old flume that diverted water from North Tarryall Creek and its tributaries to mining operations located in the upper Tarryall Drainage.  This portion of the trail is excellent for snowshoers and cross country skiers. This trail is open year round, although winter conditions could make travel more difficult. It is a multi-use trail, so please share the path!',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(94,'Palmer Lake','Colorado','Spruce Mountain Trail Upper Loop','2-8703','Take Interstate 25 exit 163 (County Line Road), turn left and drive 2.5 miles to a T intersection. Turn right on Spruce Mountain Road and drive 3.6 miles to a primitive dirt parking lot on the left.',39.17953,-104.85844,' 4 mile hiking trail located near Palmer Lake, Colorado',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(95,'Glen Haven','Colorado','Storm Mountain','2-8841','From Drake: Head northwest on Co Rd 43, continue approx. 0.3 miles to Storm Mt Rd. Turn North on Storm Mt Rd. Continue approx 2.1 miles where you will veer left to stay on Storm Mt Dr. Continue staying left on Storm Mt Dr approx 4.2 miles to trailhead location.',0,0,' Just outside of Drake, the trails leading up to Storm Mountain provide amazing views of the Roosevelt National Forest. Heading north then west from the trailhead provides a challenging climb to the top of Storm Mountain. Heading north then east offers some easier exploring opportunities.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(96,'Sedalia','Colorado','Russell Ridge','2-1994','From I-25 in Castle Rock, take the exit for US 85 to Sedalia/Littleton.  In Sedalia, turn west onto CO 67.  Head into the mountains about 15 miles to the tiny town of Sprucewood.  At the store, turn right onto Pine Junction Rd., trailhead parking is immediately on the right in a gravel area.',39.35149,-105.11899,' This trail leads you all the way up the mountain to Russell Ridge where you can take in views of the surrounding Pike National Forest. The first mile or so is a sand/gravel mix that is hard to navigate, but after that it gets better and the views are definitely worth it! This is a multi-use trail so please share the path.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(97,'Estes Park','Colorado','Bierstadt Lake','2-3147','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Go past the Beaver Meadows Visitor Center and turn left onto Bear Lake Road. Follow this road until you come to Bierstadt Lake Trailhead on the right hand side.',40.320035,-105.625005,' The trail starts out in a forest of aspens. You then pop out at the bottom of a very tall moraine. The trail zig zags up the moraine, ascending 1.4 miles. Views of the mountains are all around. You\'ll then be in a forest again and the lake is straight ahead. There\'s also a trail that goes all the way around the lake and through the trees.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-062-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(98,'Palmer Lake','Colorado','Palmer Lake Reservoir','2-1345','Access the area from I-25 to Monument, 105 to Palmer Lake, left/west on South Valley Rd., left down South Valley Crescent and to the trail head parking.N39 7.123  W104 55.271',39.118454,-104.92067,' The main entrance to the area lies between Sundance and Chautaqua Mountains and is actually the closed east end of Balanced Rock Road (aka FR322).  The road leads to both the Lower and Upper Reservoirs in addition to acting as the base to an extensive trail network.  The west end of the road connects to Rampart Range Road near the Manitou Experimental Forrest.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/05/IMG_2387-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(99,'Estes Park','Colorado','Tundra Communities','2-3155','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Keep heading east and it will turn into Trail Ridge Road. The trailhead is just past the Forest Canyon overlook at Rock Cut. It\'s on the right.If you\'re traveling from the west side of the park just head north on 34 until you get up to Trail Ridge Road. After passing the highest point on the road, the trailhead is on the left.',40.412912,-105.728833,' This trail is located just before hitting the highest point on the road. It\'s a 0.5 mile one way hike up a gentle incline on a paved path. Here you are in the tundra, high above the treeline. It takes the plants in this area a long time to grow so you are urged to stay on the designated path. This is such a rare environment for the United States. Winds can reach up to 100 mph and temperatures are frigid for almost half the year. All you can see from here is frozen tundra. There is a vault toilet accessible at the trailhead.',1,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/400_8888-086-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(100,'Leadville','Colorado','Twin Lakes Loop','2-451','From US-24 turn East on CO-82 (road to Independence Pass / Aspen).  Drive about 6 miles to the tiny town of Twin Lakes .  Parking lot is across the street from the resteraunt/inn (great food!).    There is a road going up the hill, across from the power plant, that takes you up to Lakeview campground, for those that would like to stay and camp in the area.',39.08148,-106.3824,' The breathtaking natural beauty of Colorado\'s largest glacial lakes, reflecting some of the nation\'s highest peaks, makes Twin Lakes one of the world\'s most scenic places. This 12 mile loop trail circles these stunning alpine lakes, and highlights the beautiful scenery the surrounds the area. Enjoy the view of Mt. Elbert, the highest peak in Colorado, from the trail.  This is a multi-use trail, so please share the path.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(101,'Breckenridge','Colorado','CDT CO28: Gold Hill to Georgia Pass','2-3285','CO',39.541317,-106.042347,' The CDT runs for 19.7 miles from Gold Hill Trailhead on Hwy 9 to Georgia Pass. Along the way the trail passes Brewery Hill and Mount Guyot.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(102,'Fraser','Colorado','Tipperary Creek Loop','2-860','From Denver travel west on I-70and take exit 232 onto Highway 40 west.  Pass through Winter Park and into Fraser.  Turn left at the light by the Fraser Valley Center.  This is Elk Creek Road.  Park in the Fraser Valley Center.',39.94357,-105.83275,' Tipperary Creek trail is a 20 mile loop near the city of Fraser, CO. This is a winding singletrack, with some doubletrack and fireroads mixed in, that will you through forests and out into open fields where you can take in the stunning scenery around you. This trail is mainly used for mountain biking, so be careful and make sure you share the path!',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(103,'Walden','Colorado','CDT CO43: North Lake to Wyoming Border','2-3300','CO',40.753855,-106.732266,' The CDT in Colorado runs just under 25 miles from North Lake to the Wyoming Border. Along the way, the trail passes Little Agnes Mountain, Dome Peak, Buck Mountain South, Buck Mountain North, and Black Mountain. To continue reading the trail descriptions to the north, please pick up the trail listings in Wyoming.',25,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(104,'Breckenridge','Colorado','Barney Ford To Moonstone','2-487','From Breckinridge take Boreas pass road up the mountain till you get to baldy road and turn left.  Once on Baldy road turn left on sally barber for couple hundred yards and you will see a pole with small signs on it at the Barney Ford trail head.  Once on the trail make sure you follow the arrow that points to the right.  Take this trail down till you will cross a road and it will turn into the moonstone trail.',39.50152,-106.01635,' Barney Ford To Moonstone actually follows 3 trails: Carter Park, Moonstone, and Barney Ford. Most of the trail follows along an old mine trail with plenty of mine ruins to keep you interested. The hike is a fairly gentle hike that winds through the beautiful forest.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(105,'Louisville','Colorado','East Boulder Trail','2-1110','From 95th Street (Hover in Longmont), go south to Valmont Road. Turn west on Valmont, and less than 1 mile there will be a parking lot on the south side of Valmont.  Or, go south further to Arapahoe,  Turn west on Arapahoe and go about 2 miles to a dirt road with a sign for Teller Farms on the north side.  Turn north and the parking lot just up the road.',40.02153,-105.15871,' Hike on this flat path through open meadows and around a pristine lake. This is an easy trail, perfect for families with children, or great just for stretching the legs. You\'ll encounter joggers and mountain bikers along here, so please practice trail etiquette!',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(106,'Almont','Colorado','CDT CO21: Garden Basin to Cottonwood Pass Road','2-3246','CO',38.751085,-106.434639,' Section 21 of the CDT in Colorado runs 10.3 miles from the Garden Basin Trailhead to the trailhead on Cottonwood Pass Road. Along the way, the trail passes Mount Kreutzer, Chalk Rock Mountain, Sanford Creek, Cow Creek, the headwaters of the Taylor River, Jones Mountain, and Jones Mountain North.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(107,'Denver','Colorado','Indian Creek Loop','2-434','Wadsworth Blvd south of C470 for about 3 miles.  Waterton Rd is on the left, with parking lot located about 100 yards from the intersection.',39.49111,-105.09374,' Hike through lush forests and open fields that look out on the surrounding Front Country. Most of this trail is on natural surfaces, however there is a section that you\'ll be hiking on gravel. This is a fairly difficult trail that winds up the mountain and climbs along the ridgeline. This is a multi-use trail, and a popular mountain bike trail, so please share the path and practice trail etiquette.',29,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(108,'Buena Vista','Colorado','Poplar Gulch','2-8888','This trail can be started either in the ghost town of St. Elmo or from the north off of CR344.',0,0,' From the ghost town of St. Elmo at 10,000 ft., this trail climbs to 12,250ft. at a pass then descends to CR344 leading down to Cottonwood Lake.',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2015/01/2015_01_24_0070_.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(109,'Minturn','Colorado','Meadow Mountain','2-530','Exit I-70 on exit 171 and get on Highway 24 heading towards Minturn.  Enter the Ranger Station on the right side of the road and park in the parking lot.',39.60672,-106.44544,' This trail is an old forest road and climbs gradually through large open meadows, with relics of old cabins and corrals, and some aspen and spruce-fir forest near the top.  The line shack is a small cabin that lies at the end of the trail. The line shack offers a good place for lunch and a vantage point of some views of the Gore Range and Beaver Creek ski area. Evidence of old ski runs shows that this was once an old ski area.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(110,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Hewlett Gulch','2-944','Go north out of Fort Collins on Hwy 287. Take a left at the Poudre Canyon turnoff (Ted\'s Place). From Ted\'s Place, go 10 miles up the canyon. Trail is on north side of the road between mile markers 112 &amp;amp; 111 just after the small town of Poudre Park. There is no designated parking lot, so find a safe place at the side of the road to park. Trail is on other end of a bridge that crosses the river.',40.68919,-105.31024,' The trail leads north following an old road along Gordon Creek past foundations remaining from homesteads established between 1911 and 1925. At the two mile mark there is a fork in the trail. The main trail continues north and winds through a narrow canyon with many stream crossings before heading uphill out of the creek drainage into a meadow.  To the left a steep and un-maintained trail is visible. This non-system route leaves the stream and eventually loops back to connect with the trail. Hewlett Gulch trailhead accommodates approximately 22 vehicles.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(111,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Edna Mae Bennet Nature Trail','2-319','Head for the Paseo entrance to Palmer Park and park at the trailhead right at that entrance (Paseo and Chelton.)  The trail is off to the north of the restrooms.',0,0,' Edna Mae Bennet is a 3/4 mile loop (the city of Colorado Springs says .75 mile, the Palmer Park trail guide says 2.6 miles, but it felt more like 3/4 of a mile when I hiked it) rated advanced, or black by the park\'s green/blue/black rating system.  It\'s got lots of technical steps (both stone and wood) and lots of drop offs and is very rocky.  It\'s also got some beautiful scenery and lots of bunny rabbits and squirrels to check out (that\'s the only wildlife I saw, although I don\'t doubt that there are other species lurking,) and it takes you down into the north canon, away from the roads and picnic areas.  It also intersects with the Templeton Trail if you want to get in more mileage.  All in all, a really cool, albeit short, hike.',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/010-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(112,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Serpent\'s Trail','2-5879','From Grand Junction take Grand Ave/Hwy 340 across the Colorado River and turn left onto Monument Road.  Follow the road as it curves around and continue to the east entrance of the Colorado National Monument.  Shortly after entering the Monument a parking area for &quot;Devil\'s Kitchen&quot; will appear on your left.  Park here.  Serpent\'s Trail begins just across the road from the parking area. Parking is also available on the right, just before this, at the Devil\'s Kitchen picnic area.',0,0,' Serpent\'s trail is a historic trail; it was once used as the main way to access the higher areas of the Monument before Rim Rock Drive was built.  It is an out-and-back trail comprised of over 50 switchbacks.  The views from the trail are outstanding and so is the work that was done to the trail to make it passable.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(113,'Breckenridge','Colorado','Flume Loop','2-1583','Drive to Breckenridge via hwy 9.  Parking lot is just west of Hwy 9 on Valley Brook Rd.  Ride across Hwy 9, up Highlands Drive about a 100 yds and look for the lower Flume trail sign on both sides of the street.  ',39.50083,-106.0455,' There are 3 loop trails that run north to south: the lower, middle, and upper flume. On these trails you\'ll find rocky paths running through thick forests. Every once in a while you\'ll come to a meadow where the forests breaks a little, and you can get beautiful views of the surrounding area. This trail is not that secluded and you can usually see homes from it.  This trail is multi-use so please share the trail with mountain bikers.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(114,'Silverton','Colorado','CDT CO09: Beartown Trailhead to Stony Pass Trailhead','2-3232','See Google Maps location given.',37.712273,-107.517996,' Section 9 of the Continental Divide Trail runs 7.7 miles from the Beartown Trailhead to the Stony Pass Trailhead. 1.4 miles after leaving the Beartown Trailhead the CDT joins up with the Colorado Trail and runs concurrent with it. Along the way, the trail passes Bear Creek, Beartown Bald, and Stony Pass Peak.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(115,'Gunnison','Colorado','CDT CO17: Sargents Mesa to Marshall Pass','2-3243','CO',38.29088,-106.378715,' The CDT runs for 14.5 miles from Sargents Mesa to Marshall Pass. Along the way the trail passes Windy Peak and Headwaters Hill.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(116,'Aspen','Colorado','Smuggler Road','2-2041','If you are coming off Independence Pass going West, turn right on Park Avenue.  Continue down on this road, it turns into Park Circle.  Slide right onto Co Rd 20/Smuggler Mountain Road.  Take a right after a couple hundred feet and you will be at the dirt parking lot at the base of the trail.',39.19179,-106.80816,' Smuggler Road takes you up a quick and easy trail to the the top of Smuggler Mountain. From the top you\'ll be able to take in the beautiful views of the surrounding area. You get all the views with less of the work!',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(117,'Cortez','Colorado','Sand Canyon Trail','2-509','Southwest of Cortez, up McElmo Canyon to signed trailhead, about 15 miles west of Cortez. Spring or autumn best times, but I rode it in mid-summer at sunup. 6000\'',37.3414,-108.81799,' Sand Canyon contains many Ancestral Puebloan archaeological sites. The popular Sand Canyon Trail is 6.5 miles (one-way) from Sand Canyon Pueblo down to the lower trailhead in McElmo Canyon.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(118,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Coyote Ridge','2-1403','From Fort Collins, get onto Taft Hill Rd heading south towards Loveland, once you pass the land fill on your right go another 1.5/2 miles till you see the parking lot on the right hand side.From Loveland, get onto Taft Hill Rd heading North, if you pass the Fort Collins land fill you have gone to far, turn around and follow the directions above.',40.48028,-105.11659,' Coyote ridge is a nice trail that is easy to access from Fort Collins and Loveland. It offers some great views of the front range and the plains and is fairly rocky in spots.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(119,'Manitou Springs','Colorado','Midland Railroad Trail','2-1409','H24 up the pass, past Manitou, u-turn back down the pass at the Waldo Canyon trail head parking lot, pull off into the median about 1/2 mile down.',0,0,' aka Abandoned Train Tunnels The western trail head is difficult to see when coming down the highway, and the median pull off can come up on you quickly so stay in the left lane.  There will be other cars/hikers on this route whenever its nice out, so if watching for them it will be easy to figure out.  The path starts near the guardrail on the other side, so time your dash across the highway carefully especially if you have kids.   The trail is washed out in a handful of spots, but this is still a very kid friendly trek.  There are five open tunnels, only one of which is really long enough to require a flash light.  (Note that the area can also be accessed from the waterfall near the end of Manitou off a social trail, so the numbering of the tunnels in order to describe location is somewhat relative.) There is a sixth tunnel (on the Manitou side) that has a no trespassing sign, but was not blocked.  Easily recognizable as it is the only tunnel with wooden girders, and it appeared to be cut through clay instead of granite like the others.  It also looks long enough to need a light source or bends just enough to obscure the other side.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/05/IMG_2796-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(120,'Winter Park','Colorado','James Peak','2-2048','From Idaho Springs take I-70 west to US 40 over Berthoud Pass to FS 128 take second right after mile marker 234 and park anywhere on the side of the dirt road.',39.86828,-105.74671,' James Peak Trail is an incredibly scenic trail that leads up the mountain providing stunning views. The trail starts out traversing the popular St. Marys Glacier, a permanent ice field at the base of the mountain. Crossing the glacier the trail leads out into an open meadow where you are able to lay your eyes on the beautiful profile of James Peak.  Summit either by switchbacks or a direct, uphill trail, either way you\'ll get to the top and be able to enjoy amazing mountaintop views! Take skis or a snowboard in the winter and enjoy some backcountry skiing as well!',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(121,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Strand Hill','2-77','Take highway 135 for 2 miles south out of town and turn onto Brush Creek Road on the left. Park in one of the parking spots (psuedo-trailheads) and ride your bike down the dirt road until you get to a jeep road on the right. You have to follow that up several climbs and go pretty far until you actually get to Strand Hill Trail. It\'s pretty hard to find if you\'re not a local.',38.86472,-106.91289,' The Strand Hill loop contains some old, steep gravel roads, but if you jump on one of the other nearby trails (Strand Bonus Trail or the Canal Trail) you can access the Strand Hill trail and the top of Strand Hill via singletrack in an out-and-back configuration.  This trail is such a beautiful section of singletrack winding through the deep aspens, definitely worth a hike!',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/18-strand-hill-bonus-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(122,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Colorado Midland Ute Pass','2-1878','Drive on Hwy. 24 west out of Colorado Springs. Exit at the Cave Dwellings signal. Go down the off ramp onto Manitou Ave. Right across the intersection where the road meets Manitou Ave. There is a large dirt lot. Park here. Ride up Manitou Ave. (west) until you see the obvious trail head on the left side of the road. ',38.86798,-104.9257,' Explore 6 130 year old train tunnels along the Colorado Midland Ute. This trail is full of history as the tunnels will show, but make sure you bring a flashlight along. It is recommended that you hike with a partner on this trail instead of alone.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(123,'Winter Park','Colorado','CDT CO32: Berthoud Pass to Rainbow Road','2-3289','CO',39.798271,-105.777336,' Section 32 of the CDT runs for 9.5 miles from Berthoud Pass to Rainbow Road. Along the way, the trail passes Colorado Mines Peak, and the peak of Mount Flora.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(124,'Fruita','Colorado','Flume Canyon','2-5877','Flume Canyon shares a trailhead with Pollock Bench.  From Fruita drive south over the Interstate and turn right onto King\'s View Court across from the rodeo area just after crossing the river.  Follow the road around; it will turn to gravel.  Follow the road past the Devil\'s Canyon turn-off and all the way until you see a &quot;dead end&quot; sign.  On the left you\'ll see the parking area.',0,0,' From the parking area walk straight past the bathroom to find the F1 trail.  After 6/10 of a mile you\'ll come to the start of the loop.  I like to go right and then loop around.  You can combine a part of the Flume trail with the Pollock trail by taking F2 when you come to that junction later on.  A great 5 mile hike, the upper portion is sandy and follows along some rock walls; the lower portion cuts through a damp wash before climbing back onto some rocky areas.  Gorgeous scenery!',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(125,'Durango','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Junction Creek','2-2097','Driving north through Durango, turn left (west) onto 25th Street.  This becomes Junction Street and then becomes Junction Creek Road.  The mileage and map for this route begins at the second (smaller) trailhead where the road switches back and starts to climb.  This allows you to avoid some of the families and dog-walkers that use the lower section of the trail.',37.33642,-107.91891,' This route is the southwestern terminus of the famous Colorado Trail. It\'s a great out-and-back from the Junction Creek Trailhead, or keep going and you can backpack for days. This well-maintained, and at times popular, trail will keep you climbing for 9 miles up the mountain until you reach a high point. Enjoy the views from up there because you\'ll have earned them!',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(126,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Palmer Trail / Section 16','2-192','From I-25, take US 24 West to 21st St.  Turn left onto 21st street, then right onto Lower Gold Camp Road.  At the four way stop, turn left onto Bear Creek Road.  Park on the side of the road at the end of Bear Creek Road or the parking lot at the ranger station at the end of High Drive.',38.82285,-104.89037,' Palmer Trail/Section 16 is a scenic but popular hike that traverses the foothills near Colorado Springs. The path winds through old growth forest, skirts along pristine creeks, and provides stunning views of the nearby mountains. Just because this trail is popular, don\'t let that deter you from this awesome hike! Mountain bikers are also allowed on this trail, so please share the path!',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(127,'Telluride','Colorado','River Trail','2-788','From town, head down to the gondola and the river, the trail is right beside the river. Head west on the trail.',0,0,' An easy, fairly flat hike that starts and ends right in town. The trail follows the river and is fairly wide most of the way around.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/04/IMG_0918-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(128,'Vail','Colorado','Son Of Middle Creek','2-1823','Take I-70 to Vail heading west, get off at the second Vail exit.  Take your second turn off the roundabout on the frontage road.  Take the frontage road to red sandstone road and follow the road to the first large pullout in front of you.',39.64821,-106.39609,' Son Of Middle Creek is a 10 mile loop trail that offers beautiful views. Hike through scenic aspen forests and then enjoy the scenery as the tree cover opens up and showcases the beautiful surroundings.  This is a multi-use trail so be sure to share the path.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(129,'Westminster','Colorado','Colorado Hills','2-1204','Church Ranch Road west to Simms, head north on Simms to 105th.   Trailhead is on left at 105th and Simms.',39.88815,-105.12908,' Walk this trail through the Westminister\'s Colorado Hills Open Space and you\'ll find yourself at a scenic 11-acre pond. Although this trail is near to the city, it feels like it\'s completely secluded.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(130,'Del Norte','Colorado','CDT CO08: Twin Lakes to Beartown Trailhead','2-3215','Google Maps location given is for Twin Lakes, but it if you are just going to hike this section, it is easiest to park at Beartown Trailhead on the northern end: lat=37.712333, lon=-107.518005',37.64727,-107.458476,' The Continental Divide Trail measures 10 miles in length between Twin Lakes and the Beartown Trailhead. Along the way the trail passes Hunchback Mountain, Hunchback Pass, White Dome, Vallecito Lake, Ute Creek, and Nebo Creek.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(131,'Grand Junction','Colorado','The Ribbon','2-1356','From Grand Junction, travel west on Grand Avenue, which turns into Broadway.  Cross over two bridges, at the next stop light, turn left on to Monument Road.  Turn left just before you cross the ditch on to D Rd.  Travel approximately 1 mile to where D Rd ends, go right on to Little Park Rd.  Travel approximately  2.5 miles to the Little Park Road Staging Area (First Flats) on the left, park here. ',39.017,-108.61005,' The Ribbon Trailhead provides access to the top end of the Ribbon Trail which snakes its way down massive slickrock slabs, past towering Ponderosa pines, and along a narrow ribbon of slickrock sloping toward the canyons below. Sweeping vistas of the Grand Mesa, Grand Valley, and Little Bookcliffs are another highlight of this trail. This is an out-and-back trail, so in total you\'ll be hiking about 8 miles.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(132,'Salida','Colorado','Little Rainbow','2-1736','Approaching Salida from the East on Highway 50, look for the left turn onto the not-so-well marked Burmac Road.  If you see an old garage with a Big O Tires sign out front, you just passed it.  Double back and take the first right then grab the first left that quickly dumps into a parking area.  Park here.',38.51292,-105.98054,' Hike along the base of Methodist Mountain on this well-maintained trail. The trail will take you through valleys of low-lying shrubs and then up the mountain for beautiful views of the surrounding area.  This trail is designed specifically for mountain bikers so be aware that there will be bike traffic here. Please share the path and practice trail etiquette.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(133,'Palmer Lake','Colorado','Kipp\'s Loop','2-94','Exit 163 (County Line Road) on I-25. Go west 2 miles to Greenland Open Space parking lot, on the right (about .25 miles NE of town of Palmer Lake)',0,0,' Kipp\'s Loop takes you on an 8 mile trail that wanders through wide open prairie grass fields, and along ponderosa forests. It\'s fairly flat and easy, but it offers beautiful views of the Front Country and the Rampart Range.  Keep an eye out for mountain bikers and joggers, and be sure to share the path.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(134,'Durango ','Colorado','Animas City','2-2364','From 32nd turn West and go dowm two or three blocks until the road dead ends turn right and follow the road until pavement ends. From there it\'s pretty obvious where the trail is.',37.30289,-107.87275,' Animas City Trail climbs 1,500 feet in just 3 miles, making it a difficult trail, but great for a serious workout. The trail is well-maintained and leads you up to beautiful views of downtown Durango. Check out views of the Animas Valley and Turtle Lake as well on this scenic loop trail.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(135,'Estes Park','Colorado','Trail around Bierstadt Lake','2-3148','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Go past the Beaver Meadows Visitor Center and turn left onto Bear Lake Road. Follow this road until you come to Bierstadt Lake Trailhead on the left hand side.After hiking 1.6 miles up this trail you will be at Bierstadt Lake. This is where the trail around the lake starts.',40.324746,-105.621229,' Trail goes through a forest of aspen trees around Bierstadt Lake.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(136,'Big Thomson River Valley','Colorado','Round Mountain Summit Trail','2-8590','From I-25 take the Loveland/Estes Park exit.  Turn left on hwy 34 west (Eisenhower) and continue through the Big Thomson Canyon.  After passing The Dam Store, continue an additional 4 miles and the trail head parking lot will be on your left.  It is not well marked, all that is on the main road is a brown sign wih an arrow that says &quot;parking&quot;.  If you hit the fork at drake, you went way too far.',40.4187,-105.28674,' Moderate to difficult hike mainly due to the uphill nature and the length.  This trail has some of the best viewpoints in the area.  It\'s variety of terrain keeps interesting the entire way.  There are a few camp spots.  One located approx. 2 miles up the trail.  The other couple are located at the top, 4.75miles.  Watch out for the afternoon thunderstorms that go hand in hand with the local climate during the peak seasons.',9,'http://www.tripleblaze.com/./ra-content/images/uploads/2014/09/cdv_photo_002-4.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(137,'Leadville','Colorado','CDT CO24: Halfmoon Creek to Timberline Lake','2-3249','CO',39.151655,-106.419415,' Section 24 of the CDT runs 13 miles from Halfmoon Creek to Timberline Lake. Along the way, the trail passes North Willow Creek, Rock Creek, Hagerman Road, Busk Creek, Mount Massive (elevation 14,421), the Mount Massive Wilderness Area, County Road 4, and Turquoise Lake.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(138,'Gunnison','Colorado','Black Canyon National Forest','2-2915','Black Canyon of the Gunnison National Park is located approximately 250 miles southwest of Denver.South Rim: 15 miles east of Montrose, via U.S. Highway 50 and CO Highway 347North Rim: 11 miles south of Crawford, via CO Highway 92 and North Rim Road (unpaved)There is no bridge between the north and south rims of the canyon. Allow two to three hours to drive from one side to the other.Source: National Park Service',38.554333,-107.686231,' 20 miles of trails  exist with in park. Many trails pass by steep dropoffs, so be cautious and keep a close watch on children.There are no maintained or marked trails into the inner canyon. Routes are difficult to follow, and only individuals in excellent physical condition should attempt these hikes. Source: National Park Service',20,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Black-Canyon-of-the-Gunnison-Nationa-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(139,'Grand Lake','Colorado','CDT CO37: Bowen Gulch to Willow Creek Pass','2-3294','CO',40.328265,-105.856552,' The CDT runs for 19.7 miles from Bownen Gulch to Willow Creek Pass on Hwy 125. Along the way the trail passes the Colorado River, Bowen Creek, Ruby Mountain, Cascade Mountain, and Radial Mountain.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(140,'Eldorado Springs','Colorado','Spring Brook Loop','2-7831','From Highway 93, take Highway 170 west about 1.8 miles, then turn left into the Doudy Draw trailhead.',39.93827,-105.25663,' Spring Brook Loop is a 5 mile hiking trail in Eldorado Springs, Colorado.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(141,'Monument','Colorado','Mount Herman Trail','2-271','from northbound I-25 Take the monument exit, turn left at the first light right at the second, left at 7-11 travle all the way down that road until you come to the RR crossing. go across the tracks and turn left then turn right at mt. herman road.  [Added 6/9/02 by webmaster]: Take exit #161 off I-25.  Head west and take the second left, Third Street.  Follow this as it curves around and becomes Front Street.  Turn right at the stop sign onto Second St.  After crossing the railroad tracks, turn left onto Mitchell St.  Mt. Herman Rd. will be about a half mile on the right.  Go about a mile or so and turn into the signed parking lot on the left.  The trail starts here and heads west.',39.08291,-104.88663,' Mount Herman Trail offers a wide range of trails that take you through aspen forests, along creek beds, up to the summit, or out in wide open fields.',9,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/10/mt_herman-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(142,'Salida','Colorado','CDT CO18: Marshall Pass to Monarch Pass (Monarch Crest Trail)','2-404','From Salida, head west on US 50 to Poncha Springs.  Head south on 285 for less than a quarter of a mile and park one vehicle at the gas station/shuttle parking area (they charge $5 per vehicle).  Now head up US 50 west to the top of Monarch Pass and park in the parking area on the left.  The trail starts up the dirt road.',38.49598,-106.3255,' Monarch Crest is an epic alpine trail that spends a significant amount of time above tree line. It offers gorgeous views of the surrounding mountains which are lush with vegetation: a distinct change from the front range of Colorado. This trail is quite popular with backpackers and mountain bikers, but it is great for a short day hike as well. CDT Description: Section 18 of the CDT in Colorado runs 10.7 miles from Marshall Pass to Monarch Pass and US Hwy 50. Along the way the trail passes Mount Ouray, Pahlone Peak, Mount Peck, and Monarch Ridge. The trailhead listed is for the northern end of this section. The southern end is located at lat= 38.39166 lon= -106.24696',11,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/09/10688453_10152477764162599_5464611316626622482_o.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(143,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Red Mountain Open Space','2-977','Take State Hwy 1/Terry Lake Rd to CR15 (aka the Waverly turn off) - go north (left) on CR15, turn west (left) on CR78, turn north (right) on CR17, turn west (left) on CR80, turn north (right) on CR19 (pass gravel pit on left), turn left on CR21. Go over several cattle guards, traveling about 7 miles on CR21 which will end at the trailhead parking area.',40.95823,-105.16325,' Deep crimson and tan rocks, rolling grasslands, and sandy washes await you at Red Mountain Open Space, an almost 15,000-acre open space in northeastern Colorado. From the trailhead, hikers, bikers, and horseback riders can take off on over 15 miles of multi-use trails.  Then, they can access the trails in two adjacent protected areas that are part of a much larger vision - the Laramie Foothills Mountains to Plains Project - which protects over 55,000 acres of ecologically and culturally diverse landscape.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(144,'Idaho Springs ','Colorado','Warren Gulch','2-2212','Take I-70 west of Denver to  Idaho Springs ',39.67537,-105.53201,' Warren Gulch is a high altitude trail located right outside of Idaho Springs. The trail is made of rocky singletrack that makes its way up the mountain with switchbacks. All the climbing will be worth it when you break out of the heavy forest and enjoy the stunning views! This is a multi-use trail, so please share the path.',17,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(145,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Dyke','2-1612','From Crested Butte, go west for 12 miles on Kebler Pass Road (country road 12).  You can park at various places.  Typically you would choose either trailhead (the Lake Irwin or Horse Ranch Park) or the top of Kebler Pass.',38.88111,-107.11532,' This is a gorgeous, high-altitude trail that offers up amazing views of the nearby mountain peaks. Also, this trail goes through the Kebler Pass aspen grove, one of the largest aspen groves &amp; largest living organisms on the planet! Hiking this trail is worth it just for the aspens!',15,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/aspens-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(146,'Jamestown','Colorado','Ceran Saint Vrain Loop','2-902','From Intersection of Broadway and Canyon in Boulder, go 3.4 miles north on Broadway to Lee Hill Road.  Take Lee Hill Road to Old Stage Road and go 4 miles to Lefthand Canyon Road, go left 2 miles to County Road 94 to Jamestown, go 4.7 miles to the enterance for Ceran Saint Vrain, turn right into the trailhead parking lot.  (Information provided by &quot;Mountain Biking Denver and Boulder&quot;)  a Simpler way would be to go north(or west as the book says) on Highway 36, there will be a sign for Jamestown where you will take a left, continue untill you reach the Ceran Saint Vrain parking lot enterance on the right, don\'t drive to fast or you\'ll fly right past it as I have a few times:o)',40.12361,-105.44354,' The Ceran Saint Vrain Trail is an easy trail that gradually loses elevation as it follows the South Saint Vrain Creek downstream for 1.9 miles. The trail ends at National Forest System Road 252, a rough four-wheel drive road. This road climbs 0.5 miles northwest to a four-way intersection from which it is a steep half-mile to the left up to Miller Rock. Miller Rock is a scenic high-point that offers 360-degree views.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/11/photo_021-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(147,'Durango','Colorado','Overend Mountain Park','2-7942','There are a variety of trailheads accessing this network of trails.  To get you acquainted with the northern sector, suggest turning west on 22nd Street off Camino del Rio (Hwy 550) and driving to the end of Montview or jogging a block to the right and park at the end of Crestview.',37.28766,-107.88622,' Overend Mountain Park is a 5 mile hiking trail in Durango, Colorado.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(148,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Reservoir Ridge','2-7997','From Fort Collins, head north on Overland Trail.  From Laporte, head south on Overland Trail.  Overland Trail makes a series of turns, Michaud Lane is in the elbow of the 90 degree turn.  Head down Michaud Lane to the end, this puts you right into the parking lot for Reservoir Ridge Natural Area next to Claymore Lake.',40.61131,-105.15311,' Reservoir Ridge is a 3 mile hiking trail in Fort Collins, Colorado.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(149,'Vail','Colorado','Buffehr Creek The North Vail Trail To Davos Towers','2-1824','Heading West on US I-70 in Vail Colorado head east on the northern frontage road to Buffehr Creek Road.  Turn left heading north for two tenths of a mile to the North Vail Trail Buffehr Creek parking area.  Parking is from 7 AM to 11 PM, and only three hours (as of 060110, new rules) with no overnight parking.  Hiking trip on this route takes 3 hours, biking takes about 1.5 depending on your skills.',39.63702,-106.41537,' This trail starts out flat, but once you hit the switchbacks you\'ve got about 1,800 feet of climbing to do. Follow the trail through the forest, and come out on top to enjoy the views of Edwards, Avon, Minturn, Meadow Mountain and Vail. All of that hard climbing is totally worth it!',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(150,'Hermosa','Colorado','Durango Mountain Resort (purgatory)','2-7904','From Durango, take US 550 north about 30 miles to Durango Mountain Resort, located on the left side of the highway.',37.62925,-107.83184,' Durango Mountain Resort (purgatory) is a 40 mile hiking trail in Hermosa, Colorado.',40,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(151,'Creede','Colorado','Ute Creek Trail (Loop)','2-8857','From Creede take Hwy 149 towards Lake City and turn left onto FS road 520.  Follow the signs about 10 miles to Thirty Mile Campground and continue to the other side of the reservoir.  You\'ll see a bathroom, parking area and sign on the left. Park here and begin.',0,0,' After a quick ford of the river you can hike as far as you want.  The loop we do involves the Ute Creek, CDT and West Ute Lake trails.',25,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2015/01/CDTtoWestUteLake.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(152,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','Buffalo Pass To Mountain View Trail','2-1693','From Steamboat, take 6th St. north, make a right on Missouri Ave. then a left on N. Park Ave.  Take this north until it turns into Routt Co. 38.  About 2 miles north you will hit a FR 60 on the right and a sign which points to Buffalo Pass.  It is about 13 miles up to the pass.',40.54419,-106.68481,' Buffalo Pass To Mountain View Trail passes through beautiful meadows along ridgelines that provide incredibly scenic views of the surrounding area. This well-marked trail winds through forests and skirts around lakes, and makes for a seriously beautiful hike. This section of the trail is multi-use so please practice trail etiquette.',28,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(153,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','Emerald Mountain','2-7953','Take 5th street heading south/west from downtown and cross the river. Several parking areas near the ski area.',40.48201,-106.83521,' Emerald Mountain is a 40 mile hiking trail in Steamboat Springs, Colorado.',40,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(154,'Grant','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Kenosha Pass To Lost Creek Wilderness Bound','2-1433','Going South on 285 from Bailey, hang a left at the Colorado trail parking lot on Kenosha pass (not right, but left as you\\\'re going south.)',39.41296,-105.75798,' This section of trail is 6.5 miles one-way and is 13 miles round trip if you hike it as an out-and-back. At first it passes through a few beautiful aspen groves, and then the singletrack pops out into an open alpine field with some spectacular views of the South Park Valley. This is definitely a must-hike trail!',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(155,'Manitou Springs','Colorado','Williams Canyon','2-2035','Head west on Manitou Avenue until you can make a right on Canyon Avenue.  Follow Canyon Avenue (it will bear right after a couple block) until you come to the underpass under Highway 24 and look for a place to park.  IMPORTANT NOTE:  this trail crosses private property owned by the Cave of the Winds and you can only legally access it if you turn in a waiver at the ticket desk there.  Be sure to do that before you head for the trail.  Waiver available at http://www.inclineclub.com/caveofthewinds.pdf',38.86404,-104.91731,' Williams Canyon is a 5 mile out-and-back trail that winds through the canyon and brings you to a beautiful waterfall. The hike passes by deep caves, fields of wildflowers, an old stone house, and some zip lines as well. Enjoy the beautiful canyon scenery as you explore this trail!',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(156,'Littleton','Colorado','Ken Caryl Valley','2-1881','West of Denver in the foothills near the Ken Caryl Valley Housing area.  Drive west of Denver on C470.  Exit on Ken Caryl Drive and drive into the valley.  Park just west of the first stoplight and start on the trail head for Kathy Johnson trail.',39.57567,-105.14829,' Head out to the Ken Caryl Ranch and enjoy over 20 miles of trail in the 4,800-acres of foothills open space. There are 10 trails here ranging from easy to difficult, with the longest trail topping out at 3.8 miles. All of these trails but one are private trails, only open to residents. The Cathy Johnson Trail and South Hogback Open Space is the only trail that\'s open to the public. It\'s a 2.1 mile trail that ranges from easy to moderate along the trail.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(157,'Allenspark','Colorado','Sandbeach Lake','2-3353','Located between the towns of Meeker and Allenspark on Colorado route 7 (Peak to Peak Scenic Highway). Watch for signs.',0,0,' This is a tough 2,000 foot elevation gain on a rocky mountain path. Be prepared to spend a day hiking out and back. Along the way you\'ll hike through dense forests, skirt a beautiful alpine lake, and enjoy the views of the surrounding area.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-287-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(158,'Kremmling','Colorado','CDT CO40: FR104 to Rabbit Ears Pass','2-3297','CO',40.342118,-106.338095,' The CDT runs just under 30 miles from Forest Road 104 to US Hwy 40. Along the way, the trail passes Little Haystack Mountain, Dennis Hump, North Ryder Peak, Ironclad Mountain, Hwy 14, Mexican Ridge South, Diamond Mountain, US Hwy 40, and Baker Mountain.',30,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(159,'Ridgway','Colorado','Wetterhorn Basin / West Fork of the Cimmaron','2-8856','To get here from Grand Junction, Colorado, drive south towards Ridgway and turn left onto the Owl Creek Pass road. Just past Owl Creek Pass, turn right onto the West Fork road. Drive as far as you can. If you have a truck, or even a higher clearance Subaru, you will be able to make it almost all the way down the gravel road. Hike across the creek and into the West Fork Basin. Where the trail becomes indistinct look for cairns and head up towards an obvious pass area. Be prepared for a very loose, exposed section of scree and talus. It\'s fairly intimidating and scary for about 3 minutes. Head up and over West Fork Pass; follow the signs on the way down for Wetterhorn Basin. Just after crossing the creek and heading up the opposite bank, where the trail seems to disappear, is your campsite. The trail actually continues to the left, through the meadow towards Wetterhorn Pass. Look for posts and cairns along the way.',0,0,' Beautiful and mostly remote hike with only one technical section. Best to have trekking poles and a camera!',12,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2015/01/2014-08-16104720.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(160,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','West Monument Creek Trail #713','2-763','Enter the Air Force Academy at the south gate. Turn left on Pine Drive, then left on W. Monument Creek Drive. Trailhead parking at the end of the road on the right.',38.972572,-104.901259,' Loop hike that takes you past the Tesla Plant and up a steep canyon until finally dropped back via Stanley Canyon trail. The 713 trail is rarely crowded - in fact each time I\'ve hiked past the Tesla plant I\'ve seen no one.',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/03/DSCF0010-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(161,'Colorado Springs - Air Force Academy','Colorado','Goat Camp Creek','2-1375','Head for the visitors center on the Academy.  Across from the entrance is a dirt road, stay right, that will lead you to a parking lot.  The trail head is just up the jeep trail.  N39 00.422 x W104 54.257',0,0,' Goat Camp Creek to Eagle Peak is a tough ascent.  The short distance is all up with only a short reprieve in the saddle.  Consistent traffic on the trail keeps the path cut all year long but the ice will try to deter you.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/04/2-13-10-006-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(162,'Fruita','Colorado','Moore Fun','2-1660','From I -70 take Loma exit 15 go south to frontage rd. to Kokopelli Trail parking area.',39.19711,-108.85863,' This out-and-back trail is part of the Kokopelli Trail system, which means you can link it up with other trails to make it longer, or to use it as a loop. Most of the hike is spent climbing a rocky line with plenty of ledges. Look around because the views along this trail are stunning.  This trail is very popular with mountain bikers, as is this whole area, so please practice trail etiquette and share the trail.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(163,'Golden','Colorado','White Ranch','2-400','From Denver, take 70W to Golden.  White Ranch State Park is ~2miles north of Golden and ~17 miles south of Boulder on Hwy 93.   Turn west (right if coming from Golden) onto W 56th Ave and follow the signs to the parking lot.',39.79906,-105.24839,' White Ranch has a wide variety of trails, from really rocky cactus-lined tracks to wooden bridges. There are several great views of Golden, Denver, and the Front Range.',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/400-1223999414.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(164,'Yampa','Colorado','Mosquito Lake (Bear River Trail) (#1120)','2-732','From Yampa take County Road 7 (turns into Forest Road 900) to the end.  Park at Stillwater Resevoir.  The trail follows along side the reservoir.',0,0,' Trail starts at 10,200 feet and climbs to approximately 11,400 over 2.5 miles.  The lake is in a bowl with fantastic views on all sides.  On the days without a breeze it is aptly named.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/732-1235697205.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(165,'Gunnison','Colorado','CDT CO16: CO Hwy 114 to Sargents Mesa','2-3242','CO',38.225316,-106.585779,' Section 16 of the CDT runs for just over 20 miles from CO Hwy 114 to Sargents Mesa. Along the way the trail passes through some high forests as well as Long Branch Baldy.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(166,'Golden','Colorado','Golden Gate Canyon State Park','2-108','Golden Gate Canyon SP is a short 30 miles from Denver. Follow I-70 west to exit 265 for highway 58. Take highway 58 west to highway 93. Turn right (north) on highway 93 for approximately 1 mile to Golden Gate Canyon road. Turn left and follow Golden Gate Canyon road 13 miles to the Visitor Center. The campground is approximately 5 miles from the Visitor Center( in the summer when Mountain Base Rd is open. In winter continue on Hwy 46 West 3 mi to Hwy 119 go north on Hwy 119 4mi to mile marker 15.5 approximately and look for Gap Rd on your right). RVs or vehicles towing large trailers must continue west to Hwy 119 all seasons.',39.830859,-105.410531,'The Golden Gate Canyon State Park offers 12,000 acres of dense wooded areas, rocky mountain peaks, and aspen laden meadows. Miles of trails are available for the avid hiker, biker, camper or horseback rider. Winter sports are also exciting and popular here during the cold months. The park offers several amenities such as the 132 campsites, various backcountry camping shelters, electrical hook-ups, toilets, and laundry facilities, among many more. More than 12,000 acres of dense forest, rocky peaks, and aspen-rimmed meadows laced with miles of trails awaiting the hiker, horseback rider, mountain biker and winter sports enthusiast at Golden Gate Canyon State Park. Only 30 miles from Denver, Golden Gate Canyon offers such amenities as a electrical hook-ups and tent-sites in two different campgrounds, stocked fishing ponds, picnic sites and the Panorama Point Scenic Overlook, where visitors can see 100 miles of the Continental Divide.  Over 35 miles of hiking trails in the park offer pleasures and challenges for everyone. The twelve trails at Golden Gate Canyon are each named after an animal and marked with the animal\'s footprint. Trail head parking areas are easily accessible from the main roads in the park. Mountain bikes and horses are permitted in the park on multiple-use  trails.',35,'http://www.tripleblaze.com/./ra-content/images/uploads/2013/05/200_8733-292-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(167,'Golden','Colorado','Chimney Gulch','2-146','This trail starts just below Lookout Mtn in Golden.  The easiest way to get there is to take Hwy 6 North from I-70 for about 2 miles.  Just before you reach the Hwy 58 intersection you will notice a small dirt pullout on the left side.  Jeffco Open space has a great map of this park/trail.  The park is called Windy Saddle.',39.74272,-105.23472,' Chimney Gulch Trail is in the Jefferson County trail system and is connected to the Windy Saddle Trail and Park. The trail climbs to 2,000 feet in 2.5 miles from Highway 6 to the summit at Lookout Mountain Nature Center. The trail is moderate to advanced and passes through grass prairie and pine forest, crossing streams at several places.',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/04/0377537.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(168,'Grand Lake','Colorado','CDT CO36: Grand Lake to Bowen Gulch','2-3293','CO',40.240439,-105.826756,' Section 36 of the CDT in Colorado runs a length 28.2 miles from Grand Lake to Bowen Gulch. Note: there is also a possible shortcut to shorten this section. Along the way, the trail passes Green Mountain, Mount Patterson, Taylor Peak, The Sharkstooth, Otis Peak, Hallett Peak, Joe Mills Mountain, Sprague Mountain, Nakai Peak, and US Hwy 34.',28,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(169,'Manitou Springs','Colorado','The Incline','2-5935','Manitou Springs exit from 24 west. Left on Ruxton, continue on Hydro street towards the Cog Railway. Hard to find parking on weekends.',0,0,' This &quot;incline&quot; is like climbing a ladder.  8,585 ft and 2,610 steps ( at least according to the last step of the incline) Looking up all you see are vast wooden planks that continue endlessly.',1,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/04/cdv_photo_009-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(170,'Aspen Park','Colorado','Meyer Ranch Park','2-629','Take HWY 285 west out of Denver to about 1/2 mile east of Aspen Park. Trailhead and parking are on the southside of the road.',39.54621,-105.2723,' Rolling hay meadows lead to forested hillsides, with the ever-present chatter of pine squirrels and the rustle of quaking aspen leaves. The landscape invites one to meander and explore this exquisite park.Previously a working ranch, Meyer Ranch Park offers peaceful strolls through wildflower-laden meadows, lodgepole pine forests and aspen groves. There are a total of 4 hiking trails here: Owl\'s Perch Trail (.5mi), Lodgepole Loop Trail (1.2mi), Sunny Aspen Trail (.8mi), and Ole Ski Run Trail (1.3mi).',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/03/ASPENS-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(171,'Dillon','Colorado','Keystone Gulch','2-768','From I-70, take Highway 6 to Keystone.  At the first stoplight make a right then immediate left at the T.  Turn right on Soda Ridge Road then left on Keystone Gulch Road (dirt).  Parking area is on left and obvious.',39.59938,-105.97498,' This trail takes you through beautiful and dense forests that pass beaver ponds and creeks along the way. You\'ll start to take switchbacks up the mountain until you reach the timber line where you\'ll get to enjoy incredible views of the surrounding area!',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(172,'Palmer Lake','Colorado','Spruce Mountain','2-807','The Spruce Meadow trail head is off of I-25 at exit 167.  This is between Monument and Castle Rock.  After exiting I-25, turn West.  Follow the road for about 1 mile. The road will cross 2 railroad tracks.  The trail head is located left (South) after the 2nd railroad crossing.  The parking lot is very large and is very easy to see from the road.',39.17978,-104.85794,' The Spruce Mountain Trail gently switchbacks up Spruce Mountain through a ponderosa pine and Douglas fir forest up to fabulous rocky overlooks and a loop around the fairly-flat, forested mountaintop. The first lookout offers breathtaking views of Greenland Open Space, surrounding buttes, Pikes Peak, the Palmer Divide, Carpenter Creek and thousands of acres of protected open space.  There are plenty of opportunities to gaze off rocky lookouts, ridges and meadows from over 8 miles of trails. Bring your camera.  For variety, descend on the service road, hike the loop to the west, and hike back along the Eagle Pass trail.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(173,'Deckers','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Green Mountain','2-194','From Colorado Springs, take US 24 to Woodland Park.  Turn right onto CO 67 and go to Deckers.  Continue straight onto CO 126 approximately 15 miles.  Turn left onto road 550.  Parking lot is on the right.  There is a $4 daily use fee.',39.34482,-105.2573,' Colorado Trail / Green Mountain features 16 miles of hiking trails near Deckers, CO.',16,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/194-1223933378.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(174,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Bear Creek Regional Park','2-281','From I-25, exit at US 24 West, Cimmaron St. Head west. At the second stoplight (21st St.), turn left.The trail is on the right after the big hill. Parking is available on the right.',38.82509,-104.85969,' Bear Creek Regional Park is an extremely popular park, mainly for its stellar dog parks, with 3 miles covering a total of 575 acres. There are some walking paths that wind throughout the park for visitors to enjoy.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(175,'Telluride','Colorado','Galloping Goose','2-789','Trail starts across from the Conoco at the 145 junction.',0,0,' This rail-trail follows an old railroad grade into Ilium valley and goes about 15 miles one way. The trail leads over 20 scenic foot bridges, past many historical landmarks, and through the Uncompahgre National Forest.  Good out and back that\'s fairly flat - just turn around before you start feeling tired!',15,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/04/IMG_0926-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(176,'Carbondale','Colorado','Red Hill','2-832','From Glenwood Springs take hwy 82 south to Carbondale. At the intersection of hwy 133 and Hwy 82 turn left onto county road 107. Park there, its that simple. Begin your ride up CR 107 for about 1 mile you will find the entrance to Red Rill Park on your left. ',39.41843,-107.2204,' Red Hill Recreation Area is a network of trails that all lead to the summit of Mushroom Rock. The paths are usually rocky and lined with low-lying desert shrubs, and the views from the top are absolutely stunning! Please share the path with mountain bikers!',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(177,'Fraser','Colorado','Winter Park Resort','2-128','To get to Winter Park Resort from all points around the Denver area, find your way to I-70 heading West out of Denver. Follow I-70 West approximately 40 miles to Exit 232 to Winter Park, Empire and Granby. Follow Exit 232 onto Hwy 40 which will take you over Berthoud Pass (great photo ops) and to Winter Park. Mileage from Exit 232 to Winter Park is approximately 24 miles. Total mileage from Denver is 67 miles. ',39.8909,-105.76126,' Winter Park Resort opens up their trails in the off-season. There\'s over 25 miles of trail that traverse the mountain and offer hikers and mountain bikers an amazing area to explore.',25,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(178,'Keystone','Colorado','Aqueduct','2-987','From I-70 at Silverthorn take HWY 6 east to Keystone. At the stoplight, turn right onto Keystone Road. Turn left immediately, cross the Snake River. Turn right onto Soda Ridge Road. Park at Keystone Gulch on your left.',39.59974,-105.97601,' Mainly this trail is used as a connector between the Keystone Gulch Trail and other trails like the Blair Witch and Colorado Trail. It\'s about 5 miles in total, follows a stream, crosses footbridges, and offers amazing views of the aqueduct. At times it has very steep up and downhills, so be ready for a workout. This is a multi-use trail so please use caution.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(179,'Gunnison','Colorado','Curecanti National Recreation Area','2-2918','Curecanti National Recreation Area is located approximately 200 miles southwest of Denver.U.S. Highway 50 runs the length of Curecanti between Montrose and Gunnison, Colorado. The recreation area is also accessed from CO Hwy 149 and CO Hwy 92.Source: National Park Service',38.461999,-107.183843,' Curecanti National Recreation Area is a series of three reservoirs along the once wild Gunnison River. The reservoirs that make up Curecanti today are a destination for water-based recreation high in the Rocky Mountains. Best known for salmon and trout fishing, Curecanti also offers opportunities for hiking, boating, camping, and bird watching. There are a total of 7 beautiful hiking trails within the recreation area, all ranging from 1.5 miles to 6 miles. It\'s the perfect place to get away with your family, or build your endurance on a tough hike.',25,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Curecanti-NRA-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(180,'Boulder','Colorado','Boulder Valley Ranch','2-1328','From Boulder, go north on US 36. Continue past Jay Rd. for 1.5 miles, and take a right on a dirt road. The Foothills trailhead is just a little farther on the left. There are several other trailheads too.',40.07991,-105.26259,' The Eagle (2.6 mile from Mesa Reservoir to Eagle Trailhead) and Sage Trails (1.8 mile [2.7 for whole Sage/Eagle Loop]) form a loop between this trailhead and the Eagle Trailhead. Heading southward on the Sage Trail you can either take this loop or head westward on the Cobalt Trail below an old smelter of 1930s to 1940s vintage and connect to the Eagle Trail as it heads toward the Foothills Trailhead.  Another option is to pass the Cobalt Trail (0.9 mile) and take the Eagle Trail as it turns up toward the now dry Mesa Reservoir. A loop hike is available in the Mesa Reservoir area by following the Hidden Valley (1.0 mile) and Mesa Reservoir Trails (0.8 mile).',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(181,'Bailey','Colorado','Redskin Mountain','2-1536','From Colorado Springs, take US 24 to Woodland Park. Turn right onto CO 67 and go to Deckers. Continue straight onto CO 126 approximately 15 miles. Turn left onto FS Road 550.  Go about 10 miles, turn left onto FS Road 543 (Wellington Lake Rd.).  Parking is on the right at Colorado Trail sign.  From Denver, take Hwy 285 to Bailey and turn left onto County Rd 68.  Go approximately 9 miles, trailhead is on the right as described above.',39.33833,-105.40112,' This portion of trail is a part of the Colorado Trail and it lies right next to the Buffalo Creek trail system, running right past the Buffalo Creek campground. As such, it is a beautiful piece of singletrack that is well-worth a hike!',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(182,'Denver','Colorado','Cherry Creek Trail','2-318','Park anywhere legal near Colorado Blvd and the Alameda-Cherry Creek Drive area and head east on the Cherry Creek bike path.  Right before you get to the Four Mile House, you\'ll see a drop-in for the trail to your right.',0,0,' The Cherry Creek Trail is a fairly easy hike, being mostly flat with only a few technical sections.  However, one can get in a roughly 14-mile round trip if you do the entire thing (it ends a little ways past Evans/Iliff.)  It runs north/south between the bike path and the creek.  Sure, there are better hikes out there, but it\'s central location makes it a good after work hike and it\'s ease makes it good to take kids on.  There\'s lots of shade and even a couple of bars that serve food and cold drinks about a block from the trail on Iliff.  You\'ll likely encounter other hikers, trail runners, mountain bikers, and kids playing in the creek, so be alert, because there are a few blind corners.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/03/6560_1159490637200_1525828347_403315-0.jp.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(183,'Fruita','Colorado','Rustlers Loop','2-286','Take I-70 to exit #15. The Kokopelli trailhead parking lot is just off the exit on Frontage road. Either park in the main lot or opt to drive over the hill and park in the small lot near the trailhead gate.',39.17779,-108.82791,' This easy 3.5 mile loop takes you around the top of the mesa for stunning views of the Colorado River below. Canyon walls and desert bluffs surround you on this beautiful hike. Remember to share the path!',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(184,'Estas Park','Colorado','Gem Lake','2-8578','Directions from Estes Park: Drive north on MacGregor Avenue. Cross the Hwy 34 bypass and continue to a sharp right turn and sign for MacGregor Ranch. Follow the blacktop ranch road to the parking area.',0,0,' Gem Lake Trail is a 1.8 mile out and back trail located near Estes Park, Colorado that features a lake and is rated as moderate. The trail is primarily used for hiking and is accessible year-round.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(185,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Blodgett Peak','2-280','From I-25 take Woodmen Rd exit (149) and head west. Cross bridge over train-tracks. At next light Woodmen turns to the right, follow it. Stay on Woodmen for several miles (5 or so) as it passes a school on the left. At stop sign continue straight as it winds through sub-divisions. Woodmen gains in altitute as it head west and then it starts to run parallel to the range. On your right you will see a fire-road with a gate, a small sign identifies it as Blodget Open Space. Pull in and park or park on the street. ',38.9489,-104.8861,' Blodgett Peak hiking trail leads steeply up the mountain to a relatively-low elevation peak. However, the views from the top make the climb worth it, as it gives panoramic views of nearby Pikes Peak and the United States Air Force Academy.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/280-1223987490.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(186,'Avon','Colorado','Beaver Creek Ski Resort','2-382','From Denver, take I-70 West to exit 167, Avon.  Follow the signs to the Beaver Creek Ski resort.  There is no parking once you\'re up the mountain so be sure to make arrangements.',39.63121,-106.52535,' Beaver Creek Ski Resort features 37 miles of multi-use trails with 7 trails reserved for hikers only. The hiking trails range from 1-6 miles in length and are rated as green, blue, and black according to their difficulty levels.  Some of these trails are perfect for families and pass by playgrounds, others summit mountains for scenic views of the surrounding area.',37,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(187,'Lone Tree','Colorado','Bluffs Regional Park Trail','2-904','From I-25 take Lincoln Ave east about one block to Ridgegate Parkway, take that south about 1/2 mile to the trailhead',39.52848,-104.8867,' Bluffs Regional Park Trail features 4 miles of hiking trails near Lone Tree, CO. There is a 2.7-mile loop of soft-surface trail (3.5 miles including the feeder trails and overlooks) that winds along the open country. Enjoy beautiful views of the surrounding area. This trail is perfect for families with children, but it is a multi-use trail so please practice trail etiquette.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(188,'Fruita','Colorado','Kodel Canyon','2-5878','Kodel Canyon shares a trailhead with Devil\'s Canyon.  From Fruita drive south across the Interstate and turn right onto King\'s View Court.  Follow the road as it turns to gravel and after a mile or so you\'ll see a parking area far out on the left and a sign for &quot;Devil\'s Canyon.&quot;',0,0,' From the parking area follow the gravel road up and over a slight knoll.  Continue down the gravel road until you see a trail sign on the left for one of the &quot;K&quot; trails.  It\'s best to have a map (usually available at the parking area) to find your way through the myriad of trails in the Kodel Canyon section.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/04/523997_10151502022360285_54950418_n-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(189,'Snowmass Village','Colorado','Rim Trail','2-1441','From Interstate 70, take the Glenwood Springs Exit and head South on highway 82. Approx. 35 miles, follow signs for Snowmass and turn right on Brush Creek Road.  After 5-7 miles, you will go under a skier bridge and soon after turn right onto Divide Road.  The trailhead is on the right on you will clearly see the parking across the road.',39.20847,-106.95732,' Rim Trail takes you along the ridge of the mountain showcasing the stunning views that Snowmass has to offer. Even though you get amazing views on the trail, it\'s not too difficult besides the initial climbs. Please share the path with mountain bikers.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(190,'Granby','Colorado','CDT CO35: Monarch Lake to Grand Lake','2-3292','CO',40.110791,-105.74638,' Section 35 of the CDT in Colorado runs 14.2 miles from Monarch Lake to Grand Lake. Along the way, the trail enters Rocky Mountain National Park and passes Lake Granby, Green Ridge, and Shadow Mountain Lake.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(191,'Salida','Colorado','Arkansas Headwaters Recreation Area','2-3629','To get to the AHRA Visitor Center from the intersection of Highways 285/24 at Johnson Village, go south on Highway 285, drive 14 miles to Hwy 291, turn left, drive 8 miles to G St and turn left at the Skateboard Park. Go to the end of this block which intersects with Sackett Ave, parallel to the Arkansas River. The AHRA Visitor Center is the brick building with a blue roof on the corner of G and Sackett Streets. From the intersection of Highways 50/291, turn north on Hwy 291 (1st Street), go one block past the stop light to G Street, turn right 1 block to Sackett Ave, turn left. The Visitor center is on left corner of Sackett and G Streets.',38.537484,-105.992531,'The Arkansas Headwaters Recreation Area (AHRA) is recognized as one of the nation\'s most popular locations for whitewater rafting and kayaking on the Arkansas River - the most commercially rafted river in the United States! The AHRA has a wide variety of trails for every outdoor enthusiast, from the hiker to the to mountain biker and OHV rider. Hayden Meadows, at the northern end of AHRA, has ADA accessible interpretive and fishing trails, 5 wetland boardwalks, and 2 bridges surrounding a small reservoir. Collegiate Peaks Group Picnic Area: is at the head of both the Midland Bike Trail, Barbara Whipple Trail and Four Mile systems, which offer miles of scenic motorized and non-motorized routes for all skill levels. At the Ruby Mountain campground, both the FourMile trail system and the Browns Canyon Wilderness Study Area (WSA) can be accessed. FourMile is designated for both motorized and nonmotorized use, while Browns Canyon WSA is for nonmotorized use only. Below the Hecla Junction Campground a Â¾ mile foot trail leads downstream along the shoreline to Seidel\'s Suckhole, which is a great place to watch and photograph whitewater rafting in the summer and offers excellent fishing in the spring and summer. Lone Pine Recreation Site has a designated river trail approximately 1/2 mile in length that begins near the restrooms and picnic site on the east end. This trail is used for wildlife and river viewing as well as fishing access. McIntyre Hills Wilderness Study Area (WSA) can be accessed from the Five Points Campground. A trail begins between campsites #4 and #5, but much of the McIntyre Hills WSA is comprised of undesignated, or social, trails. A trail map on the entrance station shows the trail\'s alignment.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(192,'Morrison','Colorado','Lair O\' The Bear/Bear Creek Trail','2-147','Take I-70 west from Denver to C-470. C-470 east to Morrison Rd. Morrison Rd west for about 7 miles to Lair O\' the Bear open space park on the south side of the road.',39.656969,-105.263026,' Lair O\' The Bear/Bear Creek Trail follows rolling terrain over open meadows and through thick forests. Hike alongside creeks and enjoy views of the mountains and the surrounding area. Parts of this trail are popular with families, and this entire out-and-back is popular with mountain bikers so be sure share the trail.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(193,'Pine','Colorado','Buffalo Creek','2-165','From Colorado Springs, take US 24 to Woodland Park. Turn right onto CO 67 and go to Deckers. Continue straight onto CO 126 approximately 20 miles.  Parking is on the right just before the bridge at the Buffalo Creek Forest Service Work Center.  The trail starts on Buffalo Creek road on the left of CO 126 just over the bridge.  Ride about 3 miles and turn right onto Baldy Trail and stay on Baldy through the climb.  Turn right onto Gashouse, and make your next turn right onto Miller Gulch Trail.  Go left onto the Homestead trail, then right on Charlie\'s Cutoff.  This becomes Sandy Wash trail, take this back down to Buffalo Creek Road.',39.38867,-105.27217,' The Buffalo Creek trail system is at least 14 miles long and includes a number of different trails. The singletrack itself is fairly sandy and gravely. These trails offer some gorgeous views due to an old burn and they pass by some amazing rock formations. There\'s a nearby campground of the same name.  Note: this is a fairly popular mountain bike destination.',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/165-1223988900.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(194,'Denver','Colorado','Colorado Trail','2-2122','Multiple trailheads around the state, click one of the individual segment listings above to get directions to a particular staring point. From Denver, start off S. Platte Canyon Rd.',39.49016,-105.09689,' The Colorado Trail offers amazing singletrack, incredible views, some steep high-altitude climbs, and it passes through 6 wilderness areas. It is probably Colorado\'s best long-distance backpacking trail.',535,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/06/2014-06-01153306-194160.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(195,'Rocky Mountain National Park','Colorado','Loch Vale Lake','2-8608','Navigate the Rocky Mountain National Park to the Bear Lake Parking Lot.  This is a map in the parking lot showing the route to Loch Lake.',0,0,' Perfect Hike for a sunny afternoon to get up and out of the city.  Located in the beautiful Rocky Mountain National Park, the setting is one that will sweep you off your feet.  Great place for lunch or dinner.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(196,'Westminster','Colorado','Standley Lake','2-537','Take US-36 to Sheridan Blvd exit.  Turn Left at Sheridan Blvd.  Turn right on 88th Ave.  Continue on 88th Avenue to W 86th Pkwy.  At Simms Street, make a right onto trail head parking.',39.85277,-105.13012,' Standley Lake Regional Park boasts more than 14 miles of maintained trails, single-track trails and roads that are available to hiking, mountain biking and horse back riding. Maintained trails, which make up the majority of the park\'s system, offer a variety of terrain that appeals to most hikers and horseback riders.There are just a few steep hills, but they will reward you with breathtaking overlooks of Standley Lake and the Front Range. While using the trails within the park, you have the opportunity to see many of the plants and animals common to this area, including native grasses, wildflowers, cottonwoods, prairie dogs, cotton-tailed rabbits, hawks and meadowlarks, just to name a few. Standley Lake Regional Park is also the starting point for some of the city\'s major trail corridors, including the the Big Dry Creek Trail and the Farmers\' High Line Canal Trail. In addition, there is a substantial network of trails on the south side of the lake. Many of the trails link to others throughout the city\'s network of more than 63 miles of off-road trails.',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/02/photo_001-1.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(197,'Monte Vista','Colorado','Limekiln','2-1995','from Monte Vista, go west on Hwy 160 for about 6.3 miles to County Road 5W. Turn south (left) onto BLM road 5120 and go 4.1 miles and park.',37.60216,-106.29792,' Enjoy the San Luis Valley on this 6 mile out-and-back trail that takes you through a desert terrain and overlooks Colorado\'s beautiful front range. Make sure to bring extra water out here, and remember to share the trail with mountain bikers!',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(198,'Black Forest','Colorado','Black Forest Regional Park','2-282','From Colorado Springs, take Black Forest Road north into the Black Forest.  Turn left onto Shoup Rd. at the second light you see.  The park is on the right about 2 miles down Shoup.',39.01355,-104.73789,' This park includes 427 acres and is located approximately four miles east of Interstate 25 on Shoup Road.  As suggested by its name, the character of Black Forest Park is dominated by the presence of the ponderosa pine forest. The developed area, with turf playfields, tennis courts and two picnic pavilions, were developed in natural openings of the forest.  A six mile, loop trail used for non-motorized recreation winds through the park.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(199,'Boulder','Colorado','Walker Ranch','2-312','In Boulder, use Flagstaff Rd. @ Chatauqua park go about 6 or 7 miles.  Has A small dirt road on left (south) side to reach trailhead.    Watch for cyclists climbing Flagstaff Rd. From Golden, go north on Hwy 93 to Coal Creek Canyon dr. (Hwy 72) take a left and go approx 8mi to Gross Dam rd on the right, road may not be marked but it is ~.5mi past the Boulder County sign.  Take a very sharp right onto this dirt rd (nearly 180deg) and go 2.7mi to the Crescent Meadow parking lot on the right, just past the railroad tracks.',39.95145,-105.33752,' Sporting a diverse array of ecosystems to explore, it\'s virtually impossible to get bored at Walker Ranch. From the great staircase to South Boulder Creek to the open view across Crescent Meadow to the historic homestead, Walker Ranch is a cultural and natural treasure.   There are 3 trails here: Meyers Homestead Trail, Walker Ranch Loop, and Walker Ranch Link.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(200,'Breckenridge','Colorado','Dwight\'s','2-1582','From Denver: West on I-70, Exit at Frisco and to south on highway 9, there should be signs for Brekenridge, stay on 9 to Breckenridge. then turn right(west) in Lincoln Ave, this will take you to a parking lot where the ski lift are. From parking lot, go up the stairs, then go directly left, you\'ll see the trail going up the hill(where Pioneer Trail starts) Dwight\'s is on the right, but I don\'t think u want to climb it!  Or just buy a lift ticket up to the trailhead on top of the mountain.  There are Trail maps available at the ticket window',0,0,' Dwight\'s Trail is a 3 mile trail (6-out-and-back) within the Breckenridge skiing area. Either hike up for a great out-and-back trail or take the lift up and hike the 3 miles down. Enjoy beautiful aspen forests and stunning mountaintop views! This trail is multi-use is watch out for mountain bikers.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(201,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Rough Canyon','2-8584','Take Little Park Road to the main Bangs Canyon parking lot.  Follow the signs to Rough Canyon.',0,0,' Rough Canyon can be done as an out-and-back or, for the full 5 miles, as a loop.  Follow the canyon up and around, over and across boulders and pools of water to its end and then look for the easy to see trail on your left. This will take you to the Tabeguache Trail.  Go left and follow it back to the parking lot.  The steady climb on the Taeguache Trail is tiring, but it levels out after about a mile.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/05/canyon.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(202,'Boulder','Colorado','Marshall Mesa/Community Ditch','2-466','From Broadway &amp; Baseline in Boulder, travel south on Hghwy 93 towards Golden. After 4 miles you will turn left and park at the lot just to the east of 93. The trail head is at the corner of 93 and 170 (Eldorado Springs Drive/Marshall Mesa Drive).',39.95574,-105.21847,' Marshall Mesa Trail connects to the Community Ditch Trail and a loop hike can be taken combining these two trails. Self-guided interpretive signs about the coal mining and geologic history of the Marshall area are located along this trail. Community Ditch Trail provides access to the south to the Greenbelt Plateau Trail and to the west to the Doudy Draw area. Birds of prey are frequently sighted in this area. Coyotes and mule deer are common. There is a large prairie dog town near the trailhead.',16,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(203,'Dillon','Colorado','Summit Cove/Soda Creek Loop','2-769','Take I70 west of Denver to Silverthorne south on hwy.6  to Swan Mountain Road right, first left on Cove Blvd. Right at Soda Creek on Royalcoachman Blvd.  Left on Forest Glen park at Whispering Pines Trailhead on the right.',39.58802,-106.01548,' Summit Cove/Soda Creek Loop is a beautiful 15 mile loop trail. It takes you over smooth singletrack that winds through dense forests and then it opens up into scenic meadows that allow you to take in the stunning mountain views that surround you.  This is a multi-use trail so please share the trail!',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(204,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','CDT CO42: Buffalo Pass to North Lake','2-3299','CO',40.544471,-106.684703,' The CDT runs 20.7 miles from Buffalo Pass to North Lake. Along the way, the trail passes Mount Ethel and The Dome.',21,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(205,'Ridgway','Colorado','Ridgway State Park','2-3621','Take U.S. 550 SOUTH of Montrose for 22 miles to the park entrance, on the right (west) side of the road. NORTH of Ridgway on 550 4 miles to the park entrance, on the left (west) side of the road.',38.215361,-107.733346,'Mountain scenery mingles with magnificent campgrounds at Ridgway State Park.  Modern, universally-accessible recreation areas and the five-mile long reservoir make memorable days and nights. Only 15 miles from the town of Ouray, Ridgway\'s great outdoors - the &quot;Switzerland of America&quot; - welcomes those from near and far. Seven miles of trails connect the north and south ends of the park.  About three miles of universally-accessible concrete trails and 11 miles of natural surface trails enable visitors to enjoy the scenery yet remain within easy distance of park facilities.   All trails are open and in good condition. There are 14 miles of trail, open for hiking, biking and general access around the park. The Cookie Tree trail has some slight erosion on the west side of the trail (along the reservoir shoreline) due to the high water level; practice caution, the hazard is clearly marked. All other trails are in great condition. Trail maps are available at our Visitor Center. Enjoy!',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(206,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Kannah Creek Trail','2-6624','Take Hwy 50 south from Grand Junction for 12 miles; turn left onto Kannah Creek road (sign for Land\'s end) go 2.7 miles and turn right and right again to continue on Kannah Creek road.  After 6.7 turn right into a parking area just before a bridge and creek crossing.',0,0,' The Kannah Creek trail climbs almost 8 miles to Carson Lake on the Grand Mesa.  It is an out-and-back trail that gains 4,000 ft of elevation gradually.  Scenic with few fellow hikers. This trail contains many creek crossing so consideration should include spring run-off. Since the trail parallels Kannah Creek for the entire distance, fishing is available at almost any time. This trail also offers a scenic view, especially along the upper section as it looks down into the Kannah Creek Basin.',16,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/06/IMG_0218-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(207,'Fruita','Colorado','Frontside','2-8788','This ride will start from the 18 Road TH parking area.',0,0,' 22 mile hiking trail located near Fruita, Colorado',22,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(208,'Fruita','Colorado','Troy Built Trail','2-2020','From Interstate 70 take the Mack exit 11. Turn south and 1/2 mi.  will be TH parking.',39.21134,-108.87112,' Troy Built Trail is an 8 mile out-and-back trail on rocky trails traversing the desert terrain. The trail climbs up canyon walls and looks over the famous Colorado River. This trail is part of the Kokopelli Trail System. This is a multi-use trail so please share the path.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(209,'Snowmass Village','Colorado','Cross Mountain','2-1462','From exit #116 on I-70 take Hwy 82 some 38 miles to Brushcreek Rd (R) which takes you to Snowmass Village. (approx 5.5 miles) There are numerous parking options once you get there.  From Base Village, there are a few ways to ascend to this trail.',0,0,' Cross Mtn. Trail is mainly a connector trail that can be hiked from either the west or the east side. The trail ranges between 10,400-11,000 feet in elevation, and winds through scenic dense forests. It\'s one of the higher trails on the mountain, and it does have lift access if wanted. This is a multi-use trail so please be aware of mountain bikers.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(210,'Oak Creek','Colorado','Stagecoach','2-1662','North from I-70: Take the Wolcott Exit onto HWY 131 for 50 miles, turn right on County Road 14 for 6 miles.',40.288695,-106.863725,'Stagecoach State Park sets the stage for great recreation in the lush Yampa Valley by Steamboat Springs. Vistas and views are backdrops to the 820-acre reservoir providing renown lake and river fishing. Stagecoach is part of the actual trail used by the stage line between Grand Junction and Grand Valley. This trail will take you through DeBeque Canyon and along the Colorado River, highlighting some stunning views! The trail can get pretty rough and rocky in parts, but the views make it all worth it!',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(211,'Edwards','Colorado','Berry Creek Loop','2-875','From I-70 Exit 163 go south on Beard Creek road up the hill going west.  Just past Shaw Cancer Center make right onto Moonridge Dr. and left into Berry Creek access area (park on right).  ',39.65317,-106.59231,' Berry Creek Loop features is a nice little fireroad/doubletrack hike that takes you through some beautiful juniper and sage scrub. The trail overlooks the surrounding mountains and valleys, a great reward for a fairly easy hike!',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(212,'Lyons','Colorado','Rabbit Mountain Loop','2-427','From Boulder, CO.  go north on Highway 36 to Lyons, there will be a light here and you can only go left or right, go right(East) on Highway 66 for about 1 mile.  Turn left on 53rd street, there should be a sign here for Rabbit Mountain open space.  go almost 3 miles and you will see the parking lot on the right.',40.24608,-105.22387,' Whether hoping to spot a large raptor in search of prey or a gorgeous view of the Continental Divide, look no further than Rabbit Mountain. Located between Lyons and Longmont, the rich cultural and natural history of Rabbit Mountain is easily accessible to bikers, hikers, and equestrians.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/11/photo_023-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(213,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Mica Mine','2-7697','Drive up Little Park Road until you see a sign on the left for the Bangs Canyon Recreation area.  (5  miles)',38.98954,-108.61766,' The Mica Mine trail is 2.6 miles RT and is fairly easy.  It can be hiked by those as young as 4.  It\'s a great hike through Ladder Canyon to an old Mica Mine site.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/08/2013-08-10-15-48-45-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(214,'Frisco/Breckenridge','Colorado','Wheeler Loop','2-86','Take I-70 west of Denver to the second Frisco exit #201 East on Main st. to Second Av. turn right follow 2nd av. across bikepath and park in parking lot.',39.56904,-106.09971,' Wheeler Loop is a must hike if you\'re in the Breckenridge area. This hike will take you up on a steep climb until you reach the ridgeline. You\'ll keep hiking along mountain ridges and the views are incredible! The 5.5 mile steep climb at the beginning will seem like it was nothing because of these views!',30,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(215,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Reno / Flag / Bear / Deadman','2-454','From Colorado Highway 135, take the Cement Creek Road (FS 740) east to the Deadman Gulch Trailhead, about seven miles .  Cement Creek Road is about seven miles south of Crested Butte.',38.87471,-106.7981,' The Reno, Flag, Bear, and Deadman trails are some of the best singletrack trails in Crested Butte! They offer gorgeous views of the surrounding mountains, high alpine meadows, and deep Colorado forests.',20,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/11/1400-1218577576-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(216,'Vail','Colorado','Vail Mountain','2-503','Exit Vail from I-70 and follow signs to the Vail Village Parking Lot.',39.64269,-106.38821,' In the off-season, Vail Mountain opens it\'s trails up to hikers and mountain bikers. There are over 25 miles of beautiful mountainside trails, and some even reach up to the summit.',25,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(217,'Golden','Colorado','North Table Mountain','2-1497','From Golden, take CO-93 north toward Boulder. Parking area is just outside Golden on the right side of Hwy 93 and is well marked.',39.782,-105.22969,' Mostly exposed hiking trails but you\'ll find a few hidden gems here including a (seasonal?) waterfall. Tremendous views and interesting geology as the trail winds around the sides of the mesa.',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/09/photo_002-2.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(218,'Manitou Springs','Colorado','Red Mountain Trail','2-2183','Accessible two ways, but you have to do some hiking on the Paul Intemann Memorial Trail to get to it.In Manitou, take Pawnee St. up until it becomes a dirt road.  Right after you\'ll see the Paul Intemann trailhead.  Or, take Ruxton up until you would veer off to the right to go to the Incline and the Cog Railroad.  The Intemann trailhead is on the left hand side of the street.',0,0,' This is a 1.3 mile climb to the top, with the same mileage coming back down (obviously.)',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/032-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(219,'Breckenridge','Colorado','Peaks Trail','2-830','Go to the end of 2nd Ave off Main St in Frisco, or go to Peak 8 at Breckenridge Ski Resort',39.4874,-106.06724,' This is a one way trail that starts from either the town of Frisco or Breckenridge. The trail climbs in and out of numerous drainages for its\' entire length staying mostly in the lodgepole pine forest along with some aspen, spruce and fir forests. Most of the lodgepole pine trees are of the same age and provide ground cover and/or forage for wildlife in the area. You will cross some small clearings which were harvested in 1988. These trees were cut to increase the wildlife habitat and to improve the health of the forest by creating age and species diversity, thereby reducing the fire danger.  Since the grade from Breckenridge toward Frisco is generally downhill, many people travel this direction and ride the free Summit Stage Bus back to Breckenridge.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(220,'Fraser','Colorado','Northwest Passage / Tipperary / Spruce Creek / Flume','2-489','There are many places you can access this loop so feel free to pick up the trail wherever is most convenient for you.  From the town of Fraser, go out the St. Louis Creek Road approximately 2-3 miles.  You will see Forest Service signs on the right side of the road immediately past the trail crossing.  This is the bottom of Northwest Passage (on the right, going to the Northwest) and the end of Creekside (from the left to the south).',39.92606,-105.85876,' This 15 mile loop is basically a beautiful and relaxing walk in the woods. Enjoy hiking on old reclaimed forest roads, and take in the secluded nature that surrounds you. Every once in awhile you\'ll catch a glimpse of the surrounding mountains! These trails are open to mountain bikers as well, so please share the trail.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(221,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Killpecker','2-974','Take US 287 north from Fort Collins, CO or south from Laramie, WY to Red Feather Lakes Road.  Go west 24-25 miles to Deadman Road.  Turn left on Deadman Rd. go another 6-7 miles and the Killpecker Trail parking will be on your left (south).',40.81332,-105.71061,' The trail leads through a pine forest along Killpecker Creek crossing the stream twice before meeting Forest Road 300, Killpecker Road. The trail resumes south of the road about 100 yards to the east. Forest Road 300 intersects the trail twice again before the trail crests just northwest of Middle Bald Mountain then descends to end at Forest Road 517, Elkhorn Creek/Bald Mountain. The south end of North Lone Pine Trail (#953) can be accessed by going approximately a Â½-mile east on road 517.  Establishing a shuttle for the 3-mile distance between the Killpecker and North Lone Pine trailheads on Deadman Road may facilitate a loop hiking route using both trails, although motorized vehicles are not allowed on North Lone Pine trail. Killpecker trailhead accommodates approximately 3 vehicles.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(222,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','ROCK ISLAND REGIONAL TRAIL','2-8469','Parallel to Highway 24 between Falcon and Ramah.',38.833861,-104.821386,'The 23-mile Rock Island Regional Trail runs parallel to Highway 24 between Falcon and Ramah and is part of the America the Beautiful Trail.  Nine miles of the trail was constructed on the former Chicago an Rock Island Railroad Line between Falcon and Peyton.  Excellent views of several landmarks are visible from the trail including Pikes Peak, Rampart Range, Rattlesnake Buttes at Homestead Ranch Regional Park, Spanish Peaks, West Mountains, and the Sange de Cristo mountain range.  Opportunities for wildlife observation are abundant. Picnic tables are located at the Falcon Trailhead, and benches are polaced at regular intervals along the trail corridor. The 23-mile Rock Island Regional Trail runs parallel to Highway 24 between Falcon and Ramah and is part of the America the Beautiful Trail.  Nine miles of the trail was constructed on the former Chicago an Rock Island Railroad Line between Falcon and Peyton.  Excellent views of several landmarks are visible from the trail including Pikes Peak, Rampart Range, Rattlesnake Buttes at Homestead Ranch Regional Park, Spanish Peaks, West Mountains, and the Sange de Cristo mountain range.  Opportunities for wildlife observation are abundant. Picnic tables are located at the Falcon Trailhead, and benches are polaced at regular intervals along the trail corridor.',23,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(223,'Boulder','Colorado','Gregory Canyon / Chautauqua','2-1475','From Boulder, take Broadway south to Baseline. Turn right (west) onto Baseline and look for the Chautauqua ranger station / trailhead area on the left after about a mile.',39.999269,-105.282771,' Dozens of trails to choose from, most accessible from the grounds of the Chautauqua National Historic Landmark. We hiked a 2 mile loop combining McClintock and Enchanted Mesa trails. Open valley sections, forested trails, mild to steep climbs, views, rocks - you name it, this trail system has it all. Super convenient to Boulder and University of Colorado.',20,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/04/860433_10202454931154226_1118547989_o.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(224,'Mosca','Colorado','Great Sand Dunes National Park and Preserve','2-2921','From Denver, Colorado Springs, or Pueblo, the most common route is south on I-25 to Walsenburg, west on US 160, north on State Highway 150. For a more mountainous drive from Denver (same mileage as the I-25 route), you may also take US 285 south, then State Highway 17 south, then County Lane 6 east from Mosca. Source: National Park Service',37.713278,-105.68152,' The tallest dunes in North America are the centerpiece in a diverse landscape of grasslands, wetlands, conifer and aspen forests, alpine lakes, and tundra.  Explore anything from dune trails, where you can climb the &quot;high dune,&quot; to forested trails under the aspens and evergreens, to alpine trails, and back down to trails that wind through grasslands, shrublands, and wetlands! Great Sand Dunes really does have it all!',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/05/100_8649-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(225,'Littleton','Colorado','South Valley Park','2-305','From the metro area, travel west on C-470 and exit southbound on Ken Caryl Avenue. Turn left onto South Valley Road to the park\'s north parking area. Alternately, from South Platte Canyon Road (S. Wadsworth and C-470) take Deer Creek Canyon Road west to the smaller, south parking area.',39.55119,-105.13932,' Dramatic red sandstone spires. Stunning views of craggy outcroppings. Pleasant trails suited to beginning mountain bikers and hikers who prefer more level terrain. A diversity of trails offer quiet refuge from the tempo of the neighboring suburbs and criss-cross the eastern half of South Valley Park. The Swallow Trail is hiker-only.',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/07/hiking-with-jesse-019-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(226,'Conifer','Colorado','Flying J Ranch','2-630','From Denver, head south on Hwy 285 to Hwy 73 in Conifer.  Head north on Hwy 73 for 1 mile to the parking area on the left at the first entrance.  Ride the connector trail up to the main loop.',39.54513,-105.32256,' This is a very easy, very flat 2 mile loop. It does pass through some pretty forests, though.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/06/photo_009-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(227,'Dillon','Colorado','CDT CO30: Argentine Pass to Herman Gulch','2-3287','CO',39.602709,-105.813118,' Section 30 of the CDT trail in Colorado runs for 16.7 miles form Argentine Pass to Herman Gulch Trailhead at US Hwy 6. Along the way, the trail passes Decatur Mountain, Ruby Mountain, Argentine Peak, Mount Edwards, Gray\'s Peak (14,270 ft.), Torrey\'s Peak (14,267 ft.), Kelso Mountain, and US Hwy 6. Unlike most of the mountain peaks where the CDT skirts below the actual top of the mountain, the CDT actually reaches the summits of Mount Edwards and Gray\'s Peak, a 14er.',17,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(228,'Monument','Colorado','Limbaugh Canyon (715)','2-7983','take the monument palmer lake exit and head west, drive through downtown monument and over the train tracks. take a left at the stop sign, then take the right on to mt herman road. drive until you see the parking lot on the left hand side. park and ride the trail system over to 715 or take the road that splits the area in half unitl you find 715 on your left.',39.08284,-104.88776,' Limbaugh Canyon (715) is a 25 mile hiking trail in Monument, Colorado.',25,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(229,'Boulder','Colorado','Flatirons Vista','2-8696','From Boulder, head south on 93. After you pass Highway 128, turn right into the trailhead parking lot (if your vehicle isn\'t registered in Boulder county, you\'re supposed to pay a fee; ignore at your own risk!). You can also take 93 north out of Golden to get here.',39.92423,-105.23545,' 4 mile hiking trail located near Boulder, Colorado',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(230,'Pueblo','Colorado','South Shore Lake Pueblo','2-100','Take Colorado 96 west of Pueblo.  Trail starts 1/4 mile after second exit to Lake Pueblo State Park.  At the top of the hill there is a turn off and a red gate.  Trail maps are usually available on a post.',38.23701,-104.72992,' These trails are gorgeous! They follow the rims of the canyons offering stunning views of Lake Pueblo, Pikes Peak, and the Front Range. These trails are perfect for a great workout, and keep your eye out for some wildlife! Please remember to share the path!',18,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/03/IMG_0044-hdr_1024x682-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(231,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Buckhorn Loop','2-523','From Colorado Springs go west and get on Cheyenne Canyon Rd.  Follow this up through the canyon past Helen Hunt Falls to the large dirt parking lot (This is High Drive parking lot).  The trail begins on the dirt road at the back corner of the parking lot at the gate that restricts cars from access.',38.79082,-104.9041,' Buckhorn Loop (Captain Jack\'s Frontside) features a 5 mile loop trail near Colorado Springs. The trail winds through deep forests and also provides stunning views of the mountains nearby.  This trail is mainly used as a mountain bike trail so please practice caution.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(232,'Mancos','Colorado','Praeter Ridge Trail','2-3151','From the main park entrance, drive approximately 4 miles to the Morefield Campground area.',37.29696,-108.418574,' This trail is a 7.8 mile loop that starts and ends in the Morefield Campground area. The trail takes you along a ridge until you reach the top of the mountain. From the top you get stunning views of the surrounding area.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(233,'Rand','Colorado','CDT CO38: Willow Creek Pass to Troublesome Pass','2-3295','CO',40.350256,-106.089938,' Section 38 of the CDT in Colorado runs 11.6 miles from Willow Creek Pass on Hwy 125 to Troublesome Pass. Along the way, the trail passes Haystack Mountain.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(234,'Deckers','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Morrison Creek (Lunar Loop)','2-766','From Colorado Springs, take US 24 to Woodland Park.  Turn right onto CO 67 and go to  Deckers.  Continue straight onto CO 126 approximately 15 miles.  Turn left onto road 550.   Parking lot is on the right.  There is a $4 daily use fee.',39.34482,-105.2573,' This section of the trail can be turned into a loop. It climbs a total of about 800 feet, leaving the ascent pretty gradual. You\'ll hike through a large burn area which leaves you looking out over the beautiful mountainside.  Most of the Colorado Trail is multi-use so please be on the lookout for mountain bikers.',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/04/IMG_0262-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(235,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Waltham Trail','2-1720','From I-25 traveling north from Denver to Fort Collins, take the E. Harmony exit (west) and travel for 3-4 miles until you come to South Taft.  Turn right on So. Taft and drive a short distance until you intersect 38E.  Turn left on 38E and drive up around Horsetooth Lake until you come to Horsetooth Park.  Park in the parking lot on the right, but make sure you have a day pass.',40.52312,-105.1817,' Waltham Trail is a tough 12 mile trail that connects with a network of other trails. The trail traverses through the desert terrain, over bluffs, and it climbs rocky paths to keep your heart rate up.  This is a multi-use trail so please share the path.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(236,'Mesa Verde','Colorado','Mesa Verde National Park','2-2923','Mesa Verde National Park is in Southwestern Colorado. The Mesa Verde Headquarters is a one-hour drive from Cortez, Colorado, heading east on Highway 160 to the park turnoff, and a 1.5 hour drive from Durango, Colorado, heading west on Highway 160 to the park turnoff.Source: National Park Service',37.257685,-108.497812,' Hiking in Mesa Verde National Park is restricted and allowed only on designated trails. Visitors may not enter cliff dwellings unless accompanied by a uniformed park ranger. However there are several trails that total 20 miles within the park. Source: National Park Service',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/06/mesa_verde3-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(237,'Castle Rock','Colorado','Memmen Ridge Open Space','2-866','Memmen  Ridge DirectionsDirections from I-25:1. Take the Wolfensberger Rd/ Wilcox St exit, Exit 1822.Turn east at the ramp and follow Wilcox St for approx. 0.6 miles3.Turn left at 2nd St and follow for 0.3 miles.4.Turn right at Gilbert St and follow for 0.1 miles.5.Turn left at South St then turn right at Oman Road.6. Trailhead parking lot will be on your left.',39.36865,-104.84884,' This area provides a quick escape into forested open space from nearby Downtown Castle Rock. The 43-acre parcel is located south of South Street Elementary School and can be accessed from a paved trail at Oman Road. The willows and cattails in the riparian area quickly change to a mature ponderosa pine forest on the ridge\'s north-facing slope. A short trip to the top of this ridge can provide views of the southern areas of Town.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(238,'Fruita','Colorado','Devil\'s Canyon Hiking Area','2-2806','From I-70 West take the Fruita exit and turn left (south).  Cross the Colorado River and turn right onto King\'s View Court.  This will turn into a gravel/dirt road.  The sign and parking area for Devil\'s Canyon will become visible on the left after a mile at the most.',0,0,' Devil\'s Canyon is not just one hiking trail - it\'s 2 canyons and a myriad of possibilities all in one.  Unlike a lot of the trails in the Fruita/Grand Junction area, the Devil\'s Canyon trails are for horses and people only.  If you aren\'t a fan of dodging mountain or dirt bikers, this is the place to go.  Most people allow their dogs to run off-leash here as well.  Maps are available near the beginning of the trail area and should be used!  The Devil\'s Canyon side has about 6 different trails (D1-D6) that loop, connect and intersect through washes, and around canyon walls.  The Kodel Canyon side has even more trails (K1-K8?) that also intersect, mostly on top of a large ridge. The trails are all well marked, so if you\'ve got a map you\'ll have no trouble exploring here.  There are caves to peek in to, old miner cabins to photograph and views galore.  A popular area, you\'ll never be alone out here, but you\'ll definitely enjoy the hike.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/02/panorama-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(239,'Franktown','Colorado','Castlewood Canyon State Park','2-1978','To reach the main entrance of Castlewood Canyon State Park, take I-25 to Castle Rock, exit onto Founders Parkway eastbound. Take Founders Parkway to Hwy 86, go east on Hwy 86 four miles to Franktown. Turn South on Hwy 83 (S. Parker Rd) and go five miles south to the main park entrance.',39.361316,-104.768353,'Castlewood Canyon State Park is a Colorado state park near Franktown, Colorado. The park protects a unique part of Colorado\'s history (the Castlewood Canyon Dam). Nature lovers and groups enjoy environmental diversity on several hiking trails ranging from mild to moderate. The trails range from .5 to 4 miles and can be combined for longer journeys.  The winding Cherry Creek flowing along the canyon floor provides wonderful rest stops.  Pets, on a leash, are welcome on most trails, except the new East Canyon Preservation Area trail.',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/07/castle-060-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(240,'Snowmass Village','Colorado','Government/Brush Creek','2-1464','From I-70 take exit #116 to HWY 82. South on 82 for 35+ miles to Brushcreek Rd. Right or south on Brushcreek for approx. 5.5 miles to a split in the road, go right onto Divide Rd. and in over a mile a parking area on leftish.',39.19134,-106.85423,' The trail begins a short distance up Maroon Creek Road at Islen Park behind the tennis courts.  It continues across the river to Buttermilk Mountain.  The total trip of 7 miles (one way) to Snowmass Village winds through wooded areas and meadows.  This is a pleasant hike after a steep beginning.   Hikers MUST be careful to stay on the trail as it crosses private property.  Miles one way: 6.8.  Elevation: 9,400 ft. - 11,400 ft. (EASY - LONG)',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(241,'Estes Park, CO','Colorado','Chasm Lake','2-3179','Head South from Estes Park on Highway 7 for 9.2 miles. Turn right onto Longs Peak Road. This road ends at the Longs Peak Trailhead. If you don\'t get here early though, you may have to park a long ways away.',0,0,' The trail is well labeled and easy to find due to the traffic it receives. From the trailhead begin by following the route towards Longs Peak. Soon after breaking treeline you will come to an intersection where the Longs Peak trail goes right and the Chasm Lake trail goes left. There is a sign here labeling the trail for Chasm lake. (There is also a restroom here) Take this trail the rest of the way to Chasm Lake.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(242,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Pipeline Trail','2-728','Look up the directions to the Jones Park trail.  They share the same trailhead.  From where you park your shuttle vehicle (if you shuttled--highly recommended), instead of taking trail 701 to the left, go straight down trail 668--this is the pipeline trail.  ',38.7631,-104.96201,' Pipeline Trail is a 6 mile out-and-back trail near the city of Colorado Springs. This trail is pretty rocky in parts and it winds through dense forests, ever once in awhile opening up into a aspen covered field. You can sneak in some views of the surrounding mountains when the tree cover breaks.  Please share the path with mountain bikers and dirt bikers.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(243,'Frisco','Colorado','CDT CO27: Copper Mountain to Gold Hill','2-3284','CO',39.492413,-106.136015,' The CDT runs for 12.6 miles from Copper Mountain to Gold Hill Trailhead on Hwy 9. Along the way, the trail passes Peak 8, Peak 4, and Tenmile Peak.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(244,'Eldorado Springs','Colorado','Eldorado Canyon State Park','2-2161','According to parks.state.co.us, &quot;Eldorado Canyon State Park is located about five miles southwest of Boulder. Take Broadway / State Highway 93 south from Boulder, turn west (right) onto Colorado 170 and then continue about three miles to the town of Eldorado Springs. Highway 170 dead-ends at the town and a dirt road continues. The park is located at the end of the dirt road on the left. Our book store / visitor\'s center is one mile west from the park\'s entrance. &quot;',39.930838,-105.293074,'Eldorado Canyon State Park is a fantastic location full of sandstone cliffs, flowing creeks, picturesque mountains and the well known Eldo\'s golden cliffs. There are numerous (500 hundred plus) rock climbing options for many levels of skill. The park also offers several  trails of various skill levels from simple to difficult, all equally beautiful.  \r\n\r\nPicnicking, fishing, hiking, rock climbing, and cross-country skiing are all popular activities here. Camping is also offered near the park. Eldorado Canyon State Park just outside of Boulder, Colorado offers over 11 miles of hiking trails. The specific trails in the park are the Eldorado Canyon Trail, Rattlesnake Gulch, Fowler Trail, Streamside Trail, and Crescent Meadows. These trails offer up gorgeous views of the canyon, some of the streams, and the surrounding mountains. They vary in difficulty greatly depending on which trail you choose.  In addition to hiking, Eldorado Canyon is a very popular destination for Bouldering and Rock Climbing with over 500 technical rock climbing routes. Several of the trails are also open to mountain biking.',11,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/08/hiking-eldorado-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(245,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Santa Fe Trail','2-267','Numerous parking areas for this trail.  1. Take Woodmen Rd. West from I-25.  After the first bridge over the creek, turn right into the parking lot.  The trail goes north or south from here.  2. Access from the Air Force Academy is also possible via the north and south entrances.',38.93288,-104.81802,' Santa Fe Trail takes you through the communities of Palmer Lake and Monument, and then it turns onto the Air Force Academy territory. The trail is a really nice, wide multi-use trail that makes for an easy hike.  Please share the trail with other users.',30,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(246,'Fruita','Colorado','Prime Cut','2-840','Take 17.5 from town to N 3/10 road and hang a right. Turn left on 18 road and go until the pavement runs out, then stay on the dirt road for 4.3 miles and the trailhead is on the left. From the trailhead, ride on up the dirt road and take the jeep road on the right for about 100 yards down a hill, then  hit the singletrack going back to the left.',39.31065,-108.70598,' Prime Cut is 3 miles of climbing up singletrack, rocky steps, and boulders. It can be used as an out-and-back or you can connect to the other network of trails, like Joe\'s Ridge, to make it into a loop.  Please note that these trails are mainly used as mountain bike trails and there is a high amount of bike traffic in the area.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(247,'Golden','Colorado','Raccoon','2-6032','From GoldenTake Highway 93 north from Golden one mile to Golden Gate Canyon Road. Turn left and continue for 13 miles to the park. From the Denver Area using Golden Gate Canyon RdFollow I-70 west to exit 265 for highway 58. Take highway 58 west to highway 93. Turn right (north) on highway 93 for approximately 1 mile to Golden Gate Canyon road. Turn left and follow Golden Gate Canyon road 13 miles to the Visitor Center. The campground is approximately 5 miles from the Visitor Center( in the summer when Mountain Base Rd is open. In winter continue on Hwy 46 West 3 mi to Hwy 119 go north on Hwy 119 4mi to mile marker 15.5 approximately and look for Gap Rd on your right). RVs or vehicles towing large trailers must continue west to Hwy 119 all seasons. From BoulderTake highway 93 south to Golden Gate Canyon road. Turn right and follow Golden Gate Canyon road 13 miles to the Visitor Center. The campground is approximately 5 miles from the Visitor Center (in summer when Mountain Base Rd is open). RVs or vehicles towing large trailers must continue west on Hwy 46 to Hwy 119 all seasons. Turn north onto 119, at mile marker approx 15.5 turn right on Gap Road to access Reverend\'s Ridge and Aspen Meadow campgrounds.',0,0,' Located in Golden Gate Canyon State Park, the Raccoon loop trail starts behind the office at the campground. It starts at an elevation of over 9,000 feet and meanders through aspen trees, blue spruce, and douglas firs. The climax of the trail is when you reach Panorama Point which provides excellent views of the Continental Divide.',3,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/05/200_8733-292-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(248,'Morrison','Colorado','Red Rocks','2-8209','See Google Maps. There are many trailheads in the area, however, including at the Red Rocks Amphitheater.',39.6731,-105.20109,' The Red Rocks area, located around the Red Rocks Amphitheater, is a trail network that winds up the mountain sides above the Hogback and the city of Denver, and amongst the incredible red rock formations. These trails offer gorgeous views of the surrounding area and the unique rock formations, making for very entertaining hiking.',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/01/IMG_0091_1024x682-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(249,'Larkspur','Colorado','Greenland Open Space','2-1136','Coming from Monument Colorado, head North on I-25.  About 5-6 miles North of Monument take exit 167.  Turn left (west) and go under the interstate.  You will now be on Greenland Rd.  Follow this road for about 1 mile and you will reach the destination.  About .5 miles into the 1 mile road the road will make a hard left turn toward the south.  The road will run into the Greenland Open Space.  ',39.18072,-104.85364,' Part of the Colorado Front Range Trail, the lower trail joins into the Old Territorial Road, connecting the old Greenland Townsite to Palmer Lake. The 11-mile trail system is within over 3,000 acres of Greenland Open Space. The trail passes through native grasslands, by ponds, through rolling Gambel oak hills and skirts ponderosa pine forests. There are beautiful views of Greenland open space, buttes and Pikes Peak.',11,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(250,'Orchard','Colorado','Jackson Lake State Park','2-3612','From the U.S. 34/I-76 interchange, take Colorado Highway 39 north for 7.25 miles through Goodrich, then go west on Y5 (follow the paved road) for 2.5 miles.',40.379382,-104.089679,'This park is an &quot;Oasis in the Plains,&quot; for swimming, boating, fishing and waterskiing. But that\'s not all... Prairie Wetland Nature Trail is a 1/4 mile, self-guided trail and is located north of Cove Campground. There is also a 1.5 mile trail located between the Visitor Center north to Northview Campground. A trail is also located on the south side of the park from the south swimbeach to Cottonwood day-use picnic area. Folks also enjoy walking along the shoreline or along park roadways.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(251,'Cuchara','Colorado','Indian (1300)','2-1689','Take highway 12 south thru La Veta; on the south side of town you will find Forest Road 421 heading west into the mountains.  Take that road about eight miles or so till you find the obvious trailhead and parking area.',37.46008,-105.13122,' The Indian Creek Trail #1300 trailhead is located on the north side of the Bear Lake Campground. This trailhead is a multi user trail system and accesses 23 miles of motorized trails available for ATV, motorcycle, bicycle, foot and horse use. Follow these scenic ATV trails through the thick mountain forests and overlook the beautiful Spanish Peaks across in the east and the high Sangre de Cristos in the southwest. Remember to share the trail!',23,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(252,'Del Norte','Colorado','Penitente Canyon','2-1859','From Del Norte travel North on HWY 112 for aproximately 5 miles then turn left onto 33 (dirt road) follow thos for apprximatly 10 miles. There will be signs for the park on the left side of the road. There are 2 pulloffs for the park go to the second road and find a place to park. We parked at the intersection and biked in, but you can drive up the road to some camoing areas to park closer to the trailhead.',37.843,-106.28452,' Penitente Canyon offers gorgeous desert landscape with impressive sandstone cliffs. It is a true rock climbing destination, so don\'t expect to have the place all to yourself!',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(253,'Breckenridge','Colorado','CDT CO29: Georgia Pass to Argentine Pass','2-3286','CO',39.461158,-105.910275,' The CDT runs for 18.3 miles from Georgia Pass to Argentine Pass. Along the way, the trail passes Santa Fe Peak and Revenue Mountain.',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(254,'Dillon','Colorado','CDT CO31: Herman Gulch to Berthoud Pass','2-3288','CO',39.702428,-105.85426,' Section 31 of the CDT in Colorado runs for 20.4 miles from Herman Gulch to Berthoud Pass on US Hwy 40. Along the way, the trail passes Mount Bethel, Mount Parnassus, Woods Mountain, The Citadel, Pettingell Peak, Hassell Peak, Harrison Mountain, Vasquez Peak, and Stanley Mountain.',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(255,'Boulder','Colorado','Meyers Homestead Trail','2-117','From Boulder at the intersection of Broadway and Baseline, go 7.5 miles west on Baseline (which winds and turns all over up the mountains), and go right into the Meyers Gulch trailhead parking lot.',39.95795,-105.33859,' Meyers Homestead Trail is part of the Walker Ranch Open Space, about 9 miles out of Boulder. This out-and-back trail has beautiful foliage and you\'re likely to see a herd of elk grazing nearby. There are also interpretive signs along the trail that teach hikers about local history and ecology.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(256,'Creede','Colorado','CDT CO12: Spring Creek Pass Trailhead to San Luis Pass','2-3235','CO',37.939487,-107.15859,' The CDT runs for 14.3 miles from Spring Creek Pass to San Luis Pass. Along the way it passes Gain Snow Mesa, Baldy no es Cinco, and Baldy.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(257,'Boulder','Colorado','Heil Valley Ranch','2-116','From Boulder, go North on Highway 36 to Lefthand Canyon Road, turn left here.  Go about .5 mile to Geer Canyon Road, turn right here.  Go about 1 mile to parking lot.',40.14817,-105.30031,' With beautiful hanging valleys, picturesque vistas, and forest meadows that seem to cling to the sky, Heil Valley Ranch is a playground for wildlife. It only takes one visit to this 5,020-acre property to turn a sedentary person into an outdoor enthusiast. There are 5 trails located here ranging from easy to moderate with the longest trail topping out at 5.2 miles. Dogs are not allowed due to wildlife concerns.',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/04/heil_valley6-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(258,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Ute Valley Park','2-265','From I-25, exit at Woodmen Rd.  Go West.  Woodmen becomes Rockrimmon Rd.  Follow Rockrimmon Rd. approximately 1.5 miles.  Turn right onto Vindicator.  Go approximately 3/4 mile.  Parking lot on the left.',38.92501,-104.85697,' Ute Valley Park has 8 miles of trails that wind through desert terrain. Most of these trails are wide and are fairly easy to hike. You\'ll have plenty of chances to view the stunning scenery that surrounds the park. These trails are multi-use, so please share the path.',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/08/UTEPARK-JUL20-6-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(259,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Doubletop Trail / #405','2-8759','Access via Block &amp; Tackle Trail 545 off Cement Creek Rd. Also accessible via Caves Trail 409 further south on Cement Creek Rd.',38.85928,-106.80531,' 5 mile hiking trail located near Crested Butte, Colorado',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(260,'Buena Vista','Colorado','CDT CO23: South Clear Creek to Halfmoon Creek','2-3248','CO',38.960842,-106.460779,' Section 23 of the CDT in Colorado runs 28.2 miles from South Clear Creek to Halfmoon Creek. Along the way, the trail passes the Sheep Gulch Trailhead, Willis Gulch, Middle Mountain, Ervin Peak, Mount Hope, Quail Mountain, Twin Lakes, Hwy 82, and Mount Elbert (elevation 14,433), the highest peak in Colorado and the highest of the Rocky Mountains of North America.',28,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/07/IMG_0063.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(261,'Eagle Vail','Colorado','Eagle Vail Trail','2-2112','Turn off of Highway 6 in Eagle Vail onto Eagle Road.  Follow road past police station and turn right onto Eagle Drive.  Park at the first parking lot on the right, and then bike up Eagle Drive to the Cul de Sac (about 10 minutes).  Singletrack starts here and winds through an aspen grove to the junction with Pauley\'s Plunge.  Turn right at this junction and ride downhill on the last bit of Pauley\'s until you reach a footbridge at the golf course.  From here you will see a sign pointing uphill and to the left for the eagle Vail trail.  Continue riding until you filter out onto the road about 3 miles later.  Ride road east along Deer Blvd and Stone Creek Dr until you reach your car at the parking lot on Eagle Dr.',39.61263,-106.48312,' This trail winds through an aspen grove to the junction with Pauley\'s Plunge.  Turn right at this junction and hike downhill on the last bit of Pauley\'s until you reach a footbridge at the golf course.  From here you will see a sign pointing uphill and to the left for the eagle Vail trail.  Continue hiking until you filter out onto the road about 3 miles later.  Hike the road east along Deer Blvd and Stone Creek Dr until you reach your car at the parking lot on Eagle Dr.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(262,'Littleton','Colorado','Chatfield State Park','2-3620','The main entrance to Chatfield State Park is located one mile south of C-470 on Wadsworth. Make a left into the park from the traffic light (there will be a brown sign for Chatfield State Park).',39.54008,-105.086501,'Float your boat in the lake, bicycle or hike on a trail that provides scenic views of the neighboring foothills and Platte River valley, camp, ride a horse and even fly a model airplane - all at Chatfield State Park, nestled next to the foothills southwest of Denver. A series of trails wind through the Chatfield area and provides the park visitor with an abundance of recreational opportunities. You can take a morning jog, walk through natural areas around the reservoir, leisurely pedal your bicycle through the park or ride a horse into the sunset. Trail maps are available at the park\'s main entrances.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(263,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','FOUNTAIN CREEK REGIONAL TRAIL','2-8484','Fountain Creek Trailheads are located at Willow Springs, Duckwood Active Use Areawith Hanson Nature Park. Access to the trail is also available from the nature trails of the Fountain Creek Nature Center.',39.739304,-104.984632,'Starting along Fountain Creek at the El Pomar Youth Sports Complex in Colorado Springs, the trail continues south through the Fountain Creek Regional Park. Starting along Fountain Creek at the El Pomar Youth Sports Complex in Colorado Springs, the trail continues south through the Fountain Creek Regional Park.',0,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(264,'Denver','Colorado','Green Mountain--William Frederick Hayden Park','2-275','From I-25, take 6th Ave. west. Drive approximately 6 miles to Kipling. Take Kipling south for 2 miles before taking a right on Alameda. Stay on Alameda for 3 miles until you see a parking area on the right. This trail is part of William Frederick Hayden Park.',39.69666,-105.19224,' With more than 2,400 acres of open space, William Frederick Hayden Park on Green Mountain is the second largest park in Lakewood.  The park features a challenging network of multi-use trails. The summit, at 6,800 feet, offers unique and stunning views of the Denver metropolitan area to the east, as well as high mountain peaks to the west.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/275-1223987631.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(265,'Allenspark','Colorado','Calypso Cascades','2-3161','This trail is located in the Wild Basin region of Rocky Mountain National Park. The nearest town is Allenspark at the southeastern corner of the park. From Allenspark, head north on SR 7. The entrance to the park will be on the left. If you are coming from Estes Park, head south on SR 7. The entrance will be on your right.',40.209179,-105.56229,' This trail follows a raging stream for 1.8 miles up to the Calypso Cascades waterfall. It is a fairly easy hike gaining 700 ft in elevation. After just 0.3 miles you will meet up with Copeland Falls. Watch the water for long enough and you might see the water ouzel or the American dipper bird.  Along the way you\'ll be shaded by lots of pine and aspen. This is a nice hike with the relaxing sound of rushing water every step of the way.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-239-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(266,'Boulder','Colorado','Rattlesnake Gulch','2-947','It\'s in Eldorado Canyon State Park.  From Boulder, drive south on CO HWY 93 5 miles to CO HWY 170.  Take this west for 2.5 miles to the entrance to the park.  The trail head is on the south side of the road, a couple of miles into the park.  I park at the lot beyond the trail head, which is where this track is from.',39.93059,-105.29434,' A moderately difficult trail leading 1.4 miles (one way) past spectacular views of the canyon and eastern plains to the remains of historic Crags hotel, 600 feet above the trailhead. Built in 1908, the hotel was accessed via an inclined railway from the canyon floor until it burned down in 1913.  The trail continues as a .8 mile loop as it travels to a view of the Continental Divide and the railroad tracks, 1,200 feet above the trailhead. The trail is 1.4 miles to the ruins and another .8 mile for the loop, making the total roundtrip distance about 3.6 miles.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(267,'Mancos','Colorado','Petroglyph Point Trail','2-3154','Follow the main park road to the Chapin Mesa area and park at the museum.',37.185301,-108.488419,' A 2.4 mile loop starting at the Spruce Tree House, leading to petroglyphs and stunning canyon scenery.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(268,'Snowmass Village','Colorado','Powerline','2-1468','From I-70 exit #116 and take Hwy 82 towards Aspen, around 35 miles. Take Brush Creek Rd. 5 miles to Base Village. Parking is abundant.',39.19455,-106.93649,' Powerline features 3 miles of hiking trails near Snowmass Village, CO.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(269,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','Zig Zag','2-2039','Mt Werner Circle to Gondola Square.  Park in the garage.  ',40.45325,-106.77239,' Zig Zag is a 5 mile out-and-back trail at Steamboat Ski Resort. Enjoy a mix of singletrack, doubletrack, and gravel road, which winds up the mountain over rolling hills and along switchbacks. Hike through thick forests, but when the forests break you\'ll enjoy stunning scenery of the surrounding area.  This is a multi-use trail, so please share the trail.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(270,'Dinosaur','Colorado','Box Canyon Trail','2-3342','From Dinosaur, CO travel west on HWY 40 to HWY 149.  Turn North on HWY 149 and proceed through the entrance station.  Trail is located about 10 miles past the temporary visitor center.',40.42537,-109.17584,' Short pleasant hike along a dry stream bed to a small box canyon. Interpretative trail with occasional signs that give local natural and cultural information.',1,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/01/box_canyon_9-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(271,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Garden of the Gods','2-278','From I-25, exit at Garden of the Gods Rd.  Head West of G.O.D.G. Rd. and follow the signs to the visitor\'s center.  Park here and ride down under the highway into the park.  At the stop signed intersection in the park, trail starts on the left side of the road.  Signs for Ute trail.',38.87701,-104.87776,' There are numerous trails to hike at Garden of the Gods. Some of them are paved and crowded with tourists, and some of them are narrow singletrack that\'s more remote.   I have visited many natural places, and Garden of the Gods is close to the top of my lists of most beautiful places of all time! You have to experience the grandeur of these sandstone rocks!  Garden of the Gods is also very popular as a rock climbing and bouldering destination.',15,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/n516253446_606202_6025-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(272,'Fountain','Colorado','Fountain Creek Nature Center','2-8377','From I-25 Exit 132A, go east on CO 16 to US Hwy. 85, then south one-half mile. Turn west on Cattail Marsh Road to parking area.',38.713753,-104.715689,'Walk the wetlands, search for great blue herons, and explore Fountain Creek - only 15 minutes south of downtown Colorado Springs! An &quot;oasis on the plains&quot; with ponds marshes, meadows, cottonwood forests, and Fountain Creek, the nature center is attractive to visitors of all ages. The nature center offers a unique look into the Cattail Marsh Wildlife Area and serves as an entry to a variety of discovery experiences. Wetlands nature exhibit feature life in, on and around the water. Other exhibits include plants, wildlife, weather and climate, and the mountain backdrop. Interpretive programs, special events, group tours, and environmental education programs for schools are offered throughout the year. Walk the wetlands, search for great blue herons, and explore Fountain Creek - only 15 minutes south of downtown Colorado Springs! An &quot;oasis on the plains&quot; with ponds marshes, meadows, cottonwood forests, and Fountain Creek, the nature center is attractive to visitors of all ages. The nature center offers a unique look into the Cattail Marsh Wildlife Area and serves as an entry to a variety of discovery experiences. Wetlands nature exhibit feature life in, on and around the water. Other exhibits include plants, wildlife, weather and climate, and the mountain backdrop. Interpretive programs, special events, group tours, and environmental education programs for schools are offered throughout the year.',0,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(273,'Black Forest','Colorado','Black Forest Section 16 Trail','2-1671','This is not the same place as Black Forest Regional Park.  Just west of the intersection of Burgess &amp; Vollmer roads in Black Forest.',38.99898,-104.66885,' Black Forest Section 16 Trail is a square shaped loop in the Black Forest. It is a gravel path that provides a 4 mile circle with very little elevation change through the beautiful forest.  This area is popular with horseback riders so please practice trail etiquette.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(274,'Fruita','Colorado','Joe\'s Ridge','2-841','Take 17.5 from town to N 3/10 road and hang a right. Turn left on 18 road and go until the pavement runs out, then stay on the dirt road for 4.3 miles and the trailhead is on the left. If you just want to ride Joe\'s Ridge, keep going past the first trailhead for about 2 more miles to the upper trailhead and you can ride Joe\'s Ridge down to the first trailhead, then either take the road back or ride Prime Cut back up. Suggested route: Ride Prime Cut up to the top and the Joe\'s Ridge back to the first trailhead.',39.30414,-108.70466,' This 3 mile trail quickly takes you out to a ridge and then descends along the ridge. The trail is open and overlooks the beautiful desert area that encircles the trail. It can be hiked either as an out-and-back or as part of a network of trails.  Please note that these trails are mainly used as mountain bike trails and there is a high amount of bike traffic in the area.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(275,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Snodgrass','2-1003','Head north out of Crested Butte towards the resort, hang a left on Washington Gulch, and  the trail starts a couple miles down on the right.  Snodgrass runs between Washington Gulch and Gothic road, so you could start on either end, or loop it.  If you are riding it as an out and back, park down on Washington so you can do most of the climbing at the beginning.',38.91929,-106.96034,' Snodgrass isn\'t as steep or remote of a trails as many near Crested Butte. The trailhead is just a short drive from town, and it meanders through a beautiful aspen forest as it slowly climbs to the open meadows at the top of the ridge. For such a short little trail, that is close to town, this is really stunning!',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(276,'Durango','Colorado','Telegraph Trail System (south)','2-1576','The Sale Barn trail head is located across from the Home Depot on US550/160 (S Camino Del Rio) at the Southern end of Durango. There is a sign at the turnoff from the highway onto a frontage road. Pull into the gravel parking lot up the hill on the right.',37.22401,-107.85639,' Telegraph Trail System (south) is basically right in downtown Durango, making it a perfect place for a quick getaway! This network of loop trails will take you on switchbacks in and out of scenic canyons and along paths with low-lying desert scrub lining the trail. You\'ll also hike into wide open fields that showcase the mountains that surround you! These trails are multi-use and very popular with mountain bikers, so please share the trail!',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/02/IMG_0064-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(277,'Vail','Colorado','Buffer Creek','2-1526','Take Vail exit 176. Head West on the North Frontage Rd. Take a Right on Red Sandstone Rd. Follow the road up hill until you see a trailhead parking lot on the left. If it is full continue up hill until you see a dirt road on the left (this is the route on bike as well) You should find parking 3/4 of a mile up the road. Signs say snowmobile parking.',39.64846,-106.39609,' This 14 mile loop trail follows both a dirt road and some singletrack. There\'s a fairly long climb, but all the work pays off with scenic views of the Gorge Range and Vail Mountain.  This is a multi-use trail and is frequented by mountain bikers so please practice trail etiquette.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(278,'Creede','Colorado','CDT CO13: San Luis Pass to Eddiesville Trailhead','2-3236','While San Luis Pass is the southernmost point, the best place to park is the northern end: lat=38.026633, lon=-106.8344',37.971954,-106.971201,' The CDT runs for 12.7 miles from San Luis Pass to the Eddiesville Trailhead. Along the way the trail passes Spring Creek, San Luis Peak, Organ Mountain, and Table Mountain.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(279,'Divide','Colorado','Mueller State Park','2-1522','From Colorado Springs, take US 24 West to Woodland Park.  Continue on 24 to Divide, CO.  At the light in Divide, turn left onto State Hwy 67.  The park is about 5 miles on the right.  Costs about $4 to get in or $10 for a campsite.',38.885386,-105.157849,' Mueller State Park\'s 55 miles of trails provide a 5,000-acre playground for the hiker, mountain biker and wildlife watcher. Visitors are invited to explore the park\'s natural and historical resources via 55 miles of trails. Trails vary from short, leisurely walks to challenging, full-day hikes. The average elevation in the park is 9,600 feet.  All trails are open to hikers. Mueller has several short trails for the family to enjoy. Each trail ranges in distance from one-half mile to 3-1/3 miles round trip.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(280,'Mesa','Colorado','Flowing Park Loop','2-7971','From HWY 65 South turn right onto Land\'s End Road and then onto Flowing Park Road (#109 - first road on the left).  Follow this road until its end at Flowing Park reservoir.  You\'ll see a gated area just ahead.  The trail begins there.',38.96189,-108.10143,' Flowing Park Loop is a 14 mile hiking trail in Mesa, Colorado.',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/12/2013-07-14-11-23-55-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(281,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Stanley Canyon','2-762','Trail starts on the US Air Force Academy. From North Gate Dr. continue on Academy Drive, turn right on Pine Drive. Trailhead is at the end of the gravel road on the right of Pine Drive. ',38.988966,-104.898527,' Fairly steep and well traveled hike up to Stanley Reservoir with forest road connection to Rampart Reservoir. Very scenic hike.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/05/Stanley-Canyon-029-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(282,'Littleton','Colorado','Cherry Creek Lake','2-6051','On the southeast fringe of Denver off I-225/Parker Road.',39.651377,-104.855255,'Cherry Creek Dam, located at the southeast edge of Denver in Aurora, CO, was the first of the three dams to be built to protect the Denver region from catastrophic South Platte River floodwaters that plagued the area for more than 100 years. Recreational opportunities include camping, fishing, picnicking, an archery/rifle range, a horse stable, nature and bike trails, a marina, and a swimming area. The park is open year-round. Cherry Creek Dam, located at the southeast edge of Denver in Aurora, CO, was the first of the three dams to be built to protect the Denver region from catastrophic South Platte River floodwaters that plagued the area for more than 100 years. Recreational opportunities include camping, fishing, picnicking, an archery/rifle range, a horse stable, nature and bike trails, a marina, and a swimming area. The park is open year-round.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(283,'Idaho Springs','Colorado','Barbour Fork Loop','2-694','Take I-70 west of Denver to Idaho Springs exit #241 left on Miner Street just past Safeway , left on Soda Creek past the hot springs continue past the dump to the parking lot just before the forest service gate. About 3 miles total from I.S',39.71445,-105.55441,' Barbour Fork Loop is an OHV trail, open to hikers, that mainly winds throughout the wooded forests of the front country. The trail is not particularly scenic because it stays mostly within tree cover, but it\'s perfect for a walk in the woods. Enjoy the surrounding aspen forests, but be ready for a tough workout, because there are plenty of steep climbs along this trail.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(284,'Silverton','Colorado','Alpine Loop','2-8693','The trail is well marked and signposted.  From the car park at the trailhead (+10,000ft) at Eureka head up the trail to Animas Forks.  This about a 3.5 mile steady climb on a decent 4WD trail that takes you up to about +11,000 ft.  About 0.5 miles past Animas Forks you take a right turn following the signs for Cinnamon Pass.  From here the trail climbs more steeply over the next 3 miles to the pass (+12,630ft) with a few difficult rock sections.  Once at the the pass, enjoy the view as you are surrounded by 14,000+ ft peak!!!.  From the pass, the trail descends steeply at first with some rocky sections.  After about 2.5 miles the trail splits (CR 12), stay left.  From here you ride another easy 7.5 miles or so downhill until you reach Co Rd 30.  There are a few turn-offs on the right on the way but just stay left.  Turn left on Co Rd 30. Ride about 8 miles on a decent dirt road where the 30 forks left around Lake San Cristabal.  Ride around the west side of the lake until you reach the 149 turn left and head into Lake City.  You\'ve just completed about 24 miles of downhill with a drop of elevation to around 8,730ft - get ready for the uphill!!  At 1st St turn left, after a few hundred yards, fork left onto Co Rd 20.  There is now about 20 miles of climbing to get the Engineer Pass (+12,800ft).  The road starts off easy so enjoy the first 10 miles as you climb easily (after about 6 miles you pass the turn off to Co Rd 23 on the right).   After about 10 miles you reach a junction (Co Rd 24), here you need to take a left turn and continue on Co Rd 20.  From here the road starts to climb more steeply with rocky and heavily rutted sections.  After about 5 more miles you will reach another junction, stay right on Co Rd 20 and right again after about another mile.  Now the real climb begins about 4 miles from Engineer Pass.  You grind it out to the pass with a few sections that you may have to hike your bike.  At the pass, the road turns to the left and continues to climb (ouch) looping around the side of Engineer Mountain.  Enjoy the view, it\'s SPECTACULAR.  Continue to climb another 0.5 mile (+150 ft) and then start to descend.  There is a short uphill (downhill all the way after this) and after a mile you come to a junction.  Take a right and follow some switchbacks down another mile where you will pass a trail on the right.  Go straight on for about 0.5 mile to another junction where you turn left.  Carry on for another 2 miles to Animas Forks (passing to trail up to Cinnamon Pass you took earlier after about 1.5 miles).  From Animas Forks, take to trail downhill another 3.5 miles to the trailhead and car park.   ',37.88086,-107.56601,' 58 mile hiking trail located near Silverton, Colorado',58,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(285,'Boulder','Colorado','Betasso Preserve','2-90','From US36 in Boulder, go west on Canyon Rd approx 4 miles. Past the tunnel, turn right on Sugarloaf Rd. Go about a mile and turn right on Betasso Rd. The trailhead is about 1/2 mile or so on the left.',40.01575,-105.34418,' A couple loops to choose from with scenery ranging from wooded to open meadows to views of Boulder below. Not too crowded on weekdays and some of the trails are closed to bikes on Wednesdays and Saturdays.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/04/betasso3-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(286,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Ginny Trail','2-2019','Take Harmony Road thru town (exit 265 off I-25) past the Taft Hill Road intersection. At this point Harmony becomes CR 38E.  Continue past Horsetooth reservoir and Horsetooth Mountain Park until you get into Masonville.  Turn left at the Masonville Mercantile (CR27).  Take a quick right (only about 1/2 mile down) on CR 32C - marked for the Bobcat Ridge Natural Area.  Stay left and continue up the road to a large parking area with facilities.  The Ginny Trail starts on the left hand side thru the fence.',40.48117,-105.22391,' Ginny Trail is a 5.4 mile out-and-back hike that climbs 1,500 feet. The trail is open for hiking and mountain biking, but closed to horses. This hike takes you through a major burn area, which provides stunning views of the surrounding area for you! This is a multi-use trail so please share the path with mountain bikers.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(287,'Bailey','Colorado','Colorado Trail/ West Jefferson Trail','2-1831','Takw hwy 285 wert of Denver to Krnosha Pass about 20 miles past Baily',39.4142,-105.7586,' Start out at Kenosha Pass and follow the Colorado Trail to the West Jefferson Trail, which is about 11 miles in. You\'ll enjoy some beautiful trail that winds throughout this heavily forested area, and then you\'ll start to climb towards the timberline. Enjoy the views from up there! West Jefferson splits off and takes you down along a creek for some beautiful hiking through the woods.',23,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(288,'Castle Rock','Colorado','Ridgeline Open Space Trail','2-869','Take exit 182 from I-25 and head west for 1.5 miles.Turn right on Coachline Rd and go 1 mile.Turn left on Foothills Dr and go .4 miles.Turn left on Clear Sky Way and go .25 miles.park at Bison Park on the left and access the trail from any of several trailheads within a block or two of here.',39.38455,-104.90784,' These soft-surface trails travel through valleys and ridgelines of the 370-acre open space property. Visitors can take in views of the Front Range to the west and the Town below as they traverse open grasslands and dense Gambel oak.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(289,'Grand Lake','Colorado','Coyote Valley','2-3156','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Keep heading east and it will turn into Trail Ridge Road. Travel all the way down Trail Ridge Road. At the end there will be several winding curves. You\'ll then be heading south on the west side of the park. About 5 miles later the Coyote Valley Trailhead will be on the right.If you\'re traveling from the west side of the park just head north on 34. The trailhead is on the left.',40.348987,-105.85716,' This is a half mile one-way trail and is completely wheelchair accessible. It\'s a very easy, kid-friendly hike with no change in elevation. The path starts out at the Colorado River and winds through a big meadow following the river with interpretive signs and benches along the way. Elk are often seem grazing out in the meadow.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(290,'Fort Collins','Colorado','North Lone Pine','2-1620','Take US 287 north from Ft. Collins or south from Laramie, WY to Red Feather Lakes Road (CR 74E).  Go west 24-25 miles to Deadman Road.  Take Deadman Road 4-5 miles to the trailhead on left (well marked).',0,0,' The trail is relatively level at the beginning then ascends along North Lone Pine Creek. It passes a Forest Service experimental station plot, crosses the stream twice, and junctions with two old logging roads near some clear cuts before skirting east of North Bald Mountain and Middle Bald Mountain. Most of the trail is in mixed forest of lodgepole pine, spruce, fir, and aspen.  There are views of Red Feather Lakes and South Bald Mountain before the trail ends at Forest Road 517. Less than one half mile west on road 517, the south end of Killpecker Trail (#956) can be accessed. North Lone Pine trailhead accommodates approximately 5 vehicles.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(291,'Woodland Park','Colorado','North Catamount Reservoir','2-1059','There are a number of access points to North and South Catamount Reservoirs, but the easiest, in my opinion, is to head out of Woodland Park via Hwy 24 towards Divide.  Turn left onto Edlow Road, which is about 2.8 miles from WP, and take that all the way to the end (3.5 miles).  There is a parking lot with restrooms.',38.92517,-105.09612,' North Catamount Reservoir has 10 miles of hiking trails that skirt the lake and wind through the nearby forests. Enjoy beautiful views of the reservoir and the surrounding area.  These trails are open to mountain bikers as well so be sure to share the trail!',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(292,'Grand Lake','Colorado','Stillwater Pass','2-1669','From Grand Lake get on to Highway 34 heading South, as you near Lake Grandby there will be a sign on the right saying Stillwater Pass 1/4 of a mile away.  Take the next right and keep following this road.  The road will soon turn to dirt and there will be a parking lot on your right, drive past it.  Later on there will be a sign at an intersection with an arrow to the left says Idleglen Staging Area.  Take the left and park at Idleglen Staging area which is a little bit further and on the left.',40.25331,-105.83443,' There are plenty of different trails at Stillwater Pass, ranging form 4x4 trails to beautiful singletrack. Find trails that will take you into pristine meadows with beautiful marshes and streams, or climb trails through the forest to reach the mountaintop for stunning views.  Head out to the Granby Ranger Station or Grand Lake Visitor Center, grab a map, and explore!',110,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(293,'Mancos','Colorado','Spruce Canyon Trail','2-3153','Follow the main park road to Chapin Mesa and park at outside the Museum. Follow signs to the Spruce Tree House and the Spruce Canyon Trail.',0,0,' A 2.4 mile loop along the edge of the picnic area and Spruce Tree House cliff dwelling. This hike takes you down into Spruce Canyon where you follow along a creek within the canyon walls. Then you climb back up the canyon onto a mesa where you can overlook where you\'ve just been.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(294,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','NEW SANTA FE REGIONAL TRAIL','2-8286','Colorado Springs CO',38.833861,-104.821386,'The 14 mile portion of the trail follows the abandoned Atkinson, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad right-of-way.  The gravel surfaced regional trail generally follows a straight and level course fo the first 6.5 miles beginning at Palmer Lake.  An easement agreement by the U.S. Air Force Academy provides a crucial 6.9 mile stretch of this trail.  Trail users must not go off the six-foot wide trail surface as it passes through the Academy.  Bicyclists must wear helmets. The 14 mile portion of the trail follows the abandoned Atkinson, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad right-of-way.  The gravel surfaced regional trail generally follows a straight and level course fo the first 6.5 miles beginning at Palmer Lake.  An easement agreement by the U.S. Air Force Academy provides a crucial 6.9 mile stretch of this trail.  Trail users must not go off the six-foot wide trail surface as it passes through the Academy.  Bicyclists must wear helmets.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(295,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Upper Upper Loop','2-1973','Ride west out of town on Teocalli Avenue to connect to the Rec Path. This gravel path crosses Brush Creek and then becomes paved, and heads up to the town of Mt. Crested Butte, meeting Gothic Road at the entrance to town. Cross Gothic Road on the crosswalk, and keep following the Rec Path until you see Hunter Hill Road on your right. (You could ride this bit on the road ... but why?) Turn right on Hunter Hill Road, and right again at the next intersection again on Hunter Hill. Go down, then up past The Overlook turnoff. The singletrack starts at the first hard left switchback, where thereÃ¢ÂÂs a parking area and a trail sign.This is the beginning of Upper Loop. From here, you can connect to a bunch of trails, like Tony\'s Trail, Upper Upper Loop, Whetstone Vista, etc. ',38.89745,-106.96732,' This trail is easily accessible from town and offers up some great views of the surrounding region and access to some deep aspen groves. Some sections of the trail are smooth, and some are very, very rocky.',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/2-smooth-upper-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(296,'Lyons','Colorado','Hall Ranch','2-272','From Boulder, take US 36 / Foothills Hwy. north toward Lyons. Turn left on Hwy 66, then left on Hwy 7 / St. Vrain Rd. in Lyons. Trailhead is on the right.',40.21052,-105.28797,' Just west of the town of Lyons, you\'ll find the rolling grasslands and sandstone buttes of Hall Ranch. The over 3,000 acres of open space provides excellent viewing opportunities for wildflowers, animals, and scenic landscapes.  There are 5 trails ranging from moderate to difficult with the longest trail topping out at 4.7 miles. Dogs are not allowed due to wildlife concerns.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(297,'Dolores','Colorado','Boggy Draw Loop','2-1670','From Cortez, take Hwy 145 north 10 miles to Dolores.  In Dolores turn left on 11th St (turns into CR 31).  About 3 miles on 11th, and turn right on Road W.  East on W about 1 miles, cross the cattle grate and park in the lot in the left.',37.50195,-108.46566,' Boggy Draw Loop offers 9 miles of beautiful singletrack through scenic forests and meadows. This day hike will take you under tree cover and then out into an open field where you can overlook the surrounding areas. The elevation doesn\'t change drastically, which makes it a nice, quiet day hike.  This is a multi-use trail so please practice trail etiquette.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(298,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Soapstone Natural Area','2-991','Soapstone Prairie Natural Area (25 miles, one way) From Fort Collins take Hwy 1/ Terry Lake Road north, turn left onto County Rd 15 and travel north to Rawhide Flats Road. Turn right (north) onto Rawhide Flats Road and follow it to the Soapstone Prairie Natural Area entrance station.',40.9438,-105.08409,' Soapstone is extraordinary with over 28 square miles of wide open vistas, nearly pristine grasslands, miles of trails and world-renowned cultural resources. The most popular recreation activities on natural areas are hiking or walking, wildlife watching and relaxing. A great benefit of being in a natural area is the stress relief one experiences, which is brought on by the warmth of the sun, fresh air, birds, grass blowing in the wind, and the sights, sounds and smells of nature.',30,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(299,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Doctor Park','2-2187','From Gunnison, take highway 135 north to Almont, take a right on the Taylor River road (Forest Road 742), continue past the Spring Creek Road for about a half mile and turn left into the North Bank Campground.  Go thru the campground to the end of the road to find the trailhead.  From Crested Butte, go south on highway 135 and take Jacks Cabin Cutoff, which will put you on the Taylor River Road just west of Spring Creek Road.',38.82525,-106.72741,' Doctor Park takes you through high alpine forests where the trail winds through beautiful aspens. At points the path leads out into open fields where you can take in stunning views of the surrounding mountains and valleys. Climb this trail up to the ridge and enjoy some great views. This is a multi-use trail so please keep an eye out for mountain bikers, and practice trail etiquette.',19,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(300,'South Fork','Colorado','Trout Creek Trail','2-2111','To get to the trailhead from South Fork travel West on HWY 160 for approx 3 miles. The trailhead is on the right side of the highway in an open meadow with a livestock loading chute in the middle of it.',37.636,-106.67391,' Trout Creek Trail is an incredibly scenic trail with wild raspberry bushes lining the trail and wild mint filling the air. The trail leads you along beautiful singletrack up to a meadow that\'s a perfect place to enjoy a little picnic.  This is a multi-use trail so please share the trail!',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(301,'Leadville','Colorado','Black Cloud Trail','2-8797','Twin Lakes',39.0693,-106.43373,' 6 mile hiking trail located near Leadville, Colorado',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(302,'Fruita','Colorado','Rabbit Ears Trail','2-8593','Take I-70 west to Exit 2, Rabbit Valley.  Turn left across the interstate and then turn left again on the frontage road.  Go east on the frontage road 4-5 miles and look for a sign for &quot;Rabbit Ears&quot; and a small parking area on the right.',0,0,' Trail is a lollipop.  It climbs for the first two miles (go left at trail fork) to an overlook, then wraps around the top of a mesa for a mostly flat to downhill walk back to the intersection.  Beautiful views of the Colorado River, Bookcliffs, etc.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2015/01/15539169533_23088c64cb_o.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(303,'Golden','Colorado','Apex Park','2-300','From the I-25 and 6th Ave. intersection in Denver, go west on 6th. As you get close to the foothills, you will drive under I-70.After the underpass, take your first left at the stoplight.You will be turning onto Hwy. 40. Drive on 40 for about a mile.  Pull into the Heritage Square parking lot on your right, and park on the north side next to the trailhead.',39.71646,-105.20924,' Apex Trail is in the Jefferson County trail system, and the eastern access is in the City of Golden. The trail is 2.3 miles long gaining up to 1,500 feet in elevation. There are exposed steep trails at time with views of Denver and Golden.  Apex Park also features the Enchanted Forest Loop, at 5.6 miles round-trip, which features gentle slopes and scenic views of the forest. The Pick N\' Sledge loop is also available, at 4.4 miles, but it is mainly used as a mountain bike trail. These trails are multi-use so please practice caution.',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/04/IMG_0544-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(304,'Del Norte','Colorado','CDT CO05: South River Peak to Squaw Pass','2-3212','Closest easily-accessible trailhead is Wolf Creek Pass: 37.4828, -106.7999',37.565184,-106.974619,' The CDT runs 23.5 miles between South River Peak and Squaw Pass. Along the way the trail passes Piedra Peak, Knife Edge, Cherokee Lake, and Chief Mountain.',24,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(305,'Fruita','Colorado','Colorado National Monument','2-2917','For travelers going westbound through the Grand Valley: Take Highway I-70 to Grand Junction, and take Exit 31 (Horizon Drive). Follow signs through Grand Junction to the east entrance.For travelers going eastbound through the Grand Valley: Take Highway I-70 to Exit 19 (Fruita) and go south on Highway 340 to the west entrance, which is approximately three miles from Fruita. The visitor center and campground are four miles up from the west entrance.Source: National Park Service',39.10077,-108.734471,' Colorado National Monument\'s trails offer many opportunities for hikers. Bird watchers and photographers discover the splendor that they traveled so far to find. Hikes range from only 0.25 mile to over 14 miles. Source: National Park Service',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Colorado-NM-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(306,'Silverton','Colorado','CDT CO10: Stony Pass Trailhead to Carson Saddle Trailhead','2-3233','CO',37.794382,-107.546073,' The CDT runs for 16 miles from Stony Pass Trailhead north to Carson Saddle Trailhead. Along the way it passes Canby Mountain, Half Peak, Tundra Top, Cataract Peak, Carson Peak, and Bent Peak.',16,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(307,'Evergreen','Colorado','Dedisse Trail','2-603','From I-70 west of Denver, take Evergreen Parkway/HWY 74 to Upper Bear Creek Road [ just before the lake] Turn right follow Upper Bear Creek about 1/2 mile turn left and park at the lake house.',39.63142,-105.33285,' Dedisse Trail is a fairly easy out-and-back trail that\'s perfect for a family with children or a leisurely day hike. Walk through deep forests, with beautiful boulders and rock formations, and enjoy the views of the lake along the hike.  This is a multi-use trail so please be aware of mountain bikers and practice trail etiquette.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(308,'Pagosa Springs','Colorado','CDT CO03: Elwood Pass to Wolf Creek Pass','2-3200','CO',37.405417,-106.64417,' Section 3 of the CDT in Colorado runs for 17.6 miles from Elwood Pass to Wolf Creek Pass. Along the way it passes Bonito Pass, Silver Mountain, Silver Pass, the Wolf Creek Ski Area, and Alberta Peak.',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(309,'Ward','Colorado','South Saint Vrain','2-1084','From Nederland, go north on 72/peak to peak highway.Roughly 3 miles north of Ward take a left on 96(Beaver Res. Rd on google maps).  Right after you get on 96 there will be the trailhead on the left, the large sign for the trail is about 20 feet or so off the road so its not VERY apparent, I drove clear past it the first time.  Just park along the road.Here\'s a link to google maps.http://maps.google.com/maps?f=d&amp;source=s_d&amp;saddr=W+2nd+St%2FCO-72&amp;daddr=Beaver+Res+Rd%2FCounty+Rd-96&amp;geocode=FczHYQIdFAi2-Q%3BFcv1YwIdGmO2-Q&amp;hl=en&amp;mra=ls&amp;sll=40.040232,-105.45639&amp;sspn=0.313312,0.705872&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;t=p&amp;z=11',40.10542,-105.48834,' From County Road 96, the South Vrain Trail climbs west along South Saint Vrain Creek. In about two miles, the trail follows an old road, then turns off to the right (north) and climbs to avoid private property. At the top of this climb, the trail crosses an old road with signs to the Stapp Lakes. The Stapp Lakes are on private property with no public access. At 3.1 miles, South Saint Vrain Trail crosses the Sourdough Trail. The trail continues gently along a little ridge for another mile to an intersection with the Waldrop Trail. The trail drops down and crosses a creek before the Brainard Lake Cutoff Trail forks left (south). The South Saint Vrain Trail crosses a meadow to reach the Mitchell Lake Trailhead spur road north of Brainard Lake.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(310,'Antonito','Colorado','CDT CO01: New Mexico Border to Blue Lake AP','2-3198','CO',36.993826,-106.457117,' Section one of the Continental Divide Trail in Colorado runs 30.3 miles from the New Mexico border, past Cumbres Pass (and the trailhead there), past Three Lakes, Past Dripping Lakes, and it ends at a trailhead near Blue Lake. The Google Maps location given is for the point where the CDT crosses the New Mexico/Colorado Border. A better parking spot would be further north at Cumbres Pass: lat=37.01797644, lon=-106.450062146 Or you could park at the northern end of this section: lat=37.238152, lon=-106.628989',30,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(311,'Fruita','Colorado','Turkey Flats','2-1640','Coming from Fruita or Grand Junction: Go through Colorado Natl Monument and take the road to Glade Park. Drive to intersection where you will find the glade park store on corner. Take road 16.50 south( you will pass a campground on right @ ~ 7 miles)   the road will fork at 8 miles stay right( sign for fruita resevoirs). Come to a picnic area on left side of road at 10 miles. Park in the lot. ',38.85538,-108.77973,' Turkey Flats is a 10 mile loop trail near Fruita, CO. This trail will lead you through beautiful aspen meadows on smooth singletrack, and every once in a while you\'ll get stunning views of the surrounding valley and the mountains in the distance.  This is a multi-use trail, so please share the path.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(312,'Pagosa Springs','Colorado','Brockover Mesa','2-3252','CO',37.291355,-107.105657,' Expansive network of trails up the mountains from Pagosa Springs in the San Juan National Forest.',100,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(313,'Grant','Colorado','Mount Bierstadt','2-2137','Take 285 from Denver to the town of Grant. Turn right onto Guanella Pass Road and drive about 13 miles up to the top of the pass. The trail begins there.',39.592382,-105.715323,' This may be one of the easiest and most accessible 14ers in Colorado, and as such it\'s a really popular route. That doesn\'t mean it\'s not worth the hike, though! The trail climbs up from the pass about 3.5 miles until it tops out on Mount Bierstadt at 14,060 feet after an elevation gain of 2,850 feet. The lower section of the trail is pretty flat as it approaches the main climb. It runs through some shrubby trees that are very short, since it is already over 11,000 feet. As soon as the trail starts climbing you rise above the tree line, and while it does climb up a peak, the trail isn\'t too steep or technical. Towards the top of the ridge right before you reach the summit, there are a few boulders that you have to scramble up but they aren\'t difficult at all. The views on this hike and from the top are absolutely incredible! Definitely bring your camera! Also, please note that this trail does enter the Mount Evans Wilderness. Please be aware of all of the special wilderness regulations.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/07/n516253446_591567_1360-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(314,'Red Feather Lakes','Colorado','Mount Margaret','2-73','Take Highway 287 North from Fort Collins to to Livermore. Turn west on 74E for 22 miles to the trailhead. The trailhead is on the right side of the highway. ',40.7796,-105.53767,' The trail crosses South Lone Pine Creek then meanders through meadows, sparse stands of lodgepole and ponderosa pine trees, and granite outcroppings. Five designated campsites, each with a bench, enclosed fire pit and grill, have been established within the first 2.5 miles for use on a first-come, first-served basis. The trail often follows old logging roads. It passes through an area known as Five Points which is the intersection of five roads/trails. At least one trail originates in Dowdy Lake Campground, and others are loops off the main trail.  Several more designated, dispersed campsites can be found along these routes. The trail continues past Five Points for nearly 2 miles to the base of Mount Margaret overlooking a deep canyon, North Lone Pine Creek and the Prairie Divide Road. Mount Margaret trailhead accommodates approximately 23 vehicles.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(315,'Salida','Colorado','Waterdog Lakes','2-8601','Off of Hwy 50 near Monarch Park',38.53127,-106.32401,' The Water Dog Lakes trail is about 2 miles one-way or 3.7 miles round-trip. This trail climbs about a thousand vertical feet on the way up to the lake, but the pristine beauty of this high alpine lake is definitely a sight to behold!',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2015/01/2014_12_18_0085_.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(316,'Telluride','Colorado','Prospect Trail','2-1573','You can start the trial from the top of the free Gondola.  Ride the Gondola up from Mountain Village or downtown Telluride.',37.93116,-107.83299,' Prospect Trail starts at the top of the free gondola from Mountain Village. This hike follows a well-maintained trail that winds through the thick forests. Ever now and then it will cross with some ski trails, where you\'ll be able to get stunning views of the surrounding mountains and the town down below. Please share the trails with mountain bikers.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(317,'Vail','Colorado','Commando Run','2-1088','Exit off I-70 at Vail and find a place to park.  From there bike to the closest mountain access point (they change frequently).',39.56343,-106.26868,' You\'ll be climbing up a lot of 4X4 trails on this hike. Go about 1.5 miles in until you see Chair 10, and then stay left. You\'ll keep climbing from here until you reach Benchmark at about 10 miles in. Turn right here and then after about a quarter mile, you\'ll see a spur trail off to your left, and you\'ll want to take that.  Climb to the top and take in the stunning views of the mountains and the valley below. All of that climbing is worth it!',20,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(318,'Durango','Colorado','Spruce Tree House Trail','2-4392','Travel to the far end of Mesa Verde National Park along HWY 10.  Park in the main lot.  Several trail begin from same parking lot, so look for signs',37.18358,-108.48776,' Short hike down across a canyon to one of the cliff dwelling houses this park is famous for.  This is one of the easier to access houses that does not require climbing.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/01/spruce_tree_trail_1-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(319,'Calhan','Colorado','Paint Mines Interpretive Park','2-1413','highway 24 to Calhan, south on Yoder and east on Paint Mine Rd.  There are several parking areas for the park.',0,0,' Hidden in the eastern prairie is a unique geological feature referred to as the Paint Mines.  Consisting of colorful clay deposits there is evidence of early activity in this area making it of historic interest as well.  The &quot;hoodoos&quot; are well worth the stop.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/05/IMG_2300-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(320,'Durango','Colorado','Dry Fork Trail','2-398','From Durango, take US 160 West about 3 miles and turn right onto Lightner Creek Road (County Road 207).  Go about a mile and turn right onto Dry Fork Road (County Road 208).  After about 2 miles, go right at the Y intersection, park at the trailhead on the left after about a mile.  Ride up the trail and take the left turn at the first intersection onto Dry Fork trail.  When you hit the Colorado Trail, take a right, then a right onto Hoffheins to complete the loop.  You\'ll climb about 1200 feet over the 4 or 5 miles to the top.',37.33109,-107.93862,' This 9 mile trail winds through the beautiful forests of Durango. Aspens shade this trail, and create a great atmosphere for a relaxing hike. All along the trail there are beautiful views of the surrounding area, which make this hike incredibly scenic. It does tend to get crowded, even on the weekdays, but don\'t let that stop you from enjoying the trail! This is a multi-use trail, so please practice trail etiquette.',9,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/398-1223989654.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(321,'Superior','Colorado','Marshall Road Open Spaces','2-148','Heading South from Boulder on HWY 93, take a left heading East on Marshall Road.  The trail parking lot will be on your right hand side.  You cannot miss it.  Heading from Denver, take US 36 heading northwest until you get to the Superior/Layfette exit.  On the off-ramp intersection take a left heading south.  You will pass back over the high way and take a right at the intersection heading toward Wild Oats and Super Target.  This Road will turn into Marshall Road.  You will stay on this road heading west for about 5 miles.  The Marshall Road turn off will be on your left after you pass the cattle range.  If you hit HWY 93 you have gone to far.  Turn around and look for the trailhead on your right.',39.94898,-105.1694,' Marshall Road Open Spaces has a variety of trails totaling 7 miles just outside of Superior, Colorado. This area mostly has a desert feel and the trails run through wide open grassy plains providing beautiful views of the Flatirons.  Some of these trails are open to mountain bikers so please be aware and share the path.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(322,'Buena Vista','Colorado','Midland Bike Trail','2-1494','From Hwy 24 in Buena Vista, go east on Main St.  (This is at the stoplight)  Go about 1 mile to a park on the Arkansas River.  That is the trailhead.  ',38.84657,-106.12238,' This is one of the most popular mountain biking routes in Buena Vista. The ride starts with a fun stretch of singletrack that climbs up from the Arkansas River. At the top, you\'ll find spectacular views of Mount Princeton and the southern Arkansas Valley from the old Midland Railroad grade along CR 304. Once you turn east, the trail returns to singletrack that slices through narrow stone cuts and drops into diversions that wind down through draws once spanned by rail trestles. The trail is approximately 7.3 miles from trailhead-to-trailhead, but it\'s possible to shorten the ride by turning back sooner.  Hiking is allowed here, but remember that this trail is meant for mountain bikers. Please practice trail etiquette and share the path.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2015/01/2014_08_09_0088_.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(323,'Highlands Ranch','Colorado','East-west Regional Trail','2-1692','Currently the main access and parking is in Highlands Ranch; trail will eventually extend to Lone Tree and Parker. Take C-470 south to S. University Blvd, right on Wildcat Reserve Pkwy, left on McArthur Ranch Rd. to Griggs Rd. Drive south 2 miles to trailhead on left. Or from Santa Fe take Daniels Park Rd. north 5 miles to Griggs Rd.; trailhead on right.',39.5038,-104.94147,' This is the first leg of the East/West Regional Trail that will connect Chatfield State Park with the Town of Parker. The trail winds through grasslands and oak bluffs including thousand of acres of the Open Space Conservation Area.',16,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(324,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Pulpit Rock Park','2-7869','take I-25 to the Nevada Exit and head east.  Once ease of I-25 turn left on to the frontage road and head north.  Take road until it ends and you will see the pulpit rock parking lot.',38.91857,-104.81378,' Pulpit Rock Park is a 6 mile hiking trail in Colorado Springs, Colorado.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(325,'Fruita','Colorado','Kessel Run','2-878','Take 17.5 from town to N 3/10 road and hang a right. Turn left on 18 road and go until the pavement runs out, then stay on the dirt road for 4.3 miles and the trailhead is on the left. From the trailhead, ride on up the dirt road up to the Joe\'s Ridge/Prime Cut junction and kessel will be on the left.',39.32281,-108.70635,' This hike starts out winding through some desert trees and descending down the mountain. It\'s a fairly quick hike that can be rocky at times, but it\'s a great place to get out and stretch your legs. Use it as an out-and-back trail or connect to the other network of trails at the end.  Please note that these trails are mainly used as mountain bike trails, and there is a high amount of bike traffic in the area.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(326,'Loma','Colorado','Highline Lake State Park','2-1893','Drive west on I-70 west from Grand Junction to Loma Exit, then north onto Colorado Highway 139 for six miles to Q Road. Go west on Q road for 1.2 miles, then turn north onto 11.8 Road for one mile to the East park entrance.',39.270308,-108.836226,'An oasis in the desert, Highline Lake is the recreation epicenter for the Grand Valley with two lakes, lush grass, trails and trees. Several trails circle Mack Mesa Lake and Highline Lake. The park is close to the well-known Kokopelli trail complex and the newer, North Fruita Desert Trails bike trail complex. There are a total of 7 trails, mostly loop trails, ranging from easy to difficult with the longest trail topping out at 6.42 miles. Remember to share the trail!',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(327,'Florissant','Colorado','Florissant Fossil Beds National Monument','2-2920','DIRECTIONS: Visitors traveling north/south on I-25: Exit at US 24 West, travel 35 miles to town of Florissant, then follow signs two miles south to the visitor center on Teller County 1. Visitors traveling east/west on US 24: Exit to the town of Florissant, then follow signs two miles south on Teller County 1 to the visitor center. Visitors traveling from the town of Cripple Creek: Follow Teller County Road 1 north for 16 miles. TRANSPORTATION: To Park: access by US Highway 24 and Teller County Road 1.Source: National Park Service',38.913529,-105.286083,' There are over 14 miles of hiking trails in the Monument. Most of the trails wind through pine covered hills with patches of Aspen and Douglas Fir. Some of the trails pass wet meadows or through riparian areas. Source: National Park Service',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Florissant-Fossil-Beds-NM-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(328,'Estes Park','Colorado','Cub Lake','2-3149','Enter Rocky Mountain National Park from the main entrance at Estes Park. Go past the Beaver Meadows Visitor Center and turn left onto Bear Lake Road. Turn into the Moraine Park Campground. Then take Fern Lake Road to the left. This road takes you to the Cub Lake Trailhead, below the campground.',40.35798,-105.604578,' This trail is 2.3 miles one way to Cub Lake. With an elevation gain of only 540 ft it\'s a great introductory hike to the park. You\'ll first cross a bridge over a river, then meander along on a dirt path with lots of pines and aspens on either side. There are beautiful streams and ponds along the way and cascading cliffs overhead. Once you get to Cub Lake you can then either turn around and go back or continue on to Fern Lake.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/200_8888-482-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(329,'Steamboat Springs','Colorado','Spring Creek','2-45','Lincoln Ave (US 40), East on 5th St 2 blocks.  Angle onto Maple St. continue to Amethyst.  Park on the side of the gravel/dirt road.  ',40.48657,-106.8178,' The Spring Creek Trail is a 5.2 mile, multi-use trail that is popular for hiking and biking with residents and visitors of Steamboat. The trail becomes a classic single track on City of Steamboat Springs property for the next 1.5 miles, climbing gently along the creek. The last 1.4 miles of the trail continues to climb in the Routt National Forest to the end of the trail at Dry Lake Campground, off of RCR # 38, Buffalo Pass Road. Please share the trail.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(330,'Fruita','Colorado','Mary\'s Loop/Horsethief Bench','2-1454','Take I-70 to exit #15. The Kokopelli trailhead parking lot is just off the exit on Frontage road. From the parking lot, ride up the hill on the gravel road into the valley. Ride down the gravel road, the trail will be climbing jeep road on the right just before the rustlers loop parking area.',39.17765,-108.8277,' This trail has plenty to keep you interested. From the beautiful overlooks where you can view the Colorado River, to the rock scrambles, to the wide open valley. This canyon hike will leave you satisfied. Watch out for mountain bike traffic!',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(331,'Denver','Colorado','Dakota Ridge','2-268','Take I-70 west out of Denver. Go past the 470 exit, and take the very next exit for Morrison. At the end of the exit, take a left (south) onto Colorado Hwy 26 at the light. Go under the I-70 overpass, and the park will be on your right 100 yards later. Trailhead is on SE side of the lot.',39.69448,-105.20493,' Dakota Ridge is an extremely rocky trail high on the Hogback between Denver and the front range. This is a very entertaining trail with rocks and staircases all over the place and some serious exposure on the tops of cliffs. Expect incredible views of Denver and the front range.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/268-1223999287.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(332,'Delta','Colorado','Sweitzer Lake State Park','2-3619','Sweitzer is located one mile south of Delta on U.S. 50. Follow the signs turning east on E. Road.',38.712388,-108.040408,'It started out as a community dream.  This lake based retreat for the Western Slope provides day-use nature, picnic and water recreation. 1 1/2 miles around the lake on dirt and gravel roads.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(333,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Glen Eyrie','2-325','Go west to the end of Garden of the Gods Road and turn south onto N 30th street, 3820 N. 30th St. On the right before you get to Garden of the Gods.',0,0,' As of right now, because of the Waldo Canyon Fire, they are not allowing any public access to hiking trails.  The trails are located at the Glen Eyrie Castle.  You must get a hiking permit during the hours they are open to the public (see the official website: http://www.navigators.org/us/ministries/gleneyrie/).  The trails go through some canyons and there\'s a nice waterfall and pond.',20,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/325-1221502603.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(334,'Nederland','Colorado','West Magnolia','2-491','From Nederland, take 119 South for about 1 mile.  On the West side, across from Magnolia (County Hwy 132) is the trailhead.',39.9502,-105.50445,' West Magnolia Trailhead provides access to eight miles of singletrack trails for hiking, biking and horseback riding west of the Peak-to-Peak Highway south of Nederland. An additional eight miles of Forest Roads that connect to Rollins Pass Road west of Rollinsville are open to motorized and non-motorized activities.  The network of interconnected trails offers many different loop opportunities with a range of difficulty levels. It is possible to connect this system of trails with the Front Range Trailhead via a short segment of Magnolia Road east of Colorado Highways 72/119.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(335,'Evergreen','Colorado','Bergen Peak','2-532','Drive west on 1-70 to the evergreen parkway exit colorado 74 and travel through bergen park to elk meadow park. Pass lewis ridge park  and turn right on stage coach blvd. follow the signs to the parking lot',39.6632,-105.35863,' Bergen Peak trail starts off fairly flat winding its way through a beautiful meadow. Following that the climb starts, there are a few steep sections, but most of the ascent consists of switchbacks. The official top of the trail doesn\'t offer much in the way of views because of it\'s surrounded by trees, however there is a rocky outcropping nearby that has amazing views for hikers to enjoy.',10,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(336,'Boulder','Colorado','Mount Sanitas','2-1474','Take Mapleton Ave. west until it turns into Sunshine Canyon Dr. Look for parking on either side of the road. There\'s also a small parking lot on the left side of the road just past the marked trailhead on the right.',40.020762,-105.294707,' Classic Boulder hike with incredible views and within walking distance of downtown Boulder. The Sanitas Trail climbs a tall ridge with sweeping views to the east and west. Also be sure to hit the Sanitas Valley Trail, a wide, gradual path just east of Mt. Sanitas.',4,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/03/photo19-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(337,'Golden','Colorado','Mount Galbraith Park','2-8574','From State Highway 93, take Golden Gate Canyon Road west approximately 1.5 miles to the parking area and trailhead.',0,0,' Come for the challenging terrain, stay for the views. Mount Galbraith Park is a hiker-only destination, boasting nearly five miles of steep, rocky trails that reward the hardy with commanding views of Golden, the plains and the Continental Divide.  The Mt. Galbraith Loop circles 1.6 miles around the top of the 7,260-foot peak. In addition to the vast and varying landscape, keep your eyes peeled for the elk, bighorn sheep, red-tailed hawks and songbirds that frequent the area.   Mount Galbraith is flanked by Clear Creek Canyon and Golden Gate Canyon, which were vital passageways into the Central Rockies for Native Americans and settlers. Miners climbed the mountain to access the western territories during the California gold rush of 1849, as travel was easier along the ridgelines than through dense drainages.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/05/014.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(338,'Winter Park','Colorado','Cr-81 To Rendezvous','2-7936','From the top of CR-81 (FSR 128) Down Twisted Ankle to Whoops trail, Whoops to Idlewild, And into the Winterwoods Loop, Which turns into Serendipity. Serendipity to Crosstrails, Crosstrails to Homestead which Spits you out in Rondezvous, which if you follow the road down, will land you right on the main road halfway between Winter Park and Fraser closer to the Winter Park side. ',39.92886,-105.75402,' Cr-81 To Rendezvous is a 3 mile hiking trail in Winter Park, Colorado.',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(339,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Farris Creek','2-1001','from Crested Butte follow the New Deli trail out to South Crested Butte, only a couple of miles; then follow the county road (Brush Creek Road) out past the trailhead to Cold Spring Ranch, about 2 miles; there is a right turn up a fairly steep hill, approx 1/2 mile beyond Cold Spring Ranch; on completing the trail you end up on this county road, follow it back to South CB and then CB itself',38.86532,-106.87414,' The Farris Creek trail is 6.1 miles long. It begins at Forest Road 740 and ends at Forest Road 736. The trail is open for the following uses: Hiking, Mountain Biking, Horseback Riding, and Motorcycle Trail Riding. This out-and-back trail crosses open plains, revealing the tall mountains rising around you, and it also winds through thick, secluded forests. It\'s a perfect place to get outside, but remember to share the trail!',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(340,'Hayden','Colorado','Elkhead State Park','2-3631','From Craig, go seven miles east on Highway #40 turn left onto County Road #29.  Signs will direct you to Elkhead Reservoir, approximately 3 miles.',40.562529,-107.389158,'Elkhead State Park in the beautiful Yampa Valley of Northwest Colorado is an oasis in the high desert. Elkhead State Park in the beautiful Yampa Valley of Northwest Colorado is an oasis in the high desert. This 900 acre reservoir provides endless recreational opportunities. They include, but are not limited to, boating, swimming, jet skiing, skiing, picnicking, wildlife watching, hiking, camping, meeting friends and neighbors, bird watching, biking, horseback riding hunting and fishing and many photo opportunities. Hike along one of a variety of trails that follow the lakeshore. Although many are short hikes, they can be very rewarding to the conscious viewer.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(341,'Woodland Park','Colorado','Lovell Gulch','2-330','From Colorado Springs, take I-25 and Hwy 24 West towards Woodland Park.  Once in Woodland Park, turn right at the McDonalds onto Baldwin Rd.  Head straight through several stop signs for about 2 miles.  There will be a sign to turn left into the parking lot for the Lovell Gulch Trailhead, which is adjacent to an animal shelter.',39.01302,-105.04443,' Lovell Gulch is an nice 5 mile loop trail that has relatively easy climbs but stunningly beautiful views. Hike through dense forests and skirt large granite boulders along the trail. Dive down into some small valleys and then hike along a ridge that showcases Pikes Peak and the Sawatch Range.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/05/cdv_photo_002-1.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(342,'Eagle','Colorado','Haymeadow Trail','2-8823','From I-70, exit 147, go south into Eagle.  Go right at the roundabout onto Grand Ave then take the 2nd left onto Capitol St.  Follow Capitol through the old part of Eagle.  After emerging from the old part of Eagle, you will reach a 3-way stop--go left here onto Brush Creek Rd.  Follow Brush Creek Road through some residential development and it will loop around and dead end at the Eagle Pool and Ice Rink.  Park here--the trail leads due south from here.  Be sure to ride the trail counterclockwise.',39.64283,-106.8148,' 6 mile hiking trail located near Eagle, Colorado',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(343,'Rifle','Colorado','Rifle Falls State Park','2-3611','Take I-70 to the Rifle exit (90), then go north on CO Highway 13 for four miles. This takes you through the town of Rifle on Railroad Ave. Turn right onto Highway 325 and drive 9.8 miles.',39.674266,-107.700369,'Rifle Falls State Park\'s lush vegetation and waterfalls have attracted photographers and movie crews from around the country who come to capture the area\'s unique scenery. Three unique hiking trails meander along the creek and through luxuriant riparian area throughout the park. They provide access to the caves, the top of the falls, and the creek upstream and downstream from the park. The Bobcat Trail follows Rifle Creek to the Colorado Division of Wildlife\'s Fish Hatchery. See the Trails section for complete trail descriptions. Please use caution as parts of the trails are steep and can become slippery when wet. Come prepared with sturdy hiking boots and plenty of water.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(344,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Independence Monument','2-5822','The lower entrance to Independence Monument can be difficult to locate.  Take Hwy 340 west.  You\'ll drive through the Redlands area, past Independence Valley subdivision and into a more rural area.  Just past an intersection with Deer Valley you\'ll approach a curve to the right with a large house sitting on the left.  What looks like a driveway right here on the left is actually the turn off to your trailhead.',0,0,' From the trailhead you\'ll hike behind houses for a bit before the trail turns and begins winding its way into the Monument.  The trail is well-maintained and not very steep.  It\'s about 2.5 miles to the Independence Monument monolith.  If you hike further you can see other formations like the Coke Ovens and Kissing Couple.  If you\'re quiet you might also see Bighorn Sheep!',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/04/5188_199664640284_5109730_n-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(345,'Kremmling','Colorado','CDT CO39: Troublesome Pass to FR104','2-3296','CO',40.332806,-106.212097,' The CDT runs 11.4 miles from Troublesome Pass to FR104. Along the way, the trail passes Poison Ridge, Sheep Mountain, and Hyannis Peak.',11,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(346,'Allenspark','Colorado','Finch Lake','2-3352','Located between the towns of Meeker and Allenspark on Colorado route 7 (Peak to Peak Scenic Highway). Watch for signs.',0,0,' Located in the Wild Basin Area of Rocky Mountain National Park, this trail leads 4.6 miles out to the secluded and pristine Finch Lake. You\'ll hike through thick forests and wide open fields to get to your destination, where you\'ll be able to look out over across the lake to the Continental Divide.  There are backcountry camping spots available around Finch Lake, just in case you wanted to get away for a little while longer.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-285-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(347,'Sedaila','Colorado','Ringtail-swallowtail','2-958','Hikers and horse riders may access from Sharptail Ridge Trailhead. From Hwy 85 (Santa Fe) turn west on Titan Parkway and drive 2 miles to Roxborough Road; turn left and drive south for 3.7 miles on gravel road; Sharptail trailhead on the left. NOTE: Hikers and horse riders accessing from Sharptail Trailhead must travel approximately 8 miles before reaching the eastern end of Ringtail Trail.Multiple users, including mountain bikes and pets on a leash, can access from the Indian Creek Trailhead of Pike National Forest; however access from Indian Creek Trail does require a daily parking fee of $4 (7/04 price). Note: From the Indian Creek Trailhead to the western end of Ringtail Trail is a distance of approximately 5.7 miles.',39.40735,-105.04986,' Ringtail-swallowtail climbs up into the beautiful and scenic Pike Hill Open Space in the Pike National Forest. The trail winds through forests and when it reaches the Open Space you get stunning views of the surrounding area! Please share the trail with mountain bikers.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(348,'Craig','Colorado','Cedar Mountain','2-8874','Cedar Mountain is accessed by taking U.S. Highway 40 west from Craig 1 mile, turn right on (County Road 7), go north for 5 miles then turn right on Cedar Mountain Access (BLM Route # 2190). http://www.blm.gov/co/st/en/fo/lsfo/programs/recreation/cedar_mtn.html',40.57484,-107.61734,' 3 mile hiking trail located near Craig, Colorado',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(349,'Leadville','Colorado','CDT CO26: Tennessee Pass to Copper Mountain','2-3251','CO',39.363239,-106.311899,' Section 26 of the CDT in Colorado runs 24.6 miles from the trailhead at Tennessee Pass / US Hwy 24 to Copper Mountain / Hwy 91. Along the way, the trail passes US Hwy 24, Sheep Mountain, North Sheep Mountain, Elk Mountain, Jacque Peak, and Copper Mountain Ski Resort.',25,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(350,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Holy Cross','2-1659','See the Pet-a-Kes trail for directions to the trailhead.',39.05025,-108.60449,' Located in the Redlands area of Grand Junction, this trail is a fun hike full of climbing around boulders and enormous trees. Enjoy the desert landscape that the trail winds through, but know that this trail was built for mountain bikers.  Remember to share the trail and practice trail etiquette.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(351,'Highlands Ranch','Colorado','Monarch Backcountry','2-528','Take Wildcat Reserve and make a right onto McAurther Ranch Parkway, than make another right on To Monarch and than travel for a little over a mile, after a turn in the road there is a very small driveway into a parking lot on the left side enter the lot slowly. You can only ride this trail if you have a Highlands ranch Rec card. ',39.51439,-104.92011,' This is a private trail for the residents of Highlands Ranch.  The trail takes you past low-lying desert shrubs, through beautiful prairie fields, alongside small ponds, and it provides awesome views the whole way. This trail is open to mountain bikers as well so be sure to share the trail!',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(352,'Morrison','Colorado','Trading Post','2-3354','15 miles west of Denver. Coming from Downtown, take I-70 west to exit 259, turn left at the bottom of the Morrison exit ramp, cruise on downhill 1.5 miles to the Red Rocks Park entrance. Coming from south Denver, take C-470 to the Morrison exit, turn west and follow the signs to the Park entrances.',0,0,' The Trading Post Trail goes through spectacular rock formations, valleys and a natural meadow. The trail is 6,280 feet above sea level. The majority of the trail is less than 30 inches wide.',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/08/300_8888-424-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(353,'Ouray','Colorado','Sutton Mine Trail','2-8600','Departing Ouray on Highway 550 south, turn right after the first switchback onto the Camp Bird Road (CR 361). The trailhead will be found on the left, about half way up Jim Brown Hill (the more or less straight part of the road where you can look down on the town of Ouray, to the right). There is limited parking at the trailhead. If full, park near the powder house below the bridge over the Uncompahgre.',0,0,' The trail starts off with a half mile of very steep switchbacks, but then flattens.  At 2 miles you\'ll reach the Bear Creek Overlook and at 2.5 the Neosho Mine.  Beautiful views!  Take a trekking pole.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/06/bearcreekfalls.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(354,'Del Norte','Colorado','CDT CO06: Squaw Pass to Weminuche Pass','2-3213','Closest easily-accessible trailhead is Wolf Creek Pass: 37.4828, -106.7999',37.601922,-107.217515,' The CDT runs for 12.9 miles between Squaw Pass and Weminuche Pass. Along the way the route runs past the Squaw Lake Trail and Snowslide Trail.',13,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/02/531284_10151903733185285_1116448988_-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(355,'Snowmass Village','Colorado','Tom Blake Trail','2-1467','From I-70 exit #116 and take HWY 82 towards Aspen. At Brushcreek Rd. turn R and proceed uphill until you reach Base Village at Snowmass, parking is abundant. From here, are several options to access the mountain to Tom Blake Trail. Grab a free trail map at any of the bike shops in the area.',39.20736,-106.95482,' Tom Blake Trail is a 6 mile trail that leads you through thick forests where you\'ll see beautiful aspen trees. This trail is perfect for a quiet stroll through the woods! This trail is multi-use, so please share the trail!',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(356,'Leadville','Colorado','CDT CO25: Timberline Lake to Tennessee Pass','2-3250','CO',39.284805,-106.446828,' Section 25 of the CDT in Colorado runs just over 13 miles from Timberline Lake to Tennessee Pass on US Hwy 24. Along the way, the trail passes Galena Mountain, West Tennessee Creek, Homestake Peak, and Missouri Hill.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(357,'Salida','Colorado','Arkansas Hills','2-2190','there are three ways to get in to the town of Salida, from Colroado 291 from Buena vista. hwy 50 from Poncha Springs and hwy 50 from canyon city. from Salida look for F street and go over the F street Bridge. the road ends and leads you in to a parking area. From there you must bike over railroad tracks. You can take the Front Side Trail or Bike up to CR 177. ',38.53805,-105.98992,' This is the closest trail system to downtown Salida. The trail system is a combination of 11 hiking and biking trails that range from 0.4 miles to 3.2 miles in length. There are several access points and all trails are well-maintained and well-marked.  These trails are multi-use trails so please practice caution.',15,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/12/IMG_0221-hdr_1024x682-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(358,'Palisade','Colorado','Palisade Rim','2-1177','Park by the Colorado River along US 6 near the mouth of DeBeque Canyon.',39.11621,-108.32022,' Palisade Rim is a beautiful out-and-back trail that you can connect with other trails in the network to make a loop. The trail follows along the rim and the edge of the cliffs, giving you an amazing view of the surrounding area. This trail is shared by mountain bikers so please share the path.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(359,'Lake George','Colorado','Eleven Mile SP','2-3594','From Colorado Springs take Hwy 24 west for 38 miles through Lake George. West of Lake George, turn left (south) on County Rd 90 and follow it for four miles. From that point, continue south on County Rd 92 for six miles to the park.',38.935378,-105.501733,'Eleven Mile SP is esteemed for its outstanding fishing. Eleven Mile is also a popular site for sailing, windsurfing, boating, hiking and camping. \r\n\r\nThe park offers nine campgrounds, five miles of hiking/biking and a convenient equipment rental center for boaters and ice-fishers. It\'s a great location for a variety of activities and scenic views. Eleven Mile SP is esteemed for its outstanding fishing. Eleven Mile is also a popular site for sailing, windsurfing, boating, hiking and camping.   The park offers several hiking trails with various levels of difficulty. Some of which are the  self-guided Nature Trail and an Orienteering trail. The trails offer beautiful meadow views, wildlife sightings and a backcountry peninsula view.',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(360,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Thunder Pass','2-7962','From Fort Collins, CO drive up Hwy 14, the Poudre Canyon, until you get to Cameron Pass about 60 mi from town. Park at the summit parking lot and ride across the road to the Michigan Ditch TH. There is a fee station just ahead $3.00/person',40.52013,-105.89182,' Thunder Pass is a 12 mile hiking trail in Fort Collins, Colorado.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(361,'Bellvue','Colorado','Brown\'s Lake Trail','2-8845','right off of crown point road',0,0,' 8 mile out and back. Located near Bellvue, CO. This trail is great for backpacking, camping and fishing!',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(362,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Pet - A - Kes','2-1658','This trail starts along with all the other Tabeguache/Lunch Loops trails.  From Grand Junction, head west on Broadway aka Hwy 340.  Turn left on Monument road and follow it about a mile to the parking area on the left.',39.05012,-108.60432,' Pet-A -Kes is a 1 mile climb within the lunch loops trail network. Traverse rocky climbs to get to the top of this trail, and then take in the beautiful desert scenery it provides. You\'re sure to love this trail, and plenty of other people do too, so make sure you look out for other hikers and bikers and you share the trail!',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(363,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Elk Park Trail','2-481','Go to the Pikes Peak Toll road and park right outside the gate.  Get you 10$ per person ready and flag a truck to carry you and your bikes up the road.  Go .5 miles past Glen Cove and pull off the left to a parking area.  It\\\'s the only Trailhead.',38.87573,-105.073,' Elk Park Trail is an 11 mile out-and-back trail close to the Barr Trail on the famous Pikes Peak. Cross streams, scale mountains, and wind through forests along this scenic trail. It offers great views and gets you away from some of the crowds on the Barr Trail. This is a multi-use trail so please practice trail etiquette.',11,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(364,'La Junta','Colorado','Bent\'s Old Fort National Historic Site','2-2913','The park is accessed via U.S. Highway 50 and Highway 194. From La Junta, Colorado on U.S. Highway 50, take Highway 109 north 1 mile to Highway 194, then east on Highway 194 six miles to the fort. From Las Animas, Colorado, on U.S. Highway 50, take Highway 194 west 13 miles. Set your GPS to 35110 State Highway 194 E., La Junta, CO.Source: National Park Service',38.044685,-103.433668,' Visitors can hike a mile and a half trail that winds its way through the cottonwood trees alongside the Arkansas River. The marsh is home to several species of birds. Interpretive exhibit signs tell the story of the river ecosystem, Santa Fe Trail and Bent\'s Fort.  Source: National Park Service',2,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Bents-old-fort-NM-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(365,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Bear Creek Canyon Loop','2-190','From I-25, take US 24 West to 21st St. Turn left onto 21st street, then right onto Lower Gold Camp Road. At the four way stop, turn left onto Bear Creek Road. Park on the side of the road at the end of Bear Creek Road or the parking lot at the caretaker\'s home at the end of High Drive.',38.79039,-104.90355,' This loop trail is difficult with a 2,200 elevation climb in the first 4 miles. Be ready for a great workout, but also enjoy this beautifully forested trail that has awesome overlooks where you can view the surrounding mountains. The downhill also features some creek crossings as well.  This is a multi-use trail so please practice caution as there is some mountain bike traffic here.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(366,'Salida','Colorado','Mount Princeton Trail','2-8657','Princeton',38.73626,-106.21371,' 3 mile hiking trail located near Salida, Colorado',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(367,'Loveland','Colorado','Devils Backbone','2-130','Starting from Taft and Eisenhower (highway 43) head west on highway 34. The has 2 lanes in each direction, the road will go down to one lane in each direction. The trail head is just a few minutes from this point. You will see a coffee shop (The Black Cup) on the right, after this bend you will see an old water tower on the right with a road before it. Turn right on this dirt road and you will see the a large Devils Backbone trailhead sign.',40.41164,-105.15243,' This trail goes on for at least 8 miles, and eventually connects up with several other trails in the area, but you only have to hike a mile or two to reach the Devil\'s Backbone. The Backbone is a line of rocks sticking out of the ground that looks like a bony spine. You\'ve got to see this in person!',8,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/10/resized_r_IMG_2466-0-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(368,'Littleton','Colorado','Colorado Trail / Waterton To South Platte','2-955','Begin at the Waterton Canyon parking lot.  This lot is about 4 miles south of C-470 on Wadsworth Blvd.  It is easy to spot because the trail and parking lot is usually quite busy.',39.49136,-105.09323,' The first 6 miles of this section tends to get a little bit crowded. It\'s very popular for day hikes, so you\'ll find plenty of families and children climbing the trail. Head up to &quot;sitting bench&quot; and you\'ll break through the crowds a little. Continue to hike through beautiful forests and along rocky outcroppings, and enjoy the views!',34,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(369,'Eagle','Colorado','The Boneyard','2-7927','From I-70 Eagle exit 147, follow first roundabout to right and make 1st left on Capitol St.  2 blocks then left on 3rd, go 1/2 mile and turn left on Mill Rd. (parking lot is on the left.  ',39.65609,-106.81743,' The Boneyard is a 7 mile hiking trail in Eagle, Colorado.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(370,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Falcon Trail','2-276',' I-25 to Northgate of Air Force Academy Non-Military Entrance - Exit 156B. Once you go through security, take your first left onto Stadium Blvd, then a right onto Academy Dr. -- Parking lot at the top of the hill on the right side of the road (near the stadium).',38.97395,-104.87754,' This beautiful trail tours the grounds of the US Air Force Academy. The trail traverses wide open prairies and secluded low mountain woods. It\'s a great place to get some sights in while enjoying nature.  This is a multi-use trail so please be respectful, also expect a possible car search at the gate.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(371,'Franktown','Colorado','Hidden Mesa','2-784','From Castle Rock take Highway 86 east toward Franktown.  Turn left at Parker road and continue on for approximately 1 mile.  Hidden Mesa Open Space will be on your left.',39.43866,-104.77142,' Hike this 1224-acre open space buffer between Castle Rock and Franktown.  Embark on this soft-surface trail from the trailhead at the old homestead at Parker Road. Follow the farm lane as it crosses over Cherry Creek and then winds up to the top of the mesa where it loops around viewpoints, rock outcroppings, grass and shrublands, as well as pines and junipers.',7,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(372,'Del Norte','Colorado','CDT CO07: Weminuche Pass to Twin Lakes','2-3214','Closest easily-accessible trailhead is the Beartown Trailhead: lat=37.712333, lon=-107.518005',37.668497,-107.332609,' The CDT runs for 10.5 miles from Weminuche Pass north to Twin Lakes. Along the way the trail passes Lavaca Creek, Ute Lake, Rio Grand Pyramid, and Window Peak.',11,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/02/6449_205149990284_6351646_n-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(373,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Heiser To Barr','2-46','Take Hwy 24. to Cascade. Turn Left at &quot;Pikes Peak&quot; light.  Take the first second left after you turn left.  If you miss the 2nd left, take the third.  Go up the road less than 1/4 mile to the park.  Jump on your bike and head on the small road going north/east.  Follow this road 1/8 mile to the trail head.  There are Private Property signs, but they apply to the driveways, not the road your on',38.8952,-104.97273,' Heiser To Barr Trail is a difficult uphill climb to the pristine Manitou Reservoir. Once you reach the reservoir you start to head back down and the trail meets back up with the Barr Trail.  This is a hard 14 miles so make sure you\'re prepared and have plenty of water!',14,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/04/IMG_2349-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(374,'Roxborough','Colorado','Roxborough State Park','2-3627','Take Wadsworth south past Chatfield State Park. Turn left on Waterton Road (just before the entrance to Lockheed Martin.) Continue on Waterton Road-crossing the South Platte River, until it ends at North Rampart Range Road (1.6 miles) Turn right (south) on North Rampart Range Road. Continue south past Roxborough Village and the Foothills Water Treatment Plant. (2.3 miles) At the intersection of North Rampart Range Road and Roxborough Park Road (just before the entrance to Arrowhead golf course), turn left onto Roxborough Park Road. Take the next right on East Roxborough Drive(about 50 yards away) to enter the park.',39.450119,-105.07042,'More than a million Denver-area residents have one of nature\'s jewels in their backyard: Roxborough State Park, a short drive southwest of Denver. Roxborough State Park offers a variety of trails for all abilities, from the half-mile Fountain Overlook trail that affords a spectacular view of rock formations, to the challenging 6.4-mile trek to 7,160-foot Carpenter Peak.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(375,'La Junta','Colorado','Picket Wire Canyon','2-1355','From La Junta go south on H109 and then turn on to CR802 into the Comanche Grass Lands. South on CR25 and follow the signs toward Withers Canyon trail head. After this it is recommended for a high clearance vehicle, but this was not needed on our trip.',37.66117,-103.56877,' Long and mostly flat hike leading towards a historic mission, 1/4 mile stretch of dinosaur tracks, and a historic ranch.',17,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2010/05/IMG_0257-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(376,'Edwards','Colorado','A-10','2-2769','From I-70 Exit 163 take Edwards Access Rd. south to Hwy 6.  Turn left and go @ 1 mile to Miller Ranch Rd. (light) making a left, park @ one of the two schools.  Ride back across the Blue-light bridge and go left at the traffic light, continue riding to Arrowhead (on right) and climb up the road to the base of the chairlift and start of the trail.',39.63422,-106.5652,' Enjoy the views of Gold Dust Peak and the surrounding mountains while climbing up Arrowhead Mountain on this beautiful 8 mile loop trail. Hike through high meadows, oakbrush, and aspens, and enjoy a few creek crossings as well.  This trail is has a high amount of mountain bike traffic so please use caution.',8,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(377,'Fruita','Colorado','Pollock Bench / Canyon','2-3094','From I-70 exit in Fruita, CO, turn left and cross the Colorado River.  Turn right onto King\'s View court.  Follow the road past Devil\'s Canyon and the Fruita Paleo trailhead to Pollock Canyon on the left.  There is a sign that says &quot;dead end in 3/4 mile&quot; right at the parking area.  The Pollock Bench trail, which overlooks Pollock Canyon heads up and to the right just past the map/register area.',0,0,' After a mostly uphill start, the trail flattens out and loops around the rim of Pollock Canyon with views into this to the south and Flume Canyon to the west.  Follow the signs for P1 clockwise or counterclockwise to complete the lollipop.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/06/DSCN0633-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(378,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Deer Creek','2-2125','To ride it from Brush Creek, start from town and ride south on the bike path that parallels highway 135. Turn left on Brush Creek Road (County Road 738) and pass the entrance to the Skyland. Keep riding out Brush Creek Road for about five miles. At this point, youÂll cross Brush Creek on a good bridge and start climbing on the road. YouÂre passing through private ranchland here, so keep to the road. The road continues to climb and becomes rougher. At the &quot;Y&quot;, stay left and begin climbing more steeply on West Brush Creek Road. The right takes you up East Brush Creek and Pearl Pass. The climb gets a little tougher at this point, then levels out before coming to another split in the road. Take another left onto Deer Creek Road. Right takes you further up West Brush Creek toward the Teocalli Ridge Trail (another classic ride).There are wooden signs at these intersections directing you. Deer Creek continues to climb up a rough double track. Go through a gate at the top of this climb and continue about 1/4 of a mile to another split in the road. Go left again and ride steeply down down through some aspens. Follow the doubletrack through a boggy area to its end, where the Deer Creek singletrack begins. The trail is very distinct and buffed along here.After two creek crossings, the trail starts to climb steadily and steeply. See how long you can stay on your bike. IÂve seen a few very strong local riders ride all the way to the top of this one. It is a major push. At the top, whether youÂre walking or still riding, youÂll love the view of the upper East river valley and the back of Crested Butte Mountain. This is a great place to recover and have bite to eat. If youÂre lucky, youÂll see elk grazing in the aspen groves uphill from you.From here, the trail weaves and bobs its way along the flanks of Whiterock Mountain. There is everything you could want in a singletrack for the next seven miles. The trail is usually in great shape early in the summer. Later on, cows can hammer the trail if it rains a lot. There are a couple tricky places where the cows regularly make side trails. The first is right after you cross the wide and rocky Perry Creek at 13 and 1/2 miles. The main trail climbs up out of the creek and through the aspens a very short distance and turns sharply right to climb through a meadow. DonÂt be tempted to stay low and straight ahead on the well worn cow path!Again, at mile 15, after you start a steady and switchbacking descent through a meadow and then into the aspens, the trail makes a sharp turn back to the left and climbs quickly for 100 feet or so to avoid a boggy area. (Several cowpaths go straight down.) Next, follow the trail down the creek and to the right, crossing a couple small creeks and heading out into the open meadows, Gothic Mountain in view straight ahead. Follow this gradually rolling section through the meadows to the final descent. At one point (mile 17.3) the trail veers hard left at some private property. There is a sign here, donÂt miss it! Continue to the left through the meadows, then curve right and down to a doubletrack. Take a right on this rough road and ride out to Gothic Road (the main gravel road). Turn left on Gothic Road, cross the East River and begin riding back toward town. After a gradual, three mile climb, top out on the road climb above Mount Crested Butte. Still feeling strong? You can ride the Snodgrass Trail (just to the right) on the way back. Or you can continue on the fast road back to town.',38.91091,-106.89045,' The Deer Creek trail is 7.6 miles long. It begins at Forest Road 582.1 and ends at Forest Road 956.2. The trail is open for the following uses: hiking, mountain biking, horseback riding. Hike through dense alpine forests along beautiful singletrack and enjoy the high alpine views that are available on this trail.',15,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(379,'Conifer','Colorado','Chair Rocks','2-656','Go 6.8 miles south of Conifer on US285 to Pine Valley Road (just a couple of miles past Schaffers Crossing) and turn left (southeast).  ThereÃ¢ÂÂs a light and a turn lane at Pine Valley so itÃ¢ÂÂs hard to miss.   Go about 10 miles to the town of Buffalo Creek.  Keep going just about another four miles and look for the Parking Lot on the right.  ',39.34449,-105.25727,' A mix between singletrack and doubletrack, this trail leads through a burn area left by the Buffalo Creek Fire in the \'90s. The trail follows along a section of the Colorado Trail to Chair Rocks and an overlook of the South Platte area. The hike is very scenic. This trail is a multi-use trail so please watch out for mountain bike traffic, and practice trail etiquette.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(380,'Copper Mountain','Colorado','Copper Triangle','2-2154','Take I-70 into the mountains and exit towards Copper Mountain. Park at any one of the number of parking lots in Copper Village.',39.50181,-106.15373,' Copper Triangle is about 30 miles of trail alternating between smooth singletrack and wide 4x4 road, double track, and paved roads. The trail quickly connects with the Colorado Trail on its climb up. Here you\'ll hike through thick, beautiful forests until you reach the tree line. Above the tree line you\'ll enjoy incredible views of the surrounding area.  This trail is a multi-use trail so please be on the lookout for mountain bikers.',30,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(381,'Salida','Colorado','Bear Creek/Methodist Mountain Loop','2-1687','This loop is a Salida mainstay. This trail has it all, a grueling gut-buster of a climb, sweet singletrack, a technical decent, and some pavement to round things out. The loop can begin/end at any number of locations. The following description starts in downtown Salida. However many people begin their journey at a pullout on CR 101 3.2 miles from US Hwy 50. By the way, the rainbow trail is dirt bike friendly so don\'t be shocked if you see a few.',38.52416,-105.99695,' Right near town, the Bear Creek/Methodist Mountain Loop takes you up steep climbs, but rewards you with beautiful views of the Arkansas River Valley. After you make the brutal climb up there is a quick descent down a fireroad that leads you back into town. This trail meets up with the Rainbow Trail which helps to make it a loop.  This is a multi-use trail so please practice caution.',18,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(382,'Loveland','Colorado','Round Mountain Foothills Nature Trail','2-964','From Loveland, head west on 34.  Once you enter they canyon and pass under the huge water pipe, go for 3.8 miles and the Round Mountain trail head is on the south side of the road.',40.42018,-105.28525,' As you stroll up the road to the overlook, you will discover Ponderosa Lane. The Ponderosa Pine is the most common tree in this area. In the plains below, few plants grow higher than the grasses and sagebrush, and spruces and firs take over in the Montane Life Zone at higher elevations.  To take this trail, there is a split in the main trail shortly after leaving the parking lot (about a 1/4 mile in) which allows you to continue on with the Foothills Nature Trail or instead go on to the summit of Sheep Mountain on the Round Mountain National Recreational Trail - Summit Adventure Trail portion, which is much more difficult and is rated as a Moderate difficulty level.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(383,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Dadd Gulch','2-893','Take HWY 14 west from Fort Collins up Poudre Canyon for 29 miles from US 287 junction.  Trailhead on left.',40.69817,-105.54017,' The trail follows a stream and an old stock trail up the gulch for about two miles before leaving the stream and passing through woods and meadows. A stock watering tank may be seen on the left just above the meadow. The upper portion of trail provides several panoramic vistas.  The trail ends at Salt Cabin Road, a forest road that loops north off Crown Point Road (forest road #139). This is a multiple use trail and is a favorite of mountain bikers and horseback riders as well as hikers and backpackers. Lower Dadd Gulch trailhead accommodates approximately 15 vehicles.',7,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/07/cdv_photo_002-2.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(384,'Fort Collins','Colorado','Michigan Ditch','2-992','From Fort Collins Head North on 287 to HWY 14 (Teds Place) Go up HWY 14 for approximately 70 miles to the Cameron Pass Parking lot. Its right at the summit. On the right as you arrive from the east. Across the street you\'ll see a gate over a very well maintained road. This is the start of the trail. ',40.51996,-105.89334,' Michigan Ditch is a fairly flat loop trail that follows jeep roads and fire roads into the wilderness. As you hike along you\'ll get excellent views of the Never Summer Mountains in Rocky Mountain National Park, and the Nokhu Crags.  There are some steep drop-offs right beside the trail and there are bears and mountain lions in this area, so be careful!',5,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(385,'Idaho Springs','Colorado','Centennial Cone Park','2-486','From Idaho Springs take I-70 east to Hwy.6 exit #244.east on Hwy 6 to Hwy 119 turn left [north] drive 1/2 mile to Douglas Mountain Road turn right it\'s about a mile to Centennial Cone Park. You can also take Hwy 6 west of Golden 11 miles to Hwy 119',39.7499,-105.38313,' Hike through the remains of many farms and homesteads in this Open Space Park. The trail takes you on top of the ridges above Clear Creek and offers beautiful views.  This is an incredibly scenic trail, and it\'s definitely a must-see if you\'re in the area. It is a multi-use trail so please practice caution.',13,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(386,'Fairplay','Colorado','Sheep Creek','2-1623','From Fairplay, CO, head south on 285 about five miles to Co Rd 5 heading west.  After about five miles on Co Rd 5, this road turns into Co Rd 22, take the right spur.  A half mile or so later, take Sheep Creek Trail (Co Rd 455) road on the right.   Follow this to forest Dr and go left.  The road ends at a parking lot for the trail.  ',39.10868,-106.10898,' Sheep Creek takes you through beautiful aspen groves and wide open fields that showcase the stunning mountains that surround you. There are some creek crossings along the trail and make sure to keep your eyes open for some beaver dams! This is a multi-use trail so be sure to share the path.',17,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(387,'Eagle','Colorado','Sylvan Lake State Park','2-3616','To Sylvan Lake, Cabins &amp; Campsites: Take I-70 to Eagle (Exit 147). Turn south and follow signs through town. Turn south on Brush Creek Road and travel 10 miles to the Visitor Center. Continue on Brush Creek Road until the road forks and becomes dirt. To reach the lake, at the fork, stay right and travel 5 miles to the campgrounds and cabins. To Brush Creek Yurts: Follow above directions until fork in road. Take left fork and travel 4 1/2 miles. The yurts are on left at the top of the switchbacks. The yurts are 9 1/2 miles from the lake.',39.481518,-106.734636,'Sylvan provides serenity in an alpine park perfect for daydreaming.  Non-motorized boating and non-electrical camping offer the opportunity for quiet recreation at this gateway to the White River National Forest and the Holy Cross Wilderness. The 1.5 mile Lake Trail is open. New sections of the West Brush Creek Trail have been completed. Hike 1 mile downstream of the campground to check out Antones Creek and Borah Gulch. Or check out over 1.5 miles of new trail heading upstream from the Meadows Day Use Area. Popular trails on the surrounding White River National Forest - Sneve Gulch, McKenzie Gulch, Nolan Lake, Lake Charles and Ironedge are all good options.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(388,'Silver Plume','Colorado','Argentine Pass','2-1488','Take I70 west of Denver to Silver Plume exit turn left go under overpass turn right on dirt service road and park.',39.69423,-105.7325,' Argentine Pass\' 21 miles lead over scenic singletrack, 4WD roads, a high alpine pass, and offer incredible mountain vistas. Along the hike you\'ll come upon the town of Waldorf, a ghost town now, which will take you back in time.  This is a multi-use trail so please practice caution.',21,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(389,'Estes Park','Colorado','Lily Lake','2-3109','Up the mountain south of Estes Park. A part of Rocky Mountain National Park',40.306814,-105.53763,' Lily Lake Trail is a wide, easy graveled trail that circles Lily Lake. It is only 1 mile long and is perfect for strollers, wheelchairs, and people who aren\'t in the mood for a strenuous hike. If you want something a little more adventurous, add the Lily Ridge trail in, which branches off of the Lily Lake trail, climbs up along the ridge, and then drops back down to the lake. The Lily Mountain trail also starts nearby, for a true mountain hike.',1,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/06/480790_10150979437963447_1994905110_-1.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(390,'Pagosa Springs','Colorado','Brockover Mesa - Outer Loop','2-1725','Four mile west of Pagosa Springs, turn north off highway 160 onto North Pagosa Blvd. Drive 3.7 miles. Look to your left opposite Mockingbird Place to see the forest entry gate #5.',37.2906,-107.10554,' Pass by ponds, forests, meadows, cattle fields, and creeks on the beautiful Brockover Mesa--Outer Loop Trail. The trail shifts between singletrack and logging roads, and provides stunning views in multiple spots. It\'s a great day hike to just enjoy the outdoors. This is a multi-use trail so please practice trail etiquette.',16,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(391,'Dinosaur','Colorado','Dinosaur National Monument','2-2919','Located on the Colorado and Utah border, Dinosaur National Monument is within a one day drive from several major cities and other national park areas.Source: National Park Service',40.437355,-109.303446,' Hiking in Dinosaur is an excellent way to appreciate the park\'s scenery and rugged landscape. The most popular trails begin near the visitor centers and the two paved tour roads. Other trails begin at more remote locations. There are 4 trails total, on the Colorado side of the park, with the trails ranging from 1/4 mile with wheel chair accessibility to 5 miles of rugged hiking.',0,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2012/04/Dinosaur-NM-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(392,'Antonito','Colorado','Continental Divide Trail: Colorado','2-3197','Colorado',36.993808,-106.457152,' The Continental Divide Trail is 3,100 miles long, stretching from Mexico to Canada and roughly following the continental divide. It is a part of the Triple Crown of long distance hiking trails in the US, along with the Pacific Crest Trail and Appalachian Trail. It is still under construction, so sections of it are constantly changing. The information posted here on Tripleblaze is the most up-to-date available, but these trail descriptions and GPS locations may become obsolete at some point in the future. If you notice any obsolete information, always feel free to post a review with the new info!  Whenever possible, the Google Maps location given for each section of trail will be for the most southern point. All sections are numbered in a south-to-north fashion.  The Colorado section runs for approximately 650 miles from the New Mexico border to the Wyoming border, traveling the high-altitude mountains through the wilds of the Colorado Rocky Mountains.  To follow the trail to the south, click on over to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.tripleblaze.com/3/3196/New-Mexico/Continental-Divide-Trail--New-Mexico.html&quot;&gt;New Mexico section&lt;/a&gt;. To follow the trail to the North, click on over to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.tripleblaze.com/3/3203/Wyoming/Continental-Divide-Trail--Wyoming.html&quot;&gt;Wyoming section&lt;/a&gt;.',734,'http://www.tripleblaze.com/./ra-content/images/uploads/2013/10/2013-10-09-10-02-25_1024x768-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(393,'Kremmling','Colorado','CDT CO41: Rabbit Ears Pass to Buffalo Pass','2-3298','CO',40.401369,-106.618313,' The CDT runs 15.3 miles from Rabbit Ears Pass near US Hwy 40 to Buffalo Pass. Along the way, the trail passes Dumont Lake and several other high-alpine lakes. The Mountain View trail spurs off of this trail, and it offers some gorgeous views of the surrounding mountains and down into the valley with Steamboat Springs below. Much of this section of the CDT trail runs through gorgeous high-alpine meadows, which are just full of beautiful wild flowers!',15,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/08/2013-08-09-08-58-13_1024x768-0-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(394,'Naturita','Colorado','Paradox Trail','2-1828','Many places to jump on the trail in the towns of Naturita, Bedrock, and Paradox. Access also available at Buckeye Reservoir near the Utah border.',38.42513,-108.96777,' The Paradox Trail links the Tabeguache Trail on the Uncompahgre Plateau with the Kokopelli Trail in the La Sal Mountains of Utah.  The 100-mile trail traverses a wide variety of terrain, elevation, and eco-zones, following existing jeep and county roads for most of its length. The adventurous nature of the Paradox Trail requires users to be cautious, personally responsible, self-sufficient, and have a working knowledge of backcountry survival.',105,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(395,'Hayden','Colorado','Yampa River State Park','2-3609','Yampa River State Park offers several public access sites along a 134-mile stretch of the Yampa River between Hayden and the Dinosaur National Monument near the Utah border. The central park office is located on Highway 40 between the cities of Craig and Hayden. See the Yampa River State Park Brochure and Map for locations of all public access sites.',40.49215,-107.313465,'Yampa River State Park, located in the beautiful Yampa valley west of Steamboat Springs, is actually three &quot;parks&quot; in one. At the Headquarters Campground, walkers can enjoy a mile of nature trail to work the kinks out from the long day\'s drive. The primary hiking opportunity is at many of the river access sites along the river. Hiking in the area is primarily on BLM lands and offers a diverse experience for all levels and interests. With the high-desert environment, your hikes can offer some of the most scenic views found anywhere. Areas like Duffy Mt., Juniper Canyon and Cross Mountain have some excellent hiking territory.',1,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(396,'Creede','Colorado','CDT CO11: Carson Saddle Trailhead to Spring Creek Pass Trailhead','2-3234','CO',37.856103,-107.367836,' The CDT runs with the Colorado Trail for 17.1 miles from the Carson Saddle Trailhead to the Spring Creek Pass Trailhead at Hwy 149. Along the way, the trail passes the highpoint of the Colorado Trail, Pt. 71 Mountain, and Jarosa Mesa.',17,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(397,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Palmer Park','2-270','From Academy Blvd. (heading south) turn right on Maizeland Rd.  An entrance to the park is on the right just past the ballfields also on the right.  Palmer Park is almost right in the middle of town (north of the airport, south of Chapel Hills Mall).',38.8768,-104.77788,' Great hiking trails for all skill levels. The park topography consists of a mesa with finger-like extensions dotted with pine and scrub. Great views of the city and miles of trails!',12,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/270-1223928035.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(398,'Colorado Springs','Colorado','Seven Bridges Trail','2-52','Head up Gold Camp road to the High-Drive Rd./Captain Jack\'s trailhead.  Follow Gold Camp {closed to vehicles} till you get to Cheyenne Creek.  On the right side of the creek is the trail which leads up either to the Buckhorn cut-off trail on the left, or Seven Bridges on the right.  ',38.79117,-104.90647,' The trailhead is directly off the closed portion of Gold Camp Rd. (on the west side). Park at the intersection of Gold Camp Rd, High Dr. and Cheyenne CaÃ±on Rd. Hike past the gate, which is in the northwest corner of the parking area, and follow the closed portion of Gold Camp Rd .7 miles to the trailhead. The trail is unmarked, so you will need to watch for the creek that goes under the road, and the trailhead will be on your right. This is a moderate hike, which criss-crosses Cheyenne Creek over a series of seven bridges.',5,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2009/02/52-1223932414.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(399,'Crested Butte','Colorado','Lower Loop','2-2255','You can connect to this trail directly from Crested Butte Via Butte Avenue and Peanut Lake Road. On the other end, you can park just off the bottom of the Gunsight Pass Road which splits off of the Slate River Road.',38.86824,-106.98873,' This is an easy hiking trail that is accessible right from the residential streets of Crested Butte. These trails are relatively flat, but the lack of trees allows them to provide incredible views of the surrounding mountain peaks and the nearby Slate River. This is very popular with locals and tourists alike.',10,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2011/09/upper-lower-2-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(400,'Eldorado Springs','Colorado','Doudy Draw Trail','2-7832','From Boulder, take CO-93 S to Hwy 170 (Eldorado Springs exit).  Turn right and drive about 1.8 miles.  The trailhead will be on your right.',39.9384,-105.25669,' Doudy Draw Trail is a 4 mile hiking trail in Eldorado Springs, Colorado.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(401,'Evergreen','Colorado','Meadow View','2-8766','Elk Meadow trail head',0,0,' 3 mile hiking trail located near Evergreen, Colorado',3,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(402,'Evergreen','Colorado','3 Sisters / Alderfer','2-314','From I-70, take CO 74/Evergreen Pkwy to downtown Evergreen.  Turn right onto County Rd. 73 and go about a mile to Buffalo Park Rd.  Follow the signs to the parking area on the right.',39.62324,-105.34659,' Near the heart of Evergreen, Alderfer/Three Sisters Park abounds with stunning vistas, landmark rock formations, beautiful old stands of ponderosa pine and the most trails per acre of any foothills park-nearly 15 miles on 770 acres. Open meadows, forests, and great views are all around.',15,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/04/1497665_10202806619986227_128395484_n.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(403,'Mosca','Colorado','San Luis State Park','2-3626','Take Highway 160 west from Walsenburg for 60 miles just past the town of Blanca. Go north on Highway 150 for 13.5 miles. Turn left on Six Mile Lane and drive straight for 8 miles and then drive north 1/8 mile to park entrance.',37.663131,-105.73521,'In the shadow of the Great Sand Dunes National Park is peaceful San Luis State Park and Wildlife Area. Waterfowl, shorebirds, songbirds and raptors fill the sky over this unique desert ecosystem, making San Luis an outstanding watchable wildlife area most of the year. Four miles of wide, level gravel trails in the wildlife area provide a pleasant, safe hiking or mountain biking experience among the low dunes and wetlands. The wildlife area is closed from Feb. 15 until July 15 annually.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(404,'Estes Park','Colorado','Estes Cone','2-8545','1: N40 16.330	 W105 33.409 - 0.0 miles : Longs Peak Trailhead2: N40 16.495	 W105 33.852 - .45 miles : Estes Cone Trail spli3: N40 17.716	 W105 34.04 - 3.05 miles : Estes Cone',0,0,' Estes Cone is located 3.05 miles from the Longs Peak Trailhead on the east side of Rocky Mountain National Park. A short but steep climb up this conical formation rewards hikers with panoramic views of Longs Peak, the Continental Divide, and Estes Park area:   The trail climbs steadily in a mixed pine forest to the Chasm Lake - Estes Cone Trail split and turns sharply north (.45 miles : 9,670\'). It continues on a moderate grade that levels over a stream (1.3 miles) to the Eugenia Mine site - a settler era gold mine which in the words of the Park &quot;produced more dreams than gold&quot;.   The trail dips past the mine to Moore Park Backcountry Campsite (1.6 miles : 9,732\') and begins a steep push to the summit, covering almost 1,000\' in the final .7 miles.   Cairns help identify the trail, but can be difficult to spot, especially with lingering snow. A 20 yard scramble up steep scree leads to the bare-rock summit of Estes Cone (3.05 miles : 11,002\').',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2014/03/DSC_0049-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(405,'Evergreen','Colorado','Maxwell Falls','2-934','From Evergreen drive south on  Hwy 73 right at Brook Forest Road for three miles. ',39.58244,-105.36083,' One of the easiest trails in the district, Maxwell Falls is a very enjoyable hike. It follows Maxwell Creek, and the waterfalls are at their best in the spring when the snow runoff is plentiful. Jefferson County law requires dogs be on a leash at all times while on this trail.',6,'http://images.tripleblaze.com/2013/09/GOPR7598-(2)-0.jpg','Hiking',NULL),(406,'Trinidad','Colorado','Trinidad Lake State Park','2-3624','Heading north on I-25, take Exit 13B to West Main Street. At the first four-way stop, turn left onto Nevada. At the next four-way stop by the Welcome Center, turn left and continue west on Highway 12 for 3.5 miles. Heading south on I-25, take exit 13B and at the stop sign, turn left under the freeway towards town. At the four-way stop next to the Sonic, go left on Nevada and make a left at the next four-way stop. Take Hwy 12 west for 3.5 miles.',37.147475,-104.571962,'Trinidad Lake is a wonderful place to escape the crowds and establish a basecamp from which to explore the great outdoors. There\'s so much to see on Trinidad\'s trails! Ten miles of trails reward eager explorers wanting to learn, exercise or conduct nature study. Several trails are ADA-accessible. Sights range from open vistas, to grasslands, forests, cliffs and ponds. Cold-weather enthusiasts can enjoy hiking all winter.',9,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(407,'Salida','Colorado','CDT CO20: Hancock to Garden Basin','2-3245','CO',38.638995,-106.361647,' The 20th section of the Continental Divide Trail in Colorado runs for 14.2 miles from the Hancock Trailhead to the Garden Basin Trailhead. Along the way, the trail passes Tincup Pass, Tincup Peak, Mirror Lake, Mirror Lake Campground, Mount Poor, Fitzpatrick Peak, and Emma Burr Mountain.',14,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(408,'Durango','Colorado','Hermosa Creek Trail','2-796','From Durango Drive north on Hwy 550 towards Purgatory ski resort. Drive past the resort and make the first left, road FS 578 or San Juan CR 38. Follow that road up and make a right at the T on top. Take the next right and follow the dirt road down the valley. Follow the signs for Sig Creek Campground and Hermosa Creek Trailhead. The campground and parking lot are on the South side of the road and require a short river crossing, usually it\'s shallow, but it\'s a good idea to check.',37.6316,-107.91565,' Hike among high ridges and deep canyons along this remote trail. The trail is wide, well-maintained, and very easy to hike, and it winds through beautiful forests, open meadows with views of the La Platas, and fields of wildflowers.  The main trail is about 16 miles, but there are plenty of side trails to explore. Either day hike or spend a couple days backpacking and exploring this area!',19,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(409,'Gleneagle','Colorado','Fox Run Regional Park','2-93','Located at the Northern edge of Colorado Springs.  Take the Baptist Road exit, East from I-25.  Drive north a couple miles to the T-intersection and take a right on Roller Coaster road.   There will be a parking area a couple hundred yards down the road, to the right.',39.06803,-104.78532,' Fox Run Park is located in the Black Forest approximately three miles east of Interstate 25. The 417-acre park features spectacular views of Pikes Peak, four miles of trails, multi-use fields, two playgrounds, two ponds, and five picnic pavilions. There are 2 looped trails that weave throughout the ponderosa forests. This is a multi-use trail so please share the path with mountain bikers.',4,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(410,'Littleton','Colorado','Waterton Canyon','2-273','From Denver, take 470 west towards littleton.  Exit at Wadsworth Blvd (CO 121).  Go about 4 miles and follow the signs to the park.  Park in the lot on the left.  The trail starts on the opposite side of the road.',39.49138,-105.09323,' Strontia Springs Dam is six and one-half miles upstream of the mouth of Waterton Canyon on the South Platte River. Water is diverted from the reservoir into a 3.4 mile-long tunnel under the mountains to the Foothills Water Treatment Plant. Completed in 1983, this dam towers 243 feet above the South Platte streambed, forming a 1.7 mile-long lake with 98 surface acres.',6,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(411,'Grand Junction','Colorado','Eagle','2-1945','From HWY 50 in Grand Jct, take HWY 340 across the Colorado River.  Take a left on Monument Road and after 2 miles the parking area will be on the left.',0,0,' Hike along rocky ledges on this 2 mile out-and-back hike. Enjoy stunning views of the surrounding desert cliffs and mesas. The entire hike is pretty rocky, so watch your step. This is a multi-use trail, so please practice trail etiquette.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(412,'Fruita','Colorado','Zion Curtain','2-2150','From Fruita traveling west on the I-70 exit at the Rabbit Valley 2 exit. Go right and follow the dirt road north up and over the hill then west to parking area.  Begin on this 2 track going west to the I-70 underpass approx. 3 miles to I-70 underpass. Proceed south under the Interstate and about a half mile or so take the first singletrack on your left. ',39.19318,-109.02869,' Zion Curtain is a 12 mile loop trail near Fruita, CO. This dusty trail will give you a good workout as you climb up to the top of the rim. From there you\'ll hike along the top for most of the time and you\'ll get to take in the beautiful desert scenery.  This is a multi-use trail, so please share the path.',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(413,'Georgetown','Colorado','Saxon Mountain','2-2420','Take I-70 west of Denver to Georgetown exit #228 Drive under the overpases and park at the Visitors Center on the right',39.7149,-105.69748,' Saxon Mountain trail is a rocky and steep path that climbs 2500ft up to the top of Saxon Mountain where you\'ll hit 11,050ft in elevation. From the top you\'ll get an amazing view of Mt. Evans and the Divide.  This is a multi-use trail so please share the path!',12,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(414,'Walden','Colorado','State Forest State Park','2-3606','I-70 to the Empire exit, Highway 40, over Berthoud Pass through Winter Park and Granby. 2 miles west of Granby take Highway 125 45 miles to the east side of Rand. Take County Road 27 14 miles to Highway 14, go right to the park 3 miles. Or I-25 to Cheyenne, WY. Take I-80 to Laramie 45 miles. Take Highway 230 to Walden 60 miles then take Highway 14 east to the park 25 miles. Or if Highway 287 is open take it to Laramie and out of Laramie take Highway 230 to Walden 60 miles and then Highway 14 east 25 miles to the park.',39.189762,-105.605891,'The ultimate in rugged Colorado, State Forest State Park offers visitors 71,000 acres of forest, jagged peaks, alpine lakes, wildlife and miles of trails.  The park stretches along the west side of the Medicine Bow Mountains and into the north end of the Never Summer Range. The ultimate in rugged Colorado, State Forest State Park offers visitors 71,000 acres of forest, jagged peaks, alpine lakes, wildlife and miles of trails. The park stretches along the west side of the Medicine Bow Mountains and into the north end of the Never Summer Range.   There are plenty of trails that wind through this beautiful park, ranging from .8 miles to 8 miles (one way). There\'s something for everyone, from the families with small children to the avid backcountry hiker.',58,NULL,'Hiking',NULL),(415,'Collbran','Colorado','Vega State Park','2-3614','Take exit 49 (if coming from Grand Junction) off I-70 to HWY 65, go approximately 18 miles on Hwy 65 and turn left onto HWY 330. Go 12 miles to the town of Collbran. Stay on 330 East past Collbran for about 12 miles to Mesa County Rd. 64 6/10ths Rd. and turn right at the &quot;Vega State Park&quot; sign. Go 5 miles to the Park Entrance Station, and go another half mile and turn right across Vega Dam to the Park Visitor Center. If coming from Denver, take Exit 62 off of I-70 turn left and follow 45 1/2 Road approximately 12 miles to Hwy 65 and turn left, proceed 1/4 mile and turn left onto Hwy 330 and follow this road as directed above to the park.',39.236472,-107.831244,'At an elevation of 8,000 feet, Vega State Park\'s high-mountain lake sits in a beautiful montane meadow on the western edge of Grand Mesa National Forest in Western Colorado. Hikers can enjoy easy wildflower walks between Oak Point and Island campgrounds or along the South Road and near the Meadows Group Shelter Area. For a more strenuous two-mile natural surface trail through aspen forest and mountain shrub vegetation begin at the OHV parking lot. This trail doubles as a snowshoe trail in winter months.',2,NULL,'Hiking',NULL);
